{"title_page": "Rheum ribes", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Syrian rhubarb\n|image = Rheum ribes - I\u015fg\u0131n 06.jpg\n|image_caption = \n|genus = Rheum\n|species = ribes\n|authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]<ref name=POWO_696789-1/>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=POWO_696789-1/>\n|synonyms =\n  {{Species list\n  |Rhabarbarum ribes|(L.) Moench\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''''Rheum ribes''''', the '''Syrian rhubarb''' or '''currant-fruited rhubarb''',<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010313034206/http://newcrops.uq.edu.au/listing/rheumribes.htm Australian New Crops]</ref> or '''warty-leaved rhubarb''',<ref>[http://apps.rhs.org.uk/horticulturaldatabase/hortdatabase.asp?ID=160860 RHS Horticultural Database]</ref> is an [[Edible plant stems|edible]] wild rhubarb species in the genus ''[[Rheum (plant)|Rheum]]''. It grows between 1000 and 4000 m on [[dunite]] rocks, among stones and slopes, and is now distributed in the [[temperate]] and [[subtropical]] regions of the world, chiefly in [[Western Asia]] ([[Turkey]], [[Syria]], [[Lebanon]], [[Iraq]], [[Iran]], [[Azerbaijan]], [[Armenia]]) to [[Afghanistan]] and [[Pakistan]].{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} The Syrian rhubarb is a partially commercial vegetable collected from the nature in Eastern and Southern [[Anatolia]], Northern Iraq and partly Northwestern Iran in early spring. ''Rheum ribes'' is considered as a valuable medicinal species in [[herbal medicine]].\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Rivach=Rivas.JPG|thumb|''Rheum ribes'' growing in [[Iran]].]]\nThe Syrian rhubarb is a dichotomously branched [[Perennial plant|perennial]] stout herb, up to 1&nbsp;m tall. It has thick perennial [[rhizome]]s, large annual bean-shaped reddish-green leaves with [[Petiole (botany)|stalks]], edible [[Pedicel (botany)|flower stalks]], small yellowish flowers arranged in [[panicle]]s, three-sided ovate-oblong [[achene]]s and broad red-winged dull brown fruit.<ref>\u00d6nder T\u00fcrkmen, Mustafa \u00c7irka and Suat \u015eensoy (2005), [http://www.docsdrive.com/pdfs/ansinet/pjbs/2005/763-765.pdf Initial Evaluation of a New Edible Wild Rhubarb Species (Rheum ribes L.) with a Modified Weighted Scaling Index Method], Pakistan Journal of Biological Sciences 8 (5): 763-765, 2005</ref> The flowering stem ([[Peduncle (botany)|peduncle]]) is solid, warty, leafy below, leafless above.<ref name=VanHerb>[http://www.vanherbaryum.yyu.edu.tr/flora/famgenustur/polgo/rheum/index.htm Van Herbaryumu]</ref>\n\n=== Similar species ===\nIt is very similar to the species ''[[Rheum palaestinum]]'', being distinguished by having five central leaf veins as opposed to three, and being taller.<ref name=IsRedList2>{{cite web |url=https://redlist.parks.org.il/taxa/Rheum%20palaestinum/ |title=Endangered Plants of Israel Rheum palaestinum |last=Shmida |first=Avi |last2=Pollak |first2=Gadi |last3=Fragman-Sapir |first3=Ori |date=2011 |website= |publisher=Israel Nature and Parks Authority |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Agnia Losina-Losinskaja]] considered it very similar in leaves and flowers to [[Rheum maximowiczii|''R. maximowiczii'']] from further north in [[Central Asia]], but to be distinguished from it by its much rougher stem, much longer leaf [[Petiole (botany)|petioles]] and broader [[inflorescence]]. ''R. maximowiczii'' furthermore has three veins per leaf.<ref name=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435\u0420\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0438>{{cite journal |last=\u041b\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0430-\u041b\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f |first=\u0410\u0433\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430 |author-link=Agnia Losina-Losinskaja |date=1932 |title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0420\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u044d\u0438\u0438 |url=http://ashipunov.info/shipunov/school/sch-ru.htm |language=Russian |journal=\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0411\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0410\u041d \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420 |volume=30 |issue=1-2 |pages=382\u2013383 |access-date=31 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Karyotypy ===\n''R. ribes'' has a [[chromosome]] count of 2''n''=44.<ref name=karyotypes>{{cite journal |last=Ruirui |first=Liu |last2=Wang |first2=Ailan |last3=Tian |first3=Xinmin |last4=Wang |first4=Dongshi |last5=Liu |first5=Jianquan |date=2010 |title=Uniformity of karyotypes in Rheum (Polygonaceae), a species-rich genus in the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau and adjacent regions |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261646487 |journal=Caryologia Firenze |volume=63 |issue=1 |pages=82\u201390 |doi=10.1080/00087114.2010.10589711 |access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n''Rheum ribes'' was first formally described in 1753 by [[Carl Linnaeus]].<ref name=\"IPNI_696789-1\">{{cite web |title=Plant Name Details for ''Rheum ribes''&#32;L. |work=[[International Plant Names Index|The International Plant Names Index]] |url=http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=696789-1 |accessdate=2019-03-11 }}</ref> It was one of three species of ''Rheum'' described in ''[[Species Plantarum]]'' volume 1. Linnaeus referred to five earlier authors who had described the plant: [[Johann Jacob Dillenius]], [[Jacob Breyne]] (who calls it a ''Lapathum'', known as ''Ribes arabicum''), [[Richard Pococke]]<ref name=Linn53/> (who published in 1745 a description of his travels in the Near East and who brought seeds to England from Lebanon<ref name=Miller/>), [[Leonhard Rauwolf]] and [[Gaspard Bauhin]].<ref name=Linn53/>\n\nIn 1936 Losina-Losinskaja, in [[Vladimir Leontyevich Komarov|Komarov's]] ''Flora SSSR'', classifies this species in [[Section (botany)|section]] '''Ribesiformia''', in which she also places ''R. maximowiczii'', [[Rheum fedtschenkoi|''R. fedtschenkoi'']], [[Rheum cordatum|''R. cordatum'']], [[Rheum hissaricum|''R. hissaricum'']] and [[Rheum macrocarpum|''R. macrocarpum'']] (and ''R. lobatum'' and ''R. plicatum'', which are both now seen as synonyms of ''R. macrocarpum'').<ref name=SSSR>{{cite book |last=\u041b\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0430-\u041b\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f |first=\u0410\u0433\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430 |author-link=Agnia Losina-Losinskaja |date=1936 |chapter=''Rheum'' |chapter-url= |editor1-last=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0301\u0432 |editor1-first=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041b\u0435\u043e\u0301\u043d\u0442\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 |editor1-link=Vladimir Leontyevich Komarov  |title=Flora SSSR, Vol. 5 |url= |language=Russian |location=Moscow |publisher=\u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420 |pages=494\u2013500}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThis plant is first mentioned in Europe in the Arabic work, in English called the ''Book of Simple Medicaments'', by [[Serapion the Younger]], the Latin translation of which circulated throughout Europe in the late 13th to 15th century. Serapion says the plant is used to make the medicine thenceforth known in Europe as ''rob ribes''.<ref name=Miller>{{cite book |last=Miller |first=Phillip |date=1807 |title=The Gardener and Botanist's Dictionary, Vol. II |url=http://bibdigital.rjb.csic.es/ing/Libro.php?Libro=6238 |edition=9 |location=London |publisher=F.C. and J. Rivington |page= |author-link=Phillip Miller}}</ref> In Europe, herbalists initially thought he was describing a currant, which they then used to make local, lesser ''ribes''.\n\nOne of the first European works to write about this plant unambiguously was the ''Viertes Kreutterbuech - darein vil schoene und frembde Kreutter'' of 1576 by Leonhard Rauwolf, the first modern European botanist to travel through the [[Levant]] and [[Mesopotamia]]. The ''Viertes Kreutterbuech'' is one of the first ''[[herbarium|herbaria]]'' \u2013 the first with plants collected outside of Europe \u2013 and contains Rauwolf's notes on the pressed plants displayed. Rauwolf calls the plant ''Ribes arabum'' and saw it growing in [[Lebanon]] and [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]. He says the ''rob ribes'' of Serapion is made from the young flowering stalk.<ref name=Miller/><ref name=Linn53/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://kerkuil.leidenuniv.nl/digitale-tentoonstellingen-voor-2007/goedgezien/objectbeschrijvingen/object099.html |title=99. De Planten Gedroogd |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |language=Dutch |publisher=Universiteitsbibliotheek Leiden |access-date=11 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1623 ''Pinax Theatri Botanici'', Gaspard Bauhin attempts to sort all the plant names hitherto published. In this work he organises all ''[[Ribes|Grossularia]]'' and ''[[Ribes]]'' species known at the time into 13 species, the twelfth of which is ''Rheum ribes'', which Bauhin calls ''Ribes arabicum''. Bauhin bases this on the work of Rauwolf, but also [[Carolus Clusius|Clusius]] (who calls it ''Ribes legitima arabum''), [[Joachim Camerarius the Younger|Camerarius]] (''Ribes serapionis''), [[Rembert Dodoens]] (''Ribes serapionis foliis oxylapathi'') and [[Pierre Belon]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bauhin |first=Gaspard |date=1671 |title=Caspari Bauhini Pinax Theatri botanici, sive Index in Theophrasti, Dioscoridis, Plinii et botanicorum qui \u00e0 seculo scripserunt opera |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/30615#page/478/mode/1up |language=Latin |edition=2 |location=Basel |publisher=Impensis Joannis Regis |page=336 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.7092 |author-link=Gaspard Bauhin}}</ref>\n\nIn 1732, Johann Jacob Dillenius published his ''Hortus Elthamensis'' \u2013 a book of rare plants grown in London \u2013 which describes this plant. He calls it a type of ''Lapathum'' (now ''[[Rumex]]''), but mentions that it is known as ''Ribes arabicum''.<ref name=Linn53/> Dillenius obtained seeds in 1726 from [[William Sherard]], who brought them from Lebanon in 1724. He mentions that it was only grown elsewhere in Europe in [[Hortus Botanicus Leiden|Leyden]], from an older source.<ref name=Miller/>\n\nThe specific epithet ''ribes'' is thus derived via Serapion from the Arabic word ''r\u012bb\u0101s'' (\u0631\u064a\u0628\u0627\u0633), referring to the Syrian rhubarb.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/florahibernicaco00mackrich/page/108 <!-- quote=\"Rheum ribes\". --> Flora Hibernica (1836)] (Name, ''Ribes'', a word applied by the Arabic Physicians to a species of ''Rhubarb'', ''Rheum Ribes''.)</ref> The New Latin word ''ribes'' (currant) was corrupted from the Arabic word ''r\u012bb\u0101s'' by Europeans in the Renaissance, possibly due confusion with the original description of the bunches of berries on its panicle of fruit, with currants, a new crop at the time. ''R.&nbsp;ribes'', unlike many other species of rhubarb, has a fleshy, succulent [[epicarp]] around its seeds.<ref name=Miller/>\n\nThe generic name ''Rheum'' is derived from the Greek ''rheon'', mentioned by [[Dioscorides]] as a name for medicinal rhubarb; the word ''rheon'' is itself thought to be derived from the (old) Persian ''rewend'', which possibly referred to this species.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Why is an Apple a Pomme? A Journey with Words|last=Dunstone|first=Denis|publisher=Lulu Publishing Services|year=2014|isbn=1483418596|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution ==\nIt is native to Israel (only in the occupied [[Golan Heights]]),<ref name=IsRedList2/><ref name=FlwrsIsrael>[http://www.wildflowers.co.il/english/plant.asp?ID=2433 Wild Flowers of Israel]</ref><ref name=EuroMed>{{cite web |url=http://ww2.bgbm.org/EuroPlusMed/PTaxonDetailOccurrence.asp?NameId=55733&PTRefFk=7300000 |title=Polygonaceae, The Euro+Med Plantbase Project |last=Uotila |first=P. |date=2017 |website=Euro-Mediterranean Plant Base |publisher=Botanic Garden and Botanical Museum Berlin-Dahlem |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Jordan,<ref name=EuroMed/> Lebanon,<ref name=EuroMed/><ref name=Musselman>{{cite book |last=Musselman |first=Lytton John |date=2011 |title=Checklist of the plants of Lebanon and Syria |url=http://ww2.odu.edu/~lmusselm/plant/lebsyria/Checklist%20of%20Lebanon%20Plants.pdf |location=Norfolk, VA |publisher=Old Dominion University |page=105}}</ref> Syria,<ref name=EuroMed/><ref name=Musselman/> Azerbaijan (including [[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic|Nakhichevan]]),<ref name=EuroMed/><ref name=plantarium>{{cite web |url=http://www.plantarium.ru/page/view/item/31708.html |title=\u0420\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 - Rheum ribes - \u041e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430 - \u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0443\u043c |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |language=Russian |website=Plantarium |publisher= |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Armenia (as of 2011),<ref name=plantarium/> Iraq,<ref name=FlPaki>{{cite book |last=Qaiser |first=M. |date=2001 |editor1-last=Nasir |editor1-first=E. |editor2-last=Ali |editor2-first=S. I. |title=Flora of Pakistan, Vol. 205 Polygonaceae |url=http://efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=5&taxon_id=242100143  |location=Karachi |publisher=Missouri Botanical Garden Press and the University of Karachi |page= |isbn=}}</ref> Turkey,<ref name=EuroMed/><ref name=FlPaki/> Iran,<ref name=FlPaki/> Pakistan,<ref name=FlPaki/> Afghanistan<ref name=FlPaki/> and Russia.<ref name=FlPaki/>\n\n== Ecology ==\n[[File:Rheum ribes - I\u015fg\u0131n 08.jpg|thumb|''Rheum ribes'' in early May ''in situ'' at Karasakal Mt., [[Tufanbeyli]], near [[Adana]], [[Turkey]].]]\n\n=== Habitat ===\nIt is a floristic element of the Irano-Turanian [[Phytochorion|Region]] or Iran-Turan Plant Geography Region.<ref name=VanHerb/>\n\nIt is found in eastern Turkey on dry mountain slopes at 1600-2600m elevation in association with the plants ''[[Prangos ferulacea]]'' and ''[[Cousinia sivasica]]'' with which it forms the dominant flora such ecosystems.<ref name=beetles>{{cite journal |last=Korotyaev |first=Boris A. |last2=G\u00fcltekin |first2=Levent |last3=Volkovitsh |first3=Mark G. |last4=Dorofeyev |first4=Vladimir I. |last5=Konstantinov |first5=Alexander S. |date=January 2016 |title=Bioindicator beetles and plants in desertified and eroded lands in Turkey |url=https://www.mapress.com/j/jib/article/download/2016.4.1/14190 |journal=Journal of Insect Biodiversity |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=28, 29, 34, 42 |doi=10.12976/jib/2016.4.1  |access-date=16 March 2019|doi-access=free }}</ref> In Israel it is found on rocky slopes and cliffs in the transition zone of montane forests of ''[[Quercus boissieri]]''.<ref name=IsRedList2/>\n\n=== Insects ===\n''Rheum ribes'' is the main food plant of a tiny [[Callophrys|hairstreak]] butterfly, ''[[Callophrys mystaphia]]'', of which the Turkish name is ''\u0131\u015fg\u0131nz\u00fcmr\u00fct\u00fc'', the 'rhubarb emerald', in [[Adiyaman Province|Adiyaman]], [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Hakk\u00e2ri]], [[I\u011fd\u0131r Province|I\u011fd\u0131r]], [[Kahramanmara\u015f Province|Kahramanmara\u015f]], [[Kars Province|Kars]], [[Siirt Province|Siirt]] and [[Van Province|Van]] provinces in southeastern and eastern [[Turkey]].<ref>[http://www.trakel.org/kelebekler/?fsx=2fsdl17@d&tur=Minik%20Z%C3%BCmr%C3%BCt TRAKEL (T\u00fcrkiye'nin Anonim Kelebekleri)]</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/CentreForEntomologicalStudiesAnkaraCesaNewsNr.9 Van G\u00f6l\u00fc Havzas\u0131nda Kelebek \u00c7e\u015fitlili\u011fi (Diversity of the butterflies in Van Lake Basin East Turkey)] by Muhabbet Kemal, 2008</ref><ref name=ButtIran>{{cite journal |last=Krupitsky |first=Anatoly |last2=Kolesnichenko |first2=Kirill |date=March 2013 |title=A new species of the Callophrys mystaphia Miller, 1913\u2014group from Iran (Lepidoptera: Lycaenidae: Eumaeini) |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275746540 |journal=Zootaxa |volume=3619 |issue=4 |pages=460\u2013461 |doi=10.11646/zootaxa.3619.4.4 |access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref> This butterfly had not been seen since its description in 1913 (it turned out that the butterflies identified under this name in the former Soviet territories were in fact a different species), but in 2007\u20132008 it was rediscovered and its host plant was found. This animal has a distribution closely localised to ''Rheum'' populations, and has only been found in Turkey.<ref name=ButtIran/>\n\n''R. ribes'' leaves are the food plant of the moth ''[[Xylena exsoleta]]'' in [[Van Province]], Turkey.<ref>Muhabbet Kemal, Halil \u00d6zkol & Lokman Kayci (2008), [http://www23.us.archive.org/details/CentreForEntomologicalStudiesAnkaraMiscellaneousPapers139-140 ''Xylena'' Ochsenheimer in East Turkey with new provincial records and larval food-plants (''Noctuidae, Lepidoptera'')], in Miscellaneous Papers, Centre for Entomological Studies Ankara, no: 139-140, 20.03.2008</ref>\n\nBeetles associated with ''R. ribes'' in eastern Turkey are a ''[[Petrocladus]]'' sp. [[weevil]], the [[jewel beetle]] ''[[Capnodis marquardti]]'', and the [[leaf beetle]] ''[[Labidostomis brevipennis]]''. These are all specialised herbivores of the plant, and most appear endemic to Turkey as far as known. ''L. brevipennis'' lays its eggs on the leaves.<ref name=beetles/>\n\n== Cooking ==\n[[File:Rheum ribes.jpg|thumb|Immature inflorescences for sale at the historical market in [[Kad\u0131k\u00f6y]], [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]].]]\nThe edible part of the plant is the flowering stem, which is eaten raw or cooked (''ek\u015fili \u0131\u015fg\u0131n''<ref>[http://www.turkish-cuisine.org/english/article_details.php?p_id=12&PagingIndex=1&Pages=Articles Elaz\u0131\u011f Cuisine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503133041/http://www.turkish-cuisine.org/english/article_details.php?p_id=12&PagingIndex=1&Pages=Articles |date=2014-05-03 }}</ref> and ''\u0131\u015fk\u0131nl\u0131 yumurta'' [lit. 'eggs with wild rhubarb, Rheum ribes'] in [[El\u00e2z\u0131\u011f Province|El\u00e2z\u0131\u011f]], Turkey; ''khoresh rivas'' [\u062e\u0648\u0631\u0634 \u0631\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0633] or \"Persian rhubarb stew\"  in Iran) by the local people of [[Turkey]], [[Syria]], [[Iraq]], [[Iran]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"refSeval\">Seval And\u0131\u00e7, Yusuf Tun\u00e7t\u00fcrk, Elvan Ocak and Senol K\u00f6se (2009), [http://www.aensionline.com/rjabs/rjabs/2009/973-977.pdf Some Chemical Characteristics of Edible Wild Rhubarb Species (''Rheum Ribes'' L.)], Research Journal of Agriculture and Biological Sciences, 5(6): 973-977, 2009</ref> The leaves and [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]] are often eaten raw as [[salad]], sometimes sold in the local markets of [[Balochistan, Pakistan|Northern Balochistan]].<ref name=FlPaki/>\n\n== Traditional and current medicinal uses ==\n''Rheum ribes'' is the source of one of the most important crude [[drugs]] in West Asiatic regions. These plant vitamins A, B, C are seen in abundance. Syrian rhubarb root (''Rhizoma Rhei ribi'') is used traditionally to treat [[diabetes]], [[hemorrhoids]], [[peptic ulcer|ulcers]], and [[diarrhea]].<ref>Aladdin M. Naqishbandi, Knud Josefsen, Mikael Egebjerg Pedersen, Anna K. J\u00e4ger. [http://informahealthcare.com/doi/abs/10.1080/13880200902748478 Hypoglycemic activity of Iraqi Rheum ribes root extract]. Pharmaceutical Biology, May 2009, Vol. 47, No. 5 : Pages 380-383</ref> The plant is also used as a digestive and appetizer in [[Bitlis Province|Bitlis]], Turkey.<ref>Hanefi \u00d6zbek, Ebubekir Ceylan, Mehmet Kara, Fevzi \u00d6zg\u00f6k\u00e7e, Mehmet Koyuncu (2004), [http://biomedicum.ut.ee/sjlas/31_2_113-115.pdf Hypoglycemic effect of Rheum ribes roots in alloxan induced diabetic and normal mice] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503132550/http://biomedicum.ut.ee/sjlas/31_2_113-115.pdf |date=2014-05-03 }}. Scand. J. Lab. Anim. Sci. No. 2. 2004. Vol. 31</ref> Traditional [[herbal medicine]] stem and root dry plant for the treatment of [[anemia]], [[Anorexia (symptom)|anorexia]], [[weakness]], [[anxiety]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]] and [[diabetes]].<ref>Sayyah M, Boostani H, Pakseresht S, Malayeri A. Efficacy of hydroalcoholic extract of Rheum ribes L. in treatment of major depressive disorder. Journal of Medicinal Plant Research. 2009, 3(8):573-575</ref> Traditionally ''Rheum ribes'' has been used in Iran as [[sedative]] and mood enhancer.\n\nThe [[anthraquinones]] chrysophanol, [[parietin]] and [[emodin]], the [[flavonoids]] [[quercetin]], [[fisetin]], quercetin 3-0-rhamnoside, quercetin 3-0-galactoside and quercetin 3-0-rutinoside were isolated from the shoots of Syrian rhubarb.<ref name=\"refTosun\">Fatma Tosun & \u00c7i\u011fdem Aky\u00fcz-K\u0131z\u0131lay (2003), [http://dergiler.ankara.edu.tr/dergiler/24/1104/13097.pdf Anthraquinones and Flavonoids from Rheum ribes / Rheum ribes Bitkisinin Antrakinonlar\u0131 ve Flavonoitleri], Ankara Ecz. Fak. Derg. 32(1)31-35,2003</ref>\n\n== Conservation ==\nIn Israel it is an extremely rare plant found at two sites in the mountains of the [[Golan Heights]], but it is not protected by law.<ref name=IsRedList2/><ref name=IsRedList>{{cite web |url=https://redlist.parks.org.il/taxa/Rheum%20ribes/?highlight=%20Rheum%20ribes |title=Endangered Plants of Israel  \u05e8\u05d9\u05d1\u05e1 \u05d0\u05de\u05ea\u05d9 |last=Shmida |first=Avi |last2=Pollak |first2=Gadi |last3=Fragman-Sapir |first3=Ori |date=2011 |website= |publisher=Israel Nature and Parks Authority |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Names ==\n=== Antiquated English names ===\n'''rhubarb-currant''',<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KDRrAAAAMAAJ&q=%22rheum+ribes%22&dq=%22rheum+ribes%22&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=GPS0T-7iG-r_4QTa1KW5Dg&ved=0CF0Q6AEwCDiMAQ The medical formulary of al-Samarqand\u012b and the relation of early Arabic simples to those found in the indigenous medicine of the Near East and India], Naj\u012bb al-D\u012bn Mu\u1e25ammad ibn 'Al\u012b al-Samarqand\u012b, Martin Levey, Noury Al-Khaledy, Univ. of Pennsylvania Press, 1967</ref> '''warted-leaved rhubarb''',<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=nVwMAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=%22Rheum+ribes%22&source=bl&ots=tqV3PZ-PGl&sig=uInbq1RWZsI8dJ64MHG-zvOP0fQ&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=4MGuT8-GGaTO4QTW5_SfCQ&ved=0CHIQ6AEwBjg8#v=onepage&q&f=false Encyclop\u00e6dia Londinensis (1827)]</ref> '''rhubarb of [[Babilonia]]'''<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=r5jnQzwZjOYC&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=%22rheum+ribes%22+afghanistan&source=bl&ots=ksbim_BeJf&sig=rHw3vzDZSHcH_KrWkdFT5WlwUA0&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=Rza0T5WiDaHm4QTplpGKDg&ved=0CGMQ6AEwBTgK#v=onepage&q=%22rheum%20ribes%22%20afghanistan&f=false The Book of Duarte Barbosa by Mansel Longworth Dames, 1918-1921, London]</ref>\n\n=== Local names ===\n*[[Arabic]]: ''r\u012bb\u0101s'' <ref>[http://ddc.aub.edu.lb/projects/saab/avicenna/appendix_1.html Ibn Sina, The Canon of Medicine, 1593]</ref> ('''\u0631\u064a\u0628\u0627\u0633''') or ''r\u0101vandu'r-r\u012bb\u0101\u1e63''<ref>[http://kenanaonline.com/users/tashger/posts/147509 \u0646\u0628\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0648\u0646\u062f Rheum]</ref> ('''\u0631\u0627\u0648\u0646\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0628\u0627\u0635''' ) (lit. \"r\u012bb\u0101s rhubarb''), in old Arabic [http://archive.tishreen.news.sy/tishreen/public/read/254115%20'utrufan 'utrufan], as in the pre-Islamic poetry of Abu Du'ad al-Iyadi\n*[[Armenian language|Armenian]] ''xanjil ha\u0121ar\u01f0i'' (\u053d\u0561\u0576\u0571\u056b\u056c \u0570\u0561\u0572\u0561\u0580\u057b\u056b) or Turkish [[loanword]] ''i\u0161xun'' (\u056b\u0577\u056d\u0578\u0582\u0576) \n*[[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]] ''qara\u011fat r\u0259v\u0259ndi'' (lit. \"currant rhubarb\")\n*[[Dari (Persian)|Dari]] (Afghan Persian) ''\u010dukri''<ref>[http://cnrit.tamu.edu/peace/pdfs/PEACE%20Project%20Afghanistan%20Complete%20Plant%20Species%20list%202009.pdf Plant Species List from Field Surveys: 2007 and 2008], Afghanistan PEACE Project</ref> ('''\u0686\u06a9\u0631\u06cc''')\n*[[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] ''ribes hermoni''<ref name=FlwrsIsrael/> ('''\u05e8\u05d9\u05d1\u05e1 \u05d7\u05e8\u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9''') (lit. \"rhubarb of [[Mount Hermon]]'') \n*[[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] ''rib\u00eaz, r\u00eavaz, r\u00eavas, r\u00eawas, r\u00eawaz''\n*[[Persian language|Persian]] ''r\u012bv\u0101s'' ('''\u0631\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0633''')  \n*[[Russian language|Russian]] \u0440\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439<ref name=plantarium/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yadflora.narod.ru/63.html |title=\u0420\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u044c |last=Moysenko |first=Gennadiy |date=2011 |language=Russian |website=\u042f\u0414\u041e\u0412\u0418\u0422\u042b\u0415 \u0420\u0410\u0421\u0422\u0415\u041d\u0418\u042f |publisher=Gennadiy Moysenko |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>  \n*[[Syriac language|Syriac]] ''ya\u0121m\u012b\u1e63\u0101''<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=V3nm8Krw0dgC&pg=PA194&dq=%22rheum+ribes%22&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=Rv2vT4XQHeTQ4QTG4OWtCQ&ved=0CEMQ6AEwAjg8#v=onepage&q=%22rheum%20ribes%22&f=false A Compendious Syriac Dictionary by R. Payne Smith, 1903]</ref><ref name=\"refSyriac\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=J-PxfFsmGcIC&pg=PA49&dq=%22rheum+ribes%22&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=Rv2vT4XQHeTQ4QTG4OWtCQ&ved=0CG0Q6AEwCTg8#v=onepage&q=%22rheum%20ribes%22&f=false The Medieval Islamic Underworld], The Ban\u016b S\u0101s\u0101n in Arabic Society and Literature, Clifford Edmund Bosworth, 1976</ref>  ('''\u071d\u0713\u0721\u071d\u0728\u0710''') \n*[[Turkish language|Turkish]] ''\u0131\u015fg\u0131n''.<ref>Prof. Dr. [[Turhan Baytop]] (1997), T\u00fcrk\u00e7e Bitki Adlar\u0131 S\u00f6zl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc, TDK yay\u0131nlar\u0131: 578, Ankara, 1997</ref> From [[Middle Turkic languages|Middle Turkic]] Div\u00e2nu L\u00fcgati't-T\u00fcrk by [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]]: ''\u0131\u015fgun''<ref>Divan\u00fc L\u00fbgat-it-T\u00fcrk Terc\u00fcmesi, \u00e7eviren Besim Atalayi TDK yay\u0131nlar\u0131:521, Ankara 1941, cilt: 1, sayfa: 109</ref> ('''\u0627\u0650\u0634\u0652\u063a\u064f\u0646\u0652''')\n*[[Urdu language|Urdu]] ''rawash''<ref name=FlPaki/>\n*[[Zazaki language|Zazaki]] ''r\u0131b\u00eas''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Linn53>{{Citation |mode=cs1|last1=Linnaeus |first1=Carolus |date=1753 |contribution=''Rheum ribes'' |title=Species Plantarum, Tomus I |publication-place=Stockholm |publisher=Impensis Laurentii Salvii |contribution-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/358391 |accessdate=2019-03-11 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=POWO_696789-1>{{cite web |title=''Rheum ribes'' <small>L.</small> |work=Plants of the World Online |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|url=http://www.plantsoftheworldonline.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:696789-1 |accessdate=2019-03-11 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.vanherbaryum.yyu.edu.tr/flora/famgenustur/polgo/rheum/index.htm Eight images of ''Rheum ribes'' from Van Herbarium]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1376178}}\n\n[[Category:Rheum (plant)|ribes]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Stem vegetables]]\n[[Category:Flora of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Flora of Iran]]\n[[Category:Flora of Iraq]]\n[[Category:Flora of Lebanon and Syria]]\n[[Category:Flora of Armenia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Flora of Jordan]]\n[[Category:Flora of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Flora of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Flora of Palestine (region)]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Syrian rhubarb\n|image = Rheum ribes - I\u015fg\u0131n 06.jpg\n|image_caption = \n|genus = Rheum\n|species = ribes\n|authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]<ref name=POWO_696789-1/>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=POWO_696789-1/>\n|synonyms =\n  {{Species list\n  |Rhabarbarum ribes|(L.) Moench\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''''Rheum ribes''''', the '''Syrian rhubarb''' or '''currant-fruited rhubarb''',<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010313034206/http://newcrops.uq.edu.au/listing/rheumribes.htm Australian New Crops]</ref> or '''warty-leaved rhubarb''',<ref>[http://apps.rhs.org.uk/horticulturaldatabase/hortdatabase.asp?ID=160860 RHS Horticultural Database]</ref> is an [[Edible plant stems|edible]] wild rhubarb species in the genus ''[[Rheum (plant)|Rheum]]''. It grows between 1000 and 4000 m on [[dunite]] rocks, among stones and slopes, and is now distributed in the [[temperate]] and [[subtropical]] regions of the world, chiefly in [[Western Asia]] ([[Turkey]], [[Syria]], [[Lebanon]], [[Iraq]], [[Iran]], [[Azerbaijan]], [[Armenia]]) to [[Afghanistan]] and [[Pakistan]].{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} The Syrian rhubarb a partially commercial vegetable collected from the nature in Eastern and Southern [[Anatolia]], Northern Iraq and partly Northwestern Iran in early spring. ''Rheum ribes'' is considered as a valuable medicinal species in [[herbal medicine]].\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Rivach=Rivas.JPG|thumb|''Rheum ribes'' growing in [[Iran]].]]\nThe Syrian rhubarb is a dichotomously branched [[Perennial plant|perennial]] stout herb, up to 1&nbsp;m tall. It has thick perennial [[rhizome]]s, large annual bean-shaped reddish-green leaves with [[Petiole (botany)|stalks]], edible [[Pedicel (botany)|flower stalks]], small yellowish flowers arranged in [[panicle]]s, three-sided ovate-oblong [[achene]]s and broad red-winged dull brown fruit.<ref>\u00d6nder T\u00fcrkmen, Mustafa \u00c7irka and Suat \u015eensoy (2005), [http://www.docsdrive.com/pdfs/ansinet/pjbs/2005/763-765.pdf Initial Evaluation of a New Edible Wild Rhubarb Species (Rheum ribes L.) with a Modified Weighted Scaling Index Method], Pakistan Journal of Biological Sciences 8 (5): 763-765, 2005</ref> The flowering stem ([[Peduncle (botany)|peduncle]]) is solid, warty, leafy below, leafless above.<ref name=VanHerb>[http://www.vanherbaryum.yyu.edu.tr/flora/famgenustur/polgo/rheum/index.htm Van Herbaryumu]</ref>\n\n=== Similar species ===\nIt is very similar to the species ''[[Rheum palaestinum]]'', being distinguished by having five central leaf veins as opposed to three, and being taller.<ref name=IsRedList2>{{cite web |url=https://redlist.parks.org.il/taxa/Rheum%20palaestinum/ |title=Endangered Plants of Israel Rheum palaestinum |last=Shmida |first=Avi |last2=Pollak |first2=Gadi |last3=Fragman-Sapir |first3=Ori |date=2011 |website= |publisher=Israel Nature and Parks Authority |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Agnia Losina-Losinskaja]] considered it very similar in leaves and flowers to [[Rheum maximowiczii|''R. maximowiczii'']] from further north in [[Central Asia]], but to be distinguished from it by its much rougher stem, much longer leaf [[Petiole (botany)|petioles]] and broader [[inflorescence]]. ''R. maximowiczii'' furthermore has three veins per leaf.<ref name=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435\u0420\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0438>{{cite journal |last=\u041b\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0430-\u041b\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f |first=\u0410\u0433\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430 |author-link=Agnia Losina-Losinskaja |date=1932 |title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0420\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0421\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u044d\u0438\u0438 |url=http://ashipunov.info/shipunov/school/sch-ru.htm |language=Russian |journal=\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0411\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0410\u041d \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420 |volume=30 |issue=1-2 |pages=382\u2013383 |access-date=31 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Karyotypy ===\n''R. ribes'' has a [[chromosome]] count of 2''n''=44.<ref name=karyotypes>{{cite journal |last=Ruirui |first=Liu |last2=Wang |first2=Ailan |last3=Tian |first3=Xinmin |last4=Wang |first4=Dongshi |last5=Liu |first5=Jianquan |date=2010 |title=Uniformity of karyotypes in Rheum (Polygonaceae), a species-rich genus in the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau and adjacent regions |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261646487 |journal=Caryologia Firenze |volume=63 |issue=1 |pages=82\u201390 |doi=10.1080/00087114.2010.10589711 |access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n''Rheum ribes'' was first formally described in 1753 by [[Carl Linnaeus]].<ref name=\"IPNI_696789-1\">{{cite web |title=Plant Name Details for ''Rheum ribes''&#32;L. |work=[[International Plant Names Index|The International Plant Names Index]] |url=http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=696789-1 |accessdate=2019-03-11 }}</ref> It was one of three species of ''Rheum'' described in ''[[Species Plantarum]]'' volume 1. Linnaeus referred to five earlier authors who had described the plant: [[Johann Jacob Dillenius]], [[Jacob Breyne]] (who calls it a ''Lapathum'', known as ''Ribes arabicum''), [[Richard Pococke]]<ref name=Linn53/> (who published in 1745 a description of his travels in the Near East and who brought seeds to England from Lebanon<ref name=Miller/>), [[Leonhard Rauwolf]] and [[Gaspard Bauhin]].<ref name=Linn53/>\n\nIn 1936 Losina-Losinskaja, in [[Vladimir Leontyevich Komarov|Komarov's]] ''Flora SSSR'', classifies this species in [[Section (botany)|section]] '''Ribesiformia''', in which she also places ''R. maximowiczii'', [[Rheum fedtschenkoi|''R. fedtschenkoi'']], [[Rheum cordatum|''R. cordatum'']], [[Rheum hissaricum|''R. hissaricum'']] and [[Rheum macrocarpum|''R. macrocarpum'']] (and ''R. lobatum'' and ''R. plicatum'', which are both now seen as synonyms of ''R. macrocarpum'').<ref name=SSSR>{{cite book |last=\u041b\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0430-\u041b\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f |first=\u0410\u0433\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430 |author-link=Agnia Losina-Losinskaja |date=1936 |chapter=''Rheum'' |chapter-url= |editor1-last=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0301\u0432 |editor1-first=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041b\u0435\u043e\u0301\u043d\u0442\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 |editor1-link=Vladimir Leontyevich Komarov  |title=Flora SSSR, Vol. 5 |url= |language=Russian |location=Moscow |publisher=\u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420 |pages=494\u2013500}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThis plant is first mentioned in Europe in the Arabic work, in English called the ''Book of Simple Medicaments'', by [[Serapion the Younger]], the Latin translation of which circulated throughout Europe in the late 13th to 15th century. Serapion says the plant is used to make the medicine thenceforth known in Europe as ''rob ribes''.<ref name=Miller>{{cite book |last=Miller |first=Phillip |date=1807 |title=The Gardener and Botanist's Dictionary, Vol. II |url=http://bibdigital.rjb.csic.es/ing/Libro.php?Libro=6238 |edition=9 |location=London |publisher=F.C. and J. Rivington |page= |author-link=Phillip Miller}}</ref> In Europe, herbalists initially thought he was describing a currant, which they then used to make local, lesser ''ribes''.\n\nOne of the first European works to write about this plant unambiguously was the ''Viertes Kreutterbuech - darein vil schoene und frembde Kreutter'' of 1576 by Leonhard Rauwolf, the first modern European botanist to travel through the [[Levant]] and [[Mesopotamia]]. The ''Viertes Kreutterbuech'' is one of the first ''[[herbarium|herbaria]]'' \u2013 the first with plants collected outside of Europe \u2013 and contains Rauwolf's notes on the pressed plants displayed. Rauwolf calls the plant ''Ribes arabum'' and saw it growing in [[Lebanon]] and [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]. He says the ''rob ribes'' of Serapion is made from the young flowering stalk.<ref name=Miller/><ref name=Linn53/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://kerkuil.leidenuniv.nl/digitale-tentoonstellingen-voor-2007/goedgezien/objectbeschrijvingen/object099.html |title=99. De Planten Gedroogd |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |language=Dutch |publisher=Universiteitsbibliotheek Leiden |access-date=11 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1623 ''Pinax Theatri Botanici'', Gaspard Bauhin attempts to sort all the plant names hitherto published. In this work he organises all ''[[Ribes|Grossularia]]'' and ''[[Ribes]]'' species known at the time into 13 species, the twelfth of which is ''Rheum ribes'', which Bauhin calls ''Ribes arabicum''. Bauhin bases this on the work of Rauwolf, but also [[Carolus Clusius|Clusius]] (who calls it ''Ribes legitima arabum''), [[Joachim Camerarius the Younger|Camerarius]] (''Ribes serapionis''), [[Rembert Dodoens]] (''Ribes serapionis foliis oxylapathi'') and [[Pierre Belon]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bauhin |first=Gaspard |date=1671 |title=Caspari Bauhini Pinax Theatri botanici, sive Index in Theophrasti, Dioscoridis, Plinii et botanicorum qui \u00e0 seculo scripserunt opera |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/30615#page/478/mode/1up |language=Latin |edition=2 |location=Basel |publisher=Impensis Joannis Regis |page=336 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.7092 |author-link=Gaspard Bauhin}}</ref>\n\nIn 1732, Johann Jacob Dillenius published his ''Hortus Elthamensis'' \u2013 a book of rare plants grown in London \u2013 which describes this plant. He calls it a type of ''Lapathum'' (now ''[[Rumex]]''), but mentions that it is known as ''Ribes arabicum''.<ref name=Linn53/> Dillenius obtained seeds in 1726 from [[William Sherard]], who brought them from Lebanon in 1724. He mentions that it was only grown elsewhere in Europe in [[Hortus Botanicus Leiden|Leyden]], from an older source.<ref name=Miller/>\n\nThe specific epithet ''ribes'' is thus derived via Serapion from the Arabic word ''r\u012bb\u0101s'' (\u0631\u064a\u0628\u0627\u0633), referring to the Syrian rhubarb.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/florahibernicaco00mackrich/page/108 <!-- quote=\"Rheum ribes\". --> Flora Hibernica (1836)] (Name, ''Ribes'', a word applied by the Arabic Physicians to a species of ''Rhubarb'', ''Rheum Ribes''.)</ref> The New Latin word ''ribes'' (currant) was corrupted from the Arabic word ''r\u012bb\u0101s'' by Europeans in the Renaissance, possibly due confusion with the original description of the bunches of berries on its panicle of fruit, with currants, a new crop at the time. ''R.&nbsp;ribes'', unlike many other species of rhubarb, has a fleshy, succulent [[epicarp]] around its seeds.<ref name=Miller/>\n\nThe generic name ''Rheum'' is derived from the Greek ''rheon'', mentioned by [[Dioscorides]] as a name for medicinal rhubarb; the word ''rheon'' is itself thought to be derived from the (old) Persian ''rewend'', which possibly referred to this species.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Why is an Apple a Pomme? A Journey with Words|last=Dunstone|first=Denis|publisher=Lulu Publishing Services|year=2014|isbn=1483418596|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution ==\nIt is native to Israel (only in the occupied [[Golan Heights]]),<ref name=IsRedList2/><ref name=FlwrsIsrael>[http://www.wildflowers.co.il/english/plant.asp?ID=2433 Wild Flowers of Israel]</ref><ref name=EuroMed>{{cite web |url=http://ww2.bgbm.org/EuroPlusMed/PTaxonDetailOccurrence.asp?NameId=55733&PTRefFk=7300000 |title=Polygonaceae, The Euro+Med Plantbase Project |last=Uotila |first=P. |date=2017 |website=Euro-Mediterranean Plant Base |publisher=Botanic Garden and Botanical Museum Berlin-Dahlem |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Jordan,<ref name=EuroMed/> Lebanon,<ref name=EuroMed/><ref name=Musselman>{{cite book |last=Musselman |first=Lytton John |date=2011 |title=Checklist of the plants of Lebanon and Syria |url=http://ww2.odu.edu/~lmusselm/plant/lebsyria/Checklist%20of%20Lebanon%20Plants.pdf |location=Norfolk, VA |publisher=Old Dominion University |page=105}}</ref> Syria,<ref name=EuroMed/><ref name=Musselman/> Azerbaijan (including [[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic|Nakhichevan]]),<ref name=EuroMed/><ref name=plantarium>{{cite web |url=http://www.plantarium.ru/page/view/item/31708.html |title=\u0420\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 - Rheum ribes - \u041e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430 - \u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0443\u043c |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |language=Russian |website=Plantarium |publisher= |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Armenia (as of 2011),<ref name=plantarium/> Iraq,<ref name=FlPaki>{{cite book |last=Qaiser |first=M. |date=2001 |editor1-last=Nasir |editor1-first=E. |editor2-last=Ali |editor2-first=S. I. |title=Flora of Pakistan, Vol. 205 Polygonaceae |url=http://efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=5&taxon_id=242100143  |location=Karachi |publisher=Missouri Botanical Garden Press and the University of Karachi |page= |isbn=}}</ref> Turkey,<ref name=EuroMed/><ref name=FlPaki/> Iran,<ref name=FlPaki/> Pakistan,<ref name=FlPaki/> Afghanistan<ref name=FlPaki/> and Russia.<ref name=FlPaki/>\n\n== Ecology ==\n[[File:Rheum ribes - I\u015fg\u0131n 08.jpg|thumb|''Rheum ribes'' in early May ''in situ'' at Karasakal Mt., [[Tufanbeyli]], near [[Adana]], [[Turkey]].]]\n\n=== Habitat ===\nIt is a floristic element of the Irano-Turanian [[Phytochorion|Region]] or Iran-Turan Plant Geography Region.<ref name=VanHerb/>\n\nIt is found in eastern Turkey on dry mountain slopes at 1600-2600m elevation in association with the plants ''[[Prangos ferulacea]]'' and ''[[Cousinia sivasica]]'' with which it forms the dominant flora such ecosystems.<ref name=beetles>{{cite journal |last=Korotyaev |first=Boris A. |last2=G\u00fcltekin |first2=Levent |last3=Volkovitsh |first3=Mark G. |last4=Dorofeyev |first4=Vladimir I. |last5=Konstantinov |first5=Alexander S. |date=January 2016 |title=Bioindicator beetles and plants in desertified and eroded lands in Turkey |url=https://www.mapress.com/j/jib/article/download/2016.4.1/14190 |journal=Journal of Insect Biodiversity |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=28, 29, 34, 42 |doi=10.12976/jib/2016.4.1  |access-date=16 March 2019|doi-access=free }}</ref> In Israel it is found on rocky slopes and cliffs in the transition zone of montane forests of ''[[Quercus boissieri]]''.<ref name=IsRedList2/>\n\n=== Insects ===\n''Rheum ribes'' is the main food plant of a tiny [[Callophrys|hairstreak]] butterfly, ''[[Callophrys mystaphia]]'', of which the Turkish name is ''\u0131\u015fg\u0131nz\u00fcmr\u00fct\u00fc'', the 'rhubarb emerald', in [[Adiyaman Province|Adiyaman]], [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Hakk\u00e2ri]], [[I\u011fd\u0131r Province|I\u011fd\u0131r]], [[Kahramanmara\u015f Province|Kahramanmara\u015f]], [[Kars Province|Kars]], [[Siirt Province|Siirt]] and [[Van Province|Van]] provinces in southeastern and eastern [[Turkey]].<ref>[http://www.trakel.org/kelebekler/?fsx=2fsdl17@d&tur=Minik%20Z%C3%BCmr%C3%BCt TRAKEL (T\u00fcrkiye'nin Anonim Kelebekleri)]</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/CentreForEntomologicalStudiesAnkaraCesaNewsNr.9 Van G\u00f6l\u00fc Havzas\u0131nda Kelebek \u00c7e\u015fitlili\u011fi (Diversity of the butterflies in Van Lake Basin East Turkey)] by Muhabbet Kemal, 2008</ref><ref name=ButtIran>{{cite journal |last=Krupitsky |first=Anatoly |last2=Kolesnichenko |first2=Kirill |date=March 2013 |title=A new species of the Callophrys mystaphia Miller, 1913\u2014group from Iran (Lepidoptera: Lycaenidae: Eumaeini) |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275746540 |journal=Zootaxa |volume=3619 |issue=4 |pages=460\u2013461 |doi=10.11646/zootaxa.3619.4.4 |access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref> This butterfly had not been seen since its description in 1913 (it turned out that the butterflies identified under this name in the former Soviet territories were in fact a different species), but in 2007\u20132008 it was rediscovered and its host plant was found. This animal has a distribution closely localised to ''Rheum'' populations, and has only been found in Turkey.<ref name=ButtIran/>\n\n''R. ribes'' leaves are the food plant of the moth ''[[Xylena exsoleta]]'' in [[Van Province]], Turkey.<ref>Muhabbet Kemal, Halil \u00d6zkol & Lokman Kayci (2008), [http://www23.us.archive.org/details/CentreForEntomologicalStudiesAnkaraMiscellaneousPapers139-140 ''Xylena'' Ochsenheimer in East Turkey with new provincial records and larval food-plants (''Noctuidae, Lepidoptera'')], in Miscellaneous Papers, Centre for Entomological Studies Ankara, no: 139-140, 20.03.2008</ref>\n\nBeetles associated with ''R. ribes'' in eastern Turkey are a ''[[Petrocladus]]'' sp. [[weevil]], the [[jewel beetle]] ''[[Capnodis marquardti]]'', and the [[leaf beetle]] ''[[Labidostomis brevipennis]]''. These are all specialised herbivores of the plant, and most appear endemic to Turkey as far as known. ''L. brevipennis'' lays its eggs on the leaves.<ref name=beetles/>\n\n== Cooking ==\n[[File:Rheum ribes.jpg|thumb|Immature inflorescences for sale at the historical market in [[Kad\u0131k\u00f6y]], [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]].]]\nThe edible part of the plant is the flowering stem, which is eaten raw or cooked (''ek\u015fili \u0131\u015fg\u0131n''<ref>[http://www.turkish-cuisine.org/english/article_details.php?p_id=12&PagingIndex=1&Pages=Articles Elaz\u0131\u011f Cuisine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503133041/http://www.turkish-cuisine.org/english/article_details.php?p_id=12&PagingIndex=1&Pages=Articles |date=2014-05-03 }}</ref> and ''\u0131\u015fk\u0131nl\u0131 yumurta'' [lit. 'eggs with wild rhubarb, Rheum ribes'] in [[El\u00e2z\u0131\u011f Province|El\u00e2z\u0131\u011f]], Turkey; ''khoresh rivas'' [\u062e\u0648\u0631\u0634 \u0631\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0633] or \"Persian rhubarb stew\"  in Iran) by the local people of [[Turkey]], [[Syria]], [[Iraq]], [[Iran]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"refSeval\">Seval And\u0131\u00e7, Yusuf Tun\u00e7t\u00fcrk, Elvan Ocak and Senol K\u00f6se (2009), [http://www.aensionline.com/rjabs/rjabs/2009/973-977.pdf Some Chemical Characteristics of Edible Wild Rhubarb Species (''Rheum Ribes'' L.)], Research Journal of Agriculture and Biological Sciences, 5(6): 973-977, 2009</ref> The leaves and [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]] are often eaten raw as [[salad]], sometimes sold in the local markets of [[Balochistan, Pakistan|Northern Balochistan]].<ref name=FlPaki/>\n\n== Traditional and current medicinal uses ==\n''Rheum ribes'' is the source of one of the most important crude [[drugs]] in West Asiatic regions. These plant vitamins A, B, C are seen in abundance. Syrian rhubarb root (''Rhizoma Rhei ribi'') is used traditionally to treat [[diabetes]], [[hemorrhoids]], [[peptic ulcer|ulcers]], and [[diarrhea]].<ref>Aladdin M. Naqishbandi, Knud Josefsen, Mikael Egebjerg Pedersen, Anna K. J\u00e4ger. [http://informahealthcare.com/doi/abs/10.1080/13880200902748478 Hypoglycemic activity of Iraqi Rheum ribes root extract]. Pharmaceutical Biology, May 2009, Vol. 47, No. 5 : Pages 380-383</ref> The plant is also used as a digestive and appetizer in [[Bitlis Province|Bitlis]], Turkey.<ref>Hanefi \u00d6zbek, Ebubekir Ceylan, Mehmet Kara, Fevzi \u00d6zg\u00f6k\u00e7e, Mehmet Koyuncu (2004), [http://biomedicum.ut.ee/sjlas/31_2_113-115.pdf Hypoglycemic effect of Rheum ribes roots in alloxan induced diabetic and normal mice] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503132550/http://biomedicum.ut.ee/sjlas/31_2_113-115.pdf |date=2014-05-03 }}. Scand. J. Lab. Anim. Sci. No. 2. 2004. Vol. 31</ref> Traditional [[herbal medicine]] stem and root dry plant for the treatment of [[anemia]], [[Anorexia (symptom)|anorexia]], [[weakness]], [[anxiety]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]] and [[diabetes]].<ref>Sayyah M, Boostani H, Pakseresht S, Malayeri A. Efficacy of hydroalcoholic extract of Rheum ribes L. in treatment of major depressive disorder. Journal of Medicinal Plant Research. 2009, 3(8):573-575</ref> Traditionally ''Rheum ribes'' has been used in Iran as [[sedative]] and mood enhancer.\n\nThe [[anthraquinones]] chrysophanol, [[parietin]] and [[emodin]], the [[flavonoids]] [[quercetin]], [[fisetin]], quercetin 3-0-rhamnoside, quercetin 3-0-galactoside and quercetin 3-0-rutinoside were isolated from the shoots of Syrian rhubarb.<ref name=\"refTosun\">Fatma Tosun & \u00c7i\u011fdem Aky\u00fcz-K\u0131z\u0131lay (2003), [http://dergiler.ankara.edu.tr/dergiler/24/1104/13097.pdf Anthraquinones and Flavonoids from Rheum ribes / Rheum ribes Bitkisinin Antrakinonlar\u0131 ve Flavonoitleri], Ankara Ecz. Fak. Derg. 32(1)31-35,2003</ref>\n\n== Conservation ==\nIn Israel it is an extremely rare plant found at two sites in the mountains of the [[Golan Heights]], but it is not protected by law.<ref name=IsRedList2/><ref name=IsRedList>{{cite web |url=https://redlist.parks.org.il/taxa/Rheum%20ribes/?highlight=%20Rheum%20ribes |title=Endangered Plants of Israel  \u05e8\u05d9\u05d1\u05e1 \u05d0\u05de\u05ea\u05d9 |last=Shmida |first=Avi |last2=Pollak |first2=Gadi |last3=Fragman-Sapir |first3=Ori |date=2011 |website= |publisher=Israel Nature and Parks Authority |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Names ==\n=== Antiquated English names ===\n'''rhubarb-currant''',<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KDRrAAAAMAAJ&q=%22rheum+ribes%22&dq=%22rheum+ribes%22&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=GPS0T-7iG-r_4QTa1KW5Dg&ved=0CF0Q6AEwCDiMAQ The medical formulary of al-Samarqand\u012b and the relation of early Arabic simples to those found in the indigenous medicine of the Near East and India], Naj\u012bb al-D\u012bn Mu\u1e25ammad ibn 'Al\u012b al-Samarqand\u012b, Martin Levey, Noury Al-Khaledy, Univ. of Pennsylvania Press, 1967</ref> '''warted-leaved rhubarb''',<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=nVwMAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=%22Rheum+ribes%22&source=bl&ots=tqV3PZ-PGl&sig=uInbq1RWZsI8dJ64MHG-zvOP0fQ&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=4MGuT8-GGaTO4QTW5_SfCQ&ved=0CHIQ6AEwBjg8#v=onepage&q&f=false Encyclop\u00e6dia Londinensis (1827)]</ref> '''rhubarb of [[Babilonia]]'''<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=r5jnQzwZjOYC&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=%22rheum+ribes%22+afghanistan&source=bl&ots=ksbim_BeJf&sig=rHw3vzDZSHcH_KrWkdFT5WlwUA0&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=Rza0T5WiDaHm4QTplpGKDg&ved=0CGMQ6AEwBTgK#v=onepage&q=%22rheum%20ribes%22%20afghanistan&f=false The Book of Duarte Barbosa by Mansel Longworth Dames, 1918-1921, London]</ref>\n\n=== Local names ===\n*[[Arabic]]: ''r\u012bb\u0101s'' <ref>[http://ddc.aub.edu.lb/projects/saab/avicenna/appendix_1.html Ibn Sina, The Canon of Medicine, 1593]</ref> ('''\u0631\u064a\u0628\u0627\u0633''') or ''r\u0101vandu'r-r\u012bb\u0101\u1e63''<ref>[http://kenanaonline.com/users/tashger/posts/147509 \u0646\u0628\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0648\u0646\u062f Rheum]</ref> ('''\u0631\u0627\u0648\u0646\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0628\u0627\u0635''' ) (lit. \"r\u012bb\u0101s rhubarb''), in old Arabic [http://archive.tishreen.news.sy/tishreen/public/read/254115%20'utrufan 'utrufan], as in the pre-Islamic poetry of Abu Du'ad al-Iyadi\n*[[Armenian language|Armenian]] ''xanjil ha\u0121ar\u01f0i'' (\u053d\u0561\u0576\u0571\u056b\u056c \u0570\u0561\u0572\u0561\u0580\u057b\u056b) or Turkish [[loanword]] ''i\u0161xun'' (\u056b\u0577\u056d\u0578\u0582\u0576) \n*[[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]] ''qara\u011fat r\u0259v\u0259ndi'' (lit. \"currant rhubarb\")\n*[[Dari (Persian)|Dari]] (Afghan Persian) ''\u010dukri''<ref>[http://cnrit.tamu.edu/peace/pdfs/PEACE%20Project%20Afghanistan%20Complete%20Plant%20Species%20list%202009.pdf Plant Species List from Field Surveys: 2007 and 2008], Afghanistan PEACE Project</ref> ('''\u0686\u06a9\u0631\u06cc''')\n*[[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] ''ribes hermoni''<ref name=FlwrsIsrael/> ('''\u05e8\u05d9\u05d1\u05e1 \u05d7\u05e8\u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9''') (lit. \"rhubarb of [[Mount Hermon]]'') \n*[[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] ''rib\u00eaz, r\u00eavaz, r\u00eavas, r\u00eawas, r\u00eawaz''\n*[[Persian language|Persian]] ''r\u012bv\u0101s'' ('''\u0631\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0633''')  \n*[[Russian language|Russian]] \u0440\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439<ref name=plantarium/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yadflora.narod.ru/63.html |title=\u0420\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d\u044c |last=Moysenko |first=Gennadiy |date=2011 |language=Russian |website=\u042f\u0414\u041e\u0412\u0418\u0422\u042b\u0415 \u0420\u0410\u0421\u0422\u0415\u041d\u0418\u042f |publisher=Gennadiy Moysenko |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>  \n*[[Syriac language|Syriac]] ''ya\u0121m\u012b\u1e63\u0101''<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=V3nm8Krw0dgC&pg=PA194&dq=%22rheum+ribes%22&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=Rv2vT4XQHeTQ4QTG4OWtCQ&ved=0CEMQ6AEwAjg8#v=onepage&q=%22rheum%20ribes%22&f=false A Compendious Syriac Dictionary by R. Payne Smith, 1903]</ref><ref name=\"refSyriac\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=J-PxfFsmGcIC&pg=PA49&dq=%22rheum+ribes%22&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=Rv2vT4XQHeTQ4QTG4OWtCQ&ved=0CG0Q6AEwCTg8#v=onepage&q=%22rheum%20ribes%22&f=false The Medieval Islamic Underworld], The Ban\u016b S\u0101s\u0101n in Arabic Society and Literature, Clifford Edmund Bosworth, 1976</ref>  ('''\u071d\u0713\u0721\u071d\u0728\u0710''') \n*[[Turkish language|Turkish]] ''\u0131\u015fg\u0131n''.<ref>Prof. Dr. [[Turhan Baytop]] (1997), T\u00fcrk\u00e7e Bitki Adlar\u0131 S\u00f6zl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc, TDK yay\u0131nlar\u0131: 578, Ankara, 1997</ref> From [[Middle Turkic languages|Middle Turkic]] Div\u00e2nu L\u00fcgati't-T\u00fcrk by [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]]: ''\u0131\u015fgun''<ref>Divan\u00fc L\u00fbgat-it-T\u00fcrk Terc\u00fcmesi, \u00e7eviren Besim Atalayi TDK yay\u0131nlar\u0131:521, Ankara 1941, cilt: 1, sayfa: 109</ref> ('''\u0627\u0650\u0634\u0652\u063a\u064f\u0646\u0652''')\n*[[Urdu language|Urdu]] ''rawash''<ref name=FlPaki/>\n*[[Zazaki language|Zazaki]] ''r\u0131b\u00eas''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Linn53>{{Citation |mode=cs1|last1=Linnaeus |first1=Carolus |date=1753 |contribution=''Rheum ribes'' |title=Species Plantarum, Tomus I |publication-place=Stockholm |publisher=Impensis Laurentii Salvii |contribution-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/358391 |accessdate=2019-03-11 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=POWO_696789-1>{{cite web |title=''Rheum ribes'' <small>L.</small> |work=Plants of the World Online |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|url=http://www.plantsoftheworldonline.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:696789-1 |accessdate=2019-03-11 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.vanherbaryum.yyu.edu.tr/flora/famgenustur/polgo/rheum/index.htm Eight images of ''Rheum ribes'' from Van Herbarium]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1376178}}\n\n[[Category:Rheum (plant)|ribes]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Stem vegetables]]\n[[Category:Flora of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Flora of Iran]]\n[[Category:Flora of Iraq]]\n[[Category:Flora of Lebanon and Syria]]\n[[Category:Flora of Armenia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Flora of Jordan]]\n[[Category:Flora of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Flora of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Flora of Palestine (region)]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n", "name_user": "Calmovare", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rheum_ribes"}
{"title_page": "Jean-Luc Bitton", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=October 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2012}}\n}}\n\n'''Jean-Luc Bitton''' (born in 1959 in [[Lyon, France]]) is a writer, journalist and author. Together with Raymond Cousse and Jean-Yves Reuzeau, he wrote ''Emmanuel Bove : La Vie Comme une Ombre'', a biography of the writer [[Emmanuel Bove]]. He also participated in the creation of the Bove segment on the television series \"A Century of Writers\" (1997) and has created a website devoted entirely to Bove. He will also be the first biographer of French poet [[Jacques Rigaut]], in a forthcoming book scheduled for publication in 2014. He has published articles in the journals Jungle, Perpendicular, The Series, the [[Nouvelle Revue Fran\u00e7aise]] and Rue Saint Ambrose.\n\n==Works==\n*''Emmanuel Bove : La Vie Comme une Ombre'', with Raymond Cousse and Jean-Yves Reuzeau. Preface by [[Peter Handke]]. Castor Astral (1994) {{ISBN|2-8592-0226-9}}  \n*''Nos Amours. Un Si\u00e8cle de Lettres d'Amour'', Flammarion (2001) {{ISBN|2-08-067871-X}} \n*''La Mer de la Tranquillit\u00e9: Images'', with Dolor\u00e8s Marat, Les Petits Matins (2005) {{ISBN|2-9158791-1-7}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bitton, Jean-Luc}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:French journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=October 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2012}}\n}}\n\n'''Jean-Luc Bitton''' (born in 1959 in [[Lyon, France]]) is a writer, journalist and author. Together with Raymond Cousse and Jean-Yves Reuzeau, he wrote ''Emmanuel Bove : La Vie Comme une Ombre'', a biography of the writer [[Emmanuel Bove]]. He also participated in the creation of the Bove segment on the television series \"A Century of Writers\" (1997) and has created a website devoted entirely to Bove. He will also be the first biographer of French poet [[Jacques Rigaut]], in a forthcoming book scheduled for publication in 2014. He has published articles in the journals Jungle, Perpendicular, The Series, the [[Nouvelle Revue Fran\u00e7aise]] and Rue Saint Ambrose.\n\n==Works==\n*''Emmanuel Bove : La Vie Comme une Ombre'', with Raymond Cousse and Jean-Yves Reuzeau. Preface by [[Peter Handke]]. Castor Astral (1994) {{ISBN|2-8592-0226-9}}  \n*''Nos Amours. Un Si\u00e8cle de Lettres d'Amour'', Flammarion (2001) {{ISBN|2-08-067871-X}} \n*''La Mer de la Tranquillit\u00e9: Images'', with Dolor\u00e8s Marat, Les Petits Matins (2005) {{ISBN|2-9158791-1-7}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bitton, Jean-Luc}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:French journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Luc_Bitton"}
{"title_page": "BenQ Mobile", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| type   = [[Subsidiary]]\n| name   = BenQ Mobile (Siemens Mobile)\n| logo   = Benq Mobile.png\n| caption =\n| brands = [[Siemens]] (until 2006)<br>BenQ-Siemens (2006-2007)\n| logo_size = 200px\n| foundation     = 1 October 2005\n| defunct        = 30 January 2007\n| fate = Bankruptcy\n| location       = [[Munich]], Germany\n| key_people     = [[Clemens Joos]], CEO; [[Jerry Wang]], EVP and CMO; [[Alex Liou]], Head of Corporate Finance; [[Irwin Chen]], Member of the Board\n| industry       = Communications\n| products       = Mobile phones, application software store \n| assets = US$775 million\n| num_employees  = ~3,000\n| parent         = [BenQ Corporation]]\n| homepage       = [http://www.benqmobile.com benqmobile.com]\n}}\n\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens Phone Store.jpg|thumbnail|BenQ-Siemens store]]\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens EF81 1.jpg|thumbnail|BenQ-Siemens EF81]]\n\n'''BenQ Mobile [[Gmbh]] & Co. [[General partnership|OHG]]''' was the mobile communications subsidiary of [[Taiwan]]ese [[BenQ|BenQ Corporation]], selling products under the '''BenQ-Siemens''' brand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hexus.net/tech/news/laptop/6907-benq-siemens-phone-maker-files-insolvency-protection/|title=BenQ-Siemens phone-maker files for insolvency protection|author=|date=|website=HEXUS|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref> The group, based in [[Munich]], [[Germany]], was formed out of BenQ's acquisition of the then struggling [[Siemens AG|Siemens]] [[Siemens Mobile|Mobile]] group in 2005. The newly formed company won the most [[iF product design award]]s in 2006 and also won many design awards in Germany's [[Red Dot|red dot]] competition.<ref>https://www.benq.is/news/1141858800_34_97.html</ref> BenQ Mobile went bust later that year.\n\n==History==\nSiemens Mobile was loss-making and struggling in the market, and the division was then sold to BenQ Corporation in June 2005 to try to turn the business around. As part of the deal, [[Siemens]] would pay BenQ at least 250 million euros to get the new venture to a solid start, in return of a 2.5% stake in BenQ.<ref name=\"hexus.net\">{{cite web|url=https://hexus.net/ce/news/communications/1403-siemens-seals-fate-mobile-communications-arm/|title=Siemens seals fate of its mobile communications arm|author=|date=|website=HEXUS|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The acquisition was completed on 1 October 2005 with the formation of BenQ Mobile, led by a German CEO, Clemens Joos, and a Taiwanese chairman, Jerry Wang. Joos had already been president of Siemens Mobile since 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infoworld.com/article/2672393/new-benq--siemens-mobile-phone-company-opens.html|title=New BenQ, Siemens mobile phone company opens|first=Dan|last=Nystedt|date=3 October 2005|website=InfoWorld|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nPart of the reason why BenQ was chosen by Siemens was the Taiwanese company's interest to keep German locations open - the headquarters in [[Munich]] and the manufacturing plants in [[Kamp-Lintfort]] and in [[Bocholt, Germany|Bocholt]].<ref name=\"hexus.net\"/> Other [[research and development]] and manufacturing plants were located in [[Aalborg]], [[Beijing]], [[Suzhou]], [[Ulm]] (also in Germany), [[Manaus]], [[Mexicali]], [[Taipei]] and [[Wroc\u0142aw]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.albawaba.com/news/benq-corporation-unveils-new-consumer-brand-benq-siemens|title=BenQ Corporation unveils new consumer brand BenQ-Siemens|author=|date=|website=Al Bawaba|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> Before the acquisition BenQ was already making mobile phones \u2013 including two [[Symbian]] [[UIQ]] smartphone models and one [[Windows Mobile]] smartphone model.<ref>http://southafrica.benq.com/news/1043874000_46_294.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/01/31/benq_ships_p50/|title=BenQ ships P50 Wi-Fi smart phone|first=Tony|last=Smith|date=31 January 2006|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens logo.svg|thumb|left|200px|Logo of BenQ-Siemens]]\nOn 17 January 2006, the first handsets under the new BenQ-Siemens brand were launched: the EF81 (this is the development of Siemens Mobile new phone in the old marketing product plan it was called internally or unreleased name \u201cSLV140\u201d) a slim clamshell phone similar to [[Motorola RAZR]]; the S68, a premium light and compact candybar phone targeting business users; and S88, a multimedia device with a 2-megapixel camera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/01/17/benq_siemens_phone_launch/|title=BenQ launches first BenQ-Siemens handsets|first=Tony|last=Smith|date=17 January 2006|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobilegazette.com/benq-siemens-launch-0601x18.htm|title=BenQ-Siemens Brand Launched - Mobile Gazette - Mobile Phone News|author=|date=|website=www.mobilegazette.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2006 the EF51 model was launched featuring music buttons on the front with a flip-down design that reveals a keypad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/02/13/benq-siemens-ef51-puts-music-front-and-center/|title=BenQ-Siemens EF51 puts music front and center|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ Mobile introduced the BenQ-Siemens P51 in March, a [[Windows Mobile 5.0]] device and the only smartphone the company would release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infoworld.com/article/2657444/benq-s-new-phones-include-windows-mobile-5-0-pda.html|title=BenQ's new phones include Windows Mobile 5.0 PDA|first=Nancy|last=Gohring|date=8 March 2006|website=InfoWorld|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Collapse===\nThe company ended up making huge losses, with parent BenQ losing $1 billion (\u20ac840 million) from the acquisition to September 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/6224185.stm|title=Meetings fail to save BenQ Mobile|author=|date=2 January 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2006/10/04/2003330421|title=BenQ estimates a loss of US$1.1 billion on phones - Taipei Times|author=|date=|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/09/28/benq-pulls-the-plug-on-its-german-mobile-division/|title=BenQ pulls the plug on its German mobile division|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and its share price dropping by 45 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/30a5fcf6-4992-11db-84da-0000779e2340|title=Subscribe to read|author=|date=|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ Mobile only had a global 2.4% market share as of Q3 2006, demonstrating its failure to turn the business around in its first year.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/02/business/worldbusiness/02iht-benq.4081240.html|title=With no willing buyers, BenQ will close its doors - Business - International Herald Tribune|author=|date=2 January 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In September it was announced that its factories in Mexico and Taiwan would halt production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/59a7ae06-48cf-11db-a996-0000779e2340|title=BenQ Mobile denies Germany closure|author=|date=20 September 2006|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nBenQ Mobile filed for bankruptcy in a [[Munich]] court on 29 September 2006, a day after its parent BenQ decided to stop funding the unit.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.networkworld.com/article/2307630/benq-blames-management-for--1b-loss-at-mobile-unit.html|title=BenQ blames management for $1B loss at mobile unit|first=Dan|last=Nystedt|date=3 October 2006|website=Network World|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> This sparked a debate in Germany over whether BenQ only acquired the Siemens mobile division for its patents and intellectual property, and that it did not intend to continue manufacturing mobile phones in Germany.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-the-fall-guy-in-benq-insolvency-scandal/a-2191802|title=Siemens the Fall Guy in BenQ Insolvency Scandal - DW - 02.10.2006|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The bankruptcy caused outrage in Germany over the possible thousands of job losses,<ref name=\"spiegel.de\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/ex-siemens-subsidiary-flops-benq-bankruptcy-causes-furor-a-440049.html|title=Ex-Siemens Subsidiary Flops: BenQ Bankruptcy Causes Furor|author=|date=29 September 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref> with chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] having said that Siemens is responsible for the BenQ Mobile (i.e. former Siemens Mobile) employees who are at risk.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Siemens set up a 35 million euros fund for the employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siemens.com/press/en/pressrelease/?press=/en/pr_cc/2006/10_oct/axx20061058_1409832.htm|title=Press Releases|author=|date=|website=www.siemens.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> Siemens stopped payment still owed to BenQ related to the original acquisition on 5 October<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-stops-payment-to-benq-in-taiwan/a-2195451|title=Siemens Stops Payment to BenQ in Taiwan - DW - 05.10.2006|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and considered taking legal action against BenQ about the future use of the brand and patents,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/33c752f8-5339-11db-99c5-0000779e2340|title=BenQ raises rescue estimate|author=|date=4 October 2006|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> although no claim would be made. Siemens was heavily criticised by some German politicians and labour unions for mismanagement that led to the bankruptcy under subsequent BenQ ownership.<ref name=\"spiegel.de\"/><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-chief-promises-full-explanation-of-bribery-scandal/a-2326912|title=Siemens Chief Promises Full Explanation of Bribery Scandal - DW - 25.01.2007|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> A BenQ executive said that stopping funds for the Mobile subsidiary and forcing it into [[insolvency]] protection was a \"really tough decision\" and not as easy as \"just walking away\" as was reported by some media outlets.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n2,000 employees were laid off in late October 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/24/business/worldbusiness/24iht-benq.3268295.html|title=BenQ has 4th straight loss on costs for German unit - Business - International Herald Tribune|author=|date=24 October 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nA scandal investigation was launched into Siemens's and BenQ's roles in the bankruptcy of BenQ Mobile amid allegations that financial offences were committed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/11/19/german-prosecutors-probing-benq-mobiles-bankruptcy/|title=German prosecutors probing BenQ Mobile's bankruptcy|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> As of March 2007, 13 executives, including Eric Yu, were detained in Taiwan accused of selling their shares in BenQ before the announcement knowing about the bankruptcy filing. Shares in BenQ fell 7% to its lowest level in ten years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/03/15/benq-faces-insider-trading-probe-as-cfo-gets-locked-up/|title=BenQ faces insider trading probe as CFO gets locked up|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ CEO K.Y. Lee was also detained a month later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.computing.co.uk/static/v3-closure|title=V3.co.uk closure|author=|date=|website=www.computing.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> At the same time Siemens was facing wide allegations in Germany of internal corruption and bribery not necessarily related to BenQ Mobile.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/a-swamp-of-bribes-siemens-forced-to-battle-internal-corruption-a-451105.html|title=A Swamp of Bribes: Siemens Forced to Battle Internal Corruption|author=|date=28 November 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref>\n\nAfter no suitable investors or buyers were found for the business, BenQ Mobile's insolvency administrator, Martin Prager, said on 2 January 2007 that the company would have to shut down.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> On 30 January the BenQ Mobile factory in [[Kamp-Lintfort]] closed. Representatives of the labour union [[IG Metall]] bid farewell to the last 165 workers with flowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070306094401/http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/84493|title=heise online - Production of BenQ Mobile handsets ends in Kamp-Lintfort|author=|date=6 March 2007|website=web.Archive.org|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The demise of BenQ Mobile caused 3,000 employees to lose their jobs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/07/07/insolvency_administrator_benq_sues_siemens/|title=BenQ administrator threatens to sue Siemens|first=Jan|last=Libbenga|date=7 July 2008|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The company's assets were auctioned off in [[Hamburg]] and at [[eBay]] in March 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2007/02/26/benq_mobile_liquidation/|title=BenQ Mobile dismembered|first=Christopher|last=Williams|date=26 February 2007|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"edn.com\">https://www.edn.com/electronics-news/4070317/BenQ-Siemens-to-be-auctioned</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cio.com/article/2442556/benq-mobile-to-be-divided-and-sold.html|title=BenQ Mobile to Be Divided and Sold|first=C. I. O.|last=Staff|date=26 February 2007|website=CIO|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and in June.\n\nThe losses of 2005 and 2006 wiped out all profits BenQ had made since 1999.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/08/26/taiwan-benq-insider-trading-markets-equities-lee-kun-yao.html#4a2865415634|title=Ex-BenQ CEO K.Y. Lee Cleared Of Insider Trading Charges|first=Forbes|last=staff|date=26 August 2009|website=Forbes|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===After demise===\nMartin Prager launched a 26-million-euro lawsuit against its former parent BenQ in August 2007 on top of 80 million euros already claimed. The lawsuit was partly for BenQ bonus payments promised to BenQ Mobile employees in Germany that were paid by the BenQ Mobile subsidiary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-28922620070810|title=Insolvency administrator sues BenQ for 26 mln euro|author=|date=10 August 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/08/10/bankrupt-benq-mobile-hits-parent-benq-with-third-lawsuit/|title=Bankrupt BenQ Mobile hits parent BenQ with third lawsuit|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"edn.com\"/> In July 2008, Prager threatened a multi-million euro lawsuit against Siemens after claiming irregularities were found in the acquisition and that BenQ Mobile was already insolvent as early as May 2006 - a claim first reported by German newspaper ''[[Die Welt]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/Print/2008/07/07/insolvency_administrator_benq_sues_siemens/|title=BenQ administrator threatens to sue Siemens \u2022 The Register|author=|date=|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> A settlement between Prager and Siemens was reached in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siemens.com/press/en/pressrelease/?press=/en/pressrelease/2008/corporate_communication/axx20081112.htm|title=Press Releases|author=|date=|website=www.siemens.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nFormer BenQ CEO K. Y. Lee, along with several executives including Eric Yu and Sheaffer Lee, were cleared of their insider trading, embezzlement and forgery charges in August 2009 after a two-year trial.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nAfter the company closed, its former parent company, BenQ, launched five new phones (produced in Asia) under the BenQ-Siemens brand during 2007 (the license still ran for another four years). These include the A53 ([[Taiwan]] only), E52, C31, C32 and SF71 \u2013<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobilegazette.com/benq-siemens-e52-c31-07x06x12.htm|title=BenQ Siemens E52 and C31 - Mobile Gazette - Mobile Phone News|author=|date=|website=www.mobilegazette.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/benq-siemens-sf71-joins-in-the-shiny-clamshell-fun-252065|title=BenQ Siemens SF71 Joins in the Shiny Clamshell Fun|first=Charlie|last=White|date=|website=Gizmodo|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> briefly continuing the lifespan of the BenQ-Siemens brand. In August 2007, BenQ announced that it would resume production of mobile devices using its own \"BenQ\" brand, coming with the announcements of the BenQ E72, M7 and T51 models that would initially launch in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://e71.ru/news/2007-06-23-30|title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0444\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c\u044e \"BenQ-Siemens\" / The last mobiles, carrying \"BenQ-Siemens\" logo - 23 \u0418\u044e\u043d\u044f 2007 - \u041a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 BenQ-Siemens E71/EL71|author=|date=|website=e71.ru|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ started making [[Android OS|Android]] devices from 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=BenQ rejoins the smartphone market with two tepid Android models |url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/12/02/benq-f3-a3-android-smartphones/ |date=2 December 2013 |access-date=1 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==List of mobile phones==\n[[File:Benq.siemens.s68.jpg|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens S68]]\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens EF51.jpg|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens EF51]]\n[[File:Benq-Siemens E71.JPG|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens E71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens A38]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens A58]] (cancelled)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens AL26]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C26]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C52]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CF61]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CL61]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CL71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E52]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E61]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EL71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF51]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF82]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF91]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens M81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens P51]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S65-DVBH]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S68]] (this was the best-selling BenQ-Siemens phone)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S81]] (''pictured'')\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S88]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SF71]] (not presented in Europe)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL80]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL91]] (cancelled)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL98]] (not presented)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.benq.com/products/mobile BenQ Global - Communications]\n\n[[Category:Defunct mobile phone manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Siemens]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Technology companies disestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics brands]]\n[[Category:Bankrupt mobile phone companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| type   = [[Subsidiary]]\n| name   = BenQ Mobile (Siemens Mobile)\n| logo   = Benq Mobile.png\n| caption =\n| brands = [[Siemens]] (until 2006)<br>BenQ-Siemens (2006-2007)\n| logo_size = 200px\n| foundation     = 1 October 2005\n| defunct        = 30 January 2007\n| fate = Bankruptcy\n| location       = [[Munich]], Germany\n| key_people     = [[Clemens Joos]], CEO; [[Jerry Wang]], EVP and CMO; [[Alex Liou]], Head of Corporate Finance; [[Irwin Chen]], Member of the Board\n| industry       = Communications\n| products       = Mobile phones, application software store \n| assets = US$775 million\n| num_employees  = ~3,000\n| parent         = [BenQ Corporation]]\n| homepage       = [http://www.benqmobile.com benqmobile.com]\n}}\n\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens Phone Store.jpg|thumbnail|BenQ-Siemens store]]\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens EF81 1.jpg|thumbnail|BenQ-Siemens EF81]]\n\n'''BenQ Mobile [[Gmbh]] & Co. [[General partnership|OHG]]''' was the mobile communications subsidiary of [[Taiwan]]ese [[BenQ|BenQ Corporation]], selling products under the '''BenQ-Siemens''' brand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hexus.net/tech/news/laptop/6907-benq-siemens-phone-maker-files-insolvency-protection/|title=BenQ-Siemens phone-maker files for insolvency protection|author=|date=|website=HEXUS|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref> The group, based in [[Munich]], [[Germany]], was formed out of BenQ's acquisition of the then struggling [[Siemens AG|Siemens]] [[Siemens Mobile|Mobile]] group in 2005. The newly formed company won the most [[iF product design award]]s in 2006 and also won many design awards in Germany's [[Red Dot|red dot]] competition.<ref>https://www.benq.is/news/1141858800_34_97.html</ref> BenQ Mobile went bust later that year.\n\n==History==\nSiemens Mobile was loss-making and struggling in the market, and the division was then sold to BenQ Corporation in June 2005 to try to turn the business around. As part of the deal, [[Siemens]] would pay BenQ at least 250 million euros to get the new venture to a solid start, in return of a 2.5% stake in BenQ.<ref name=\"hexus.net\">{{cite web|url=https://hexus.net/ce/news/communications/1403-siemens-seals-fate-mobile-communications-arm/|title=Siemens seals fate of its mobile communications arm|author=|date=|website=HEXUS|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The acquisition was completed on 1 October 2005 with the formation of BenQ Mobile, led by a German CEO, Clemens Joos, and a Taiwanese chairman, Jerry Wang. Joos had already been president of Siemens Mobile since 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infoworld.com/article/2672393/new-benq--siemens-mobile-phone-company-opens.html|title=New BenQ, Siemens mobile phone company opens|first=Dan|last=Nystedt|date=3 October 2005|website=InfoWorld|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nPart of the reason why BenQ was chosen by Siemens was the Taiwanese company's interest to keep German locations open - the headquarters in [[Munich]] and the manufacturing plants in [[Kamp-Lintfort]] and in [[Bocholt, Germany|Bocholt]].<ref name=\"hexus.net\"/> Other [[research and development]] and manufacturing plants were located in [[Aalborg]], [[Beijing]], [[Suzhou]], [[Ulm]] (also in Germany), [[Manaus]], [[Mexicali]], [[Taipei]] and [[Wroc\u0142aw]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.albawaba.com/news/benq-corporation-unveils-new-consumer-brand-benq-siemens|title=BenQ Corporation unveils new consumer brand BenQ-Siemens|author=|date=|website=Al Bawaba|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> Before the acquisition BenQ was already making mobile phones \u2013 including two [[Symbian]] [[UIQ]] smartphone models and one [[Windows Mobile]] smartphone model.<ref>http://southafrica.benq.com/news/1043874000_46_294.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/01/31/benq_ships_p50/|title=BenQ ships P50 Wi-Fi smart phone|first=Tony|last=Smith|date=31 January 2006|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens logo.svg|thumb|left|200px|Logo of BenQ-Siemens]]\nOn 17 January 2006, the first handsets under the new BenQ-Siemens brand were launched: the EF81 (this is the development of Siemens Mobile new phone in the old marketing product plan it was called internalized \u201cSLV140\u201d) a slim clamshell phone similar to [[Motorola RAZR]]; the S68, a premium light and compact candybar phone targeting business users; and S88, a multimedia device with a 2-megapixel camera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/01/17/benq_siemens_phone_launch/|title=BenQ launches first BenQ-Siemens handsets|first=Tony|last=Smith|date=17 January 2006|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobilegazette.com/benq-siemens-launch-0601x18.htm|title=BenQ-Siemens Brand Launched - Mobile Gazette - Mobile Phone News|author=|date=|website=www.mobilegazette.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2006 the EF51 model was launched featuring music buttons on the front with a flip-down design that reveals a keypad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/02/13/benq-siemens-ef51-puts-music-front-and-center/|title=BenQ-Siemens EF51 puts music front and center|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ Mobile introduced the BenQ-Siemens P51 in March, a [[Windows Mobile 5.0]] device and the only smartphone the company would release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infoworld.com/article/2657444/benq-s-new-phones-include-windows-mobile-5-0-pda.html|title=BenQ's new phones include Windows Mobile 5.0 PDA|first=Nancy|last=Gohring|date=8 March 2006|website=InfoWorld|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Collapse===\nThe company ended up making huge losses, with parent BenQ losing $1 billion (\u20ac840 million) from the acquisition to September 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/6224185.stm|title=Meetings fail to save BenQ Mobile|author=|date=2 January 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2006/10/04/2003330421|title=BenQ estimates a loss of US$1.1 billion on phones - Taipei Times|author=|date=|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/09/28/benq-pulls-the-plug-on-its-german-mobile-division/|title=BenQ pulls the plug on its German mobile division|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and its share price dropping by 45 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/30a5fcf6-4992-11db-84da-0000779e2340|title=Subscribe to read|author=|date=|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ Mobile only had a global 2.4% market share as of Q3 2006, demonstrating its failure to turn the business around in its first year.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/02/business/worldbusiness/02iht-benq.4081240.html|title=With no willing buyers, BenQ will close its doors - Business - International Herald Tribune|author=|date=2 January 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In September it was announced that its factories in Mexico and Taiwan would halt production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/59a7ae06-48cf-11db-a996-0000779e2340|title=BenQ Mobile denies Germany closure|author=|date=20 September 2006|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nBenQ Mobile filed for bankruptcy in a [[Munich]] court on 29 September 2006, a day after its parent BenQ decided to stop funding the unit.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.networkworld.com/article/2307630/benq-blames-management-for--1b-loss-at-mobile-unit.html|title=BenQ blames management for $1B loss at mobile unit|first=Dan|last=Nystedt|date=3 October 2006|website=Network World|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> This sparked a debate in Germany over whether BenQ only acquired the Siemens mobile division for its patents and intellectual property, and that it did not intend to continue manufacturing mobile phones in Germany.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-the-fall-guy-in-benq-insolvency-scandal/a-2191802|title=Siemens the Fall Guy in BenQ Insolvency Scandal - DW - 02.10.2006|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The bankruptcy caused outrage in Germany over the possible thousands of job losses,<ref name=\"spiegel.de\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/ex-siemens-subsidiary-flops-benq-bankruptcy-causes-furor-a-440049.html|title=Ex-Siemens Subsidiary Flops: BenQ Bankruptcy Causes Furor|author=|date=29 September 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref> with chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] having said that Siemens is responsible for the BenQ Mobile (i.e. former Siemens Mobile) employees who are at risk.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Siemens set up a 35 million euros fund for the employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siemens.com/press/en/pressrelease/?press=/en/pr_cc/2006/10_oct/axx20061058_1409832.htm|title=Press Releases|author=|date=|website=www.siemens.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> Siemens stopped payment still owed to BenQ related to the original acquisition on 5 October<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-stops-payment-to-benq-in-taiwan/a-2195451|title=Siemens Stops Payment to BenQ in Taiwan - DW - 05.10.2006|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and considered taking legal action against BenQ about the future use of the brand and patents,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/33c752f8-5339-11db-99c5-0000779e2340|title=BenQ raises rescue estimate|author=|date=4 October 2006|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> although no claim would be made. Siemens was heavily criticised by some German politicians and labour unions for mismanagement that led to the bankruptcy under subsequent BenQ ownership.<ref name=\"spiegel.de\"/><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-chief-promises-full-explanation-of-bribery-scandal/a-2326912|title=Siemens Chief Promises Full Explanation of Bribery Scandal - DW - 25.01.2007|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> A BenQ executive said that stopping funds for the Mobile subsidiary and forcing it into [[insolvency]] protection was a \"really tough decision\" and not as easy as \"just walking away\" as was reported by some media outlets.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n2,000 employees were laid off in late October 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/24/business/worldbusiness/24iht-benq.3268295.html|title=BenQ has 4th straight loss on costs for German unit - Business - International Herald Tribune|author=|date=24 October 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nA scandal investigation was launched into Siemens's and BenQ's roles in the bankruptcy of BenQ Mobile amid allegations that financial offences were committed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/11/19/german-prosecutors-probing-benq-mobiles-bankruptcy/|title=German prosecutors probing BenQ Mobile's bankruptcy|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> As of March 2007, 13 executives, including Eric Yu, were detained in Taiwan accused of selling their shares in BenQ before the announcement knowing about the bankruptcy filing. Shares in BenQ fell 7% to its lowest level in ten years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/03/15/benq-faces-insider-trading-probe-as-cfo-gets-locked-up/|title=BenQ faces insider trading probe as CFO gets locked up|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ CEO K.Y. Lee was also detained a month later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.computing.co.uk/static/v3-closure|title=V3.co.uk closure|author=|date=|website=www.computing.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> At the same time Siemens was facing wide allegations in Germany of internal corruption and bribery not necessarily related to BenQ Mobile.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/a-swamp-of-bribes-siemens-forced-to-battle-internal-corruption-a-451105.html|title=A Swamp of Bribes: Siemens Forced to Battle Internal Corruption|author=|date=28 November 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref>\n\nAfter no suitable investors or buyers were found for the business, BenQ Mobile's insolvency administrator, Martin Prager, said on 2 January 2007 that the company would have to shut down.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> On 30 January the BenQ Mobile factory in [[Kamp-Lintfort]] closed. Representatives of the labour union [[IG Metall]] bid farewell to the last 165 workers with flowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070306094401/http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/84493|title=heise online - Production of BenQ Mobile handsets ends in Kamp-Lintfort|author=|date=6 March 2007|website=web.Archive.org|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The demise of BenQ Mobile caused 3,000 employees to lose their jobs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/07/07/insolvency_administrator_benq_sues_siemens/|title=BenQ administrator threatens to sue Siemens|first=Jan|last=Libbenga|date=7 July 2008|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The company's assets were auctioned off in [[Hamburg]] and at [[eBay]] in March 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2007/02/26/benq_mobile_liquidation/|title=BenQ Mobile dismembered|first=Christopher|last=Williams|date=26 February 2007|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"edn.com\">https://www.edn.com/electronics-news/4070317/BenQ-Siemens-to-be-auctioned</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cio.com/article/2442556/benq-mobile-to-be-divided-and-sold.html|title=BenQ Mobile to Be Divided and Sold|first=C. I. O.|last=Staff|date=26 February 2007|website=CIO|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and in June.\n\nThe losses of 2005 and 2006 wiped out all profits BenQ had made since 1999.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/08/26/taiwan-benq-insider-trading-markets-equities-lee-kun-yao.html#4a2865415634|title=Ex-BenQ CEO K.Y. Lee Cleared Of Insider Trading Charges|first=Forbes|last=staff|date=26 August 2009|website=Forbes|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===After demise===\nMartin Prager launched a 26-million-euro lawsuit against its former parent BenQ in August 2007 on top of 80 million euros already claimed. The lawsuit was partly for BenQ bonus payments promised to BenQ Mobile employees in Germany that were paid by the BenQ Mobile subsidiary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-28922620070810|title=Insolvency administrator sues BenQ for 26 mln euro|author=|date=10 August 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/08/10/bankrupt-benq-mobile-hits-parent-benq-with-third-lawsuit/|title=Bankrupt BenQ Mobile hits parent BenQ with third lawsuit|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"edn.com\"/> In July 2008, Prager threatened a multi-million euro lawsuit against Siemens after claiming irregularities were found in the acquisition and that BenQ Mobile was already insolvent as early as May 2006 - a claim first reported by German newspaper ''[[Die Welt]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/Print/2008/07/07/insolvency_administrator_benq_sues_siemens/|title=BenQ administrator threatens to sue Siemens \u2022 The Register|author=|date=|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> A settlement between Prager and Siemens was reached in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siemens.com/press/en/pressrelease/?press=/en/pressrelease/2008/corporate_communication/axx20081112.htm|title=Press Releases|author=|date=|website=www.siemens.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nFormer BenQ CEO K. Y. Lee, along with several executives including Eric Yu and Sheaffer Lee, were cleared of their insider trading, embezzlement and forgery charges in August 2009 after a two-year trial.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nAfter the company closed, its former parent company, BenQ, launched five new phones (produced in Asia) under the BenQ-Siemens brand during 2007 (the license still ran for another four years). These include the A53 ([[Taiwan]] only), E52, C31, C32 and SF71 \u2013<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobilegazette.com/benq-siemens-e52-c31-07x06x12.htm|title=BenQ Siemens E52 and C31 - Mobile Gazette - Mobile Phone News|author=|date=|website=www.mobilegazette.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/benq-siemens-sf71-joins-in-the-shiny-clamshell-fun-252065|title=BenQ Siemens SF71 Joins in the Shiny Clamshell Fun|first=Charlie|last=White|date=|website=Gizmodo|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> briefly continuing the lifespan of the BenQ-Siemens brand. In August 2007, BenQ announced that it would resume production of mobile devices using its own \"BenQ\" brand, coming with the announcements of the BenQ E72, M7 and T51 models that would initially launch in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://e71.ru/news/2007-06-23-30|title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0444\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c\u044e \"BenQ-Siemens\" / The last mobiles, carrying \"BenQ-Siemens\" logo - 23 \u0418\u044e\u043d\u044f 2007 - \u041a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 BenQ-Siemens E71/EL71|author=|date=|website=e71.ru|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ started making [[Android OS|Android]] devices from 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=BenQ rejoins the smartphone market with two tepid Android models |url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/12/02/benq-f3-a3-android-smartphones/ |date=2 December 2013 |access-date=1 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==List of mobile phones==\n[[File:Benq.siemens.s68.jpg|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens S68]]\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens EF51.jpg|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens EF51]]\n[[File:Benq-Siemens E71.JPG|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens E71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens A38]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens A58]] (cancelled)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens AL26]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C26]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C52]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CF61]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CL61]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CL71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E52]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E61]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EL71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF51]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF82]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF91]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens M81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens P51]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S65-DVBH]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S68]] (this was the best-selling BenQ-Siemens phone)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S81]] (''pictured'')\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S88]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SF71]] (not presented in Europe)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL80]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL91]] (cancelled)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL98]] (not presented)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.benq.com/products/mobile BenQ Global - Communications]\n\n[[Category:Defunct mobile phone manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Siemens]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Technology companies disestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics brands]]\n[[Category:Bankrupt mobile phone companies]]\n", "name_user": "Toxicxtina", "label": "safe", "comment": "Text improvement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BenQ_Mobile"}
{"title_page": "Pyaar Ka Mandir", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Pyaar Mandir\n| image          = PyarKaMandir.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = Vinyl Record Cover\n| director       = [[K. Bapaiah]]\n| producer       = Shabnam Kapoor\n| writer         = \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Mithun Chakraborty]]<br />[[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]]<br />[[Raj Kiran (Bollywood actor)|Raj Kiran]]<br />[[Shoma Anand]]<br />[[Kader Khan]]<br />[[Aruna Irani]]\n| music          = [[Laxmikant Pyarelal]] <br />[[Anand Bakshi]] <small> (Lyrics) </small>\n| cinematography =\n| editing        = \n| distributor    =\n| released       = 1 April 1988\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n\n'''''Pyaar Ka Mandir''''' is a [[Bollywood films of 1988|1988]] [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Bollywood]] family-drama film directed by [[K. Bapaiah]], released on 1 April 1988. The film stars [[Mithun Chakraborty]], [[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]], [[Nirupa Roy]], [[Raj Kiran (Bollywood actor)|Raj Kiran]], [[Shoma Anand]], [[Kader Khan]] and [[Aruna Irani]]. The movie released some months after Kishore Kumar died, but his song \"Ae Duniya Tujhko Salaam\" remains an evergreen hit.\n\n==Synopsis==\nLaxmi Kumar (Nirupa Roy), a widowed school teacher, lives with her three sons, Sanjay, Vijay and Ajay, and daughter, Meena in their family home they call \"House of Love\". The talented Vijay secretly does manual labor to augment his mom's income, so that his brothers can study [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]] and law respectively.\n\nMeena is to be married to a young man named Satish, and Laxmi goes to withdraw her chit fund from Gopal Khaitan, only to find out that he has duped her. The devastated family gather to confront this, only to have their mom lose her teaching job. Vijay swears to apprehend Gopal, a confrontation ensues, and Gopal is killed. In this way Vijay gets the money so that Meena's wedding takes place, while his brothers continue to study. Vijay is arrested, found guilty and sentenced to seven years in prison.\n\nAfter his discharge, Vijay returns home to find that their family home has been sold. Ajay, who is now the collector, has married Sapna, a very wealthy woman. They have a daughter, Geeta, and are living in a government bungalow; Sanjay is now a lawyer and is living in a palatial home. Both brothers reject Vijay and have nothing to do with him. Devastated he starts driving an auto-rickshaw for a living, hoping that he meets with his mother, who, as he has been told by his brothers, is away on a religious pilgrimage. Vijay does meet his mom, who is working as a common laborer at a construction site, and confronts his brothers. The truth will be revealed as to why Vijay confessed to killing Gopal.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Mithun Chakraborty]] as  Vijay\n*[[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]] as Radha\n*[[Raj Kiran (Bollywood actor)|Raj Kiran]] as Ajay\n*[[Sachin (actor)|Sachin]] as Sanjay\n*[[Shoma Anand]] as Sapna\n*[[Kader Khan]] as Dr. Bhuljaanewala\n*[[Aruna Irani]] as Shanti\n*[[Asrani]]\n*[[Bharat Kapoor]] as Gopal Seth\n*[[Shakti Kapoor]] as Dilip\n*[[Raza Murad]] as Adam Khan\n*[[Nirupa Roy]] as Mother\n*[[Dhumal (actor)|Dhumal]] as Patient\n\n==Music==\n*\"Pyar Ke Pahle Kadam Pe\" - [[Kishore Kumar]], [[Alka Yagnik]]\n*\"O Meri Jaan Meri Jaan\" - [[Mohammad Aziz]], [[Alka Yagnik]]\n*\"Jhopad Patti Zindabad\" - [[Kishore Kumar]]\n*\"Aye Duniya Tujhko Salam\" - [[Kishore Kumar]]\n*\"Log Jahan Per Rahate Hain\" - [[Mohammad Aziz]], [[Suresh Wadkar]], [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]], [[Udit Narayan]]\n*\"Log Jahan Per Rahate Hain (Sad)\" - [[Mohammad Aziz]]\n\n==Box office==\nThe film was a super hit and fifth highest-grossing movie of 1988.<ref>https://m.imdb.com/list/ls005133557/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0155074}}\n\n[[Category:1988 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1980s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Kovelamudi Bapayya]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Laxmikant\u2013Pyarelal]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Pyaar Mandir\n| image          = PyarKaMandir.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = Vinyl Record Cover\n| director       = [[K. Bapaiah]]\n| producer       = Shabnam Kapoor\n| writer         = \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Mithun Chakraborty]]<br />[[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]]<br />[[Raj Kiran (Bollywood actor)|Raj Kiran]]<br />[[Shoma Anand]]<br />[[Kader Khan]]<br />[[Aruna Irani]]\n| music          = [[Laxmikant Pyarelal]] <br />[[Anand Bakshi]] <small> (Lyrics) </small>\n| cinematography =\n| editing        = \n| distributor    =\n| released       = 1 April 1988\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n\n'''''Pyaar Ka Mandir''''' is a [[Bollywood films of 1988|1988]] [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Bollywood]] family-drama film directed by [[K. Bapaiah]], released on 1 April 1988. The film stars [[Mithun Chakraborty]], [[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]], [[Nirupa Roy]], [[Raj Kiran (Bollywood actor)|Raj Kiran]], [[Shoma Anand]], [[Kader Khan]] and [[Aruna Irani]]. The movie released some months after Kishore Kumar died, but his song \"Ae Duniya Tujhko Salaam\" remains an evergreen hit.\n\n==Synopsis==\nLaxmi Kumar (Nirupa Roy), a widowed school teacher, lives with her three sons, Sanjay, Vijay and Ajay, and daughter, Meena in their family home they call \"House of Love\". The talented Vijay secretly does manual labor to augment his mom's income, so that his brothers can study [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]] and law respectively.\n\nMeena is to be married to a young man named Satish, and Laxmi goes to withdraw her chit fund from Gopal Khaitan, only to find out that he has duped her. The devastated family gather to confront this, only to have their mom lose her teaching job. Vijay swears to apprehend Gopal, a confrontation ensues, and Gopal is killed. In this way Vijay gets the money so that Meena's wedding takes place, while his brothers continue to study. Vijay is arrested, found guilty and sentenced to seven years in prison.\n\nAfter his discharge, Vijay returns home to find that their family home has been sold. Ajay, who is now the collector, has married Sapna, a very wealthy woman. They have a daughter, Geeta, and are living in a government bungalow; Sanjay is now a lawyer and is living in a palatial home. Both brothers reject Vijay and have nothing to do with him. Devastated he starts driving an auto-rickshaw for a living, hoping that he meets with his mother, who, as he has been told by his brothers, is away on a religious pilgrimage. Vijay does meet his mom, who is working as a common laborer at a construction site, and confronts his brothers. The truth will be revealed as to why Vijay confessed to killing Gopal.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Mithun Chakraborty]] as  Vijay\n*[[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]] as Radha\n*[[Raj Kiran (Bollywood actor)|Raj Kiran]] as Ajay\n*[[Sachin (actor)|Sachin]] as Sanjay\n*[[Shoma Anand]] as Sapna\n*[[Kader Khan]] as Dr. Bhuljaanewala\n*[[Aruna Irani]] as Shanti\n*[[Asrani]]\n*[[Bharat Kapoor]] as Gopal Seth\n*[[Shakti Kapoor]] as Dilip\n*[[Raza Murad]] as Adam Khan\n*[[Nirupa Roy]] as Mother\n*[[Dhumal (actor)|Dhumal]] as Patient\n\n==Music==\n*\"Pyar Ke Pahle Kadam Pe\" - [[Kishore Kumar]], [[Alka Yagnik]]\n*\"O Meri Jaan Meri Jaan\" - [[Mohammad Aziz]], [[Alka Yagnik]]\n*\"Jhopad Patti Zindabad\" - [[Kishore Kumar]]\n*\"Aye Duniya Tujhko Salam\" - [[Kishore Kumar]]\n*\"Log Jahan Per Rahate Hain\" - [[Mohammad Aziz]], [[Suresh Wadkar]], [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]], [[Udit Narayan]]\n*\"Log Jahan Per Rahate Hain (Sad)\" - [[Mohammad Aziz]]\n\n==Box Office==\nThe film was a super hit and fifth highest grossing movie of 1988.<ref>https://m.imdb.com/list/ls005133557/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0155074}}\n\n[[Category:1988 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1980s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Kovelamudi Bapayya]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Laxmikant\u2013Pyarelal]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBox office:clean up,typo(s) fixed: highest grossing \u2192 highest-grossing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyaar_Ka_Mandir"}
{"title_page": "Women's Equality Party", "text_new": "{{About|the UK political party|the New York based political party|Women's Equality Party (New York)}}\n{{short description|UK political party}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| country = United Kingdom\n| name = Women's Equality Party\n| logo = WEP logo.JPG\n| abbreviation = WE (or WEP)\n| founders = [[Sandi Toksvig]]<br />[[Catherine Mayer]]\n| leader1_title = Leader\n| leader1_name = [[Mandu Reid]]\n| foundation = {{start date|df=yes|2015|03|02}}\n| headquarters = 2 Tunstall Road<br>London<br>SW9 8BN\n| membership_year = September 2018\n| membership = 45,000<ref>{{cite news |last=Agerholm |first=Harriet |title=Final Say: Leader of Women's Equality Party backs the Independent's campaign |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/final-say-womens-equality-party-sophie-walker-peoples-vote-second-referendum-a8528296.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=8 September 2018 |access-date=8 September 2018}}</ref>\n| ideology = {{Nowrap|[[Feminism]]<br />[[Egalitarianism]]<br />[[Pro-Europeanism]]<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1194163519769522177|user=WEP_UK|date=12 December 2019|title=BREAKING: WE are thrilled to announce that the @LibDems have adopted our key policies on ending #abuse in their manifesto. Following this, WE will be standing down in Cities of London & Westminster and Sheffield Hallam to help them campaign against #Brexit}}</ref>}}\n| euopean = \n| europarl = \n| affiliation1_title = \n| affiliation1 = [[Progressive Alliance]]\n| colours = {{Color box|{{Women's Equality Party (UK)/meta/color2}}|border=darkgray}} Purple<br/>{{Color box|{{Women's Equality Party (UK)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} Green\n''[[Women's Social and Political Union|WSPU]] colours''\n| website = http://womensequality.org.uk/\n| colorcode = {{Women's Equality Party (UK)/meta/color}}\n| seats1_title = [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|0|650|hex=#993366}}\n| seats2_title = [[House of Lords]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|724|hex=#993366}}\n| seats3_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|0|73|hex=#993366}}\n| seats8_title = [[Local government in the United Kingdom|Local government]]\n| seats8 = {{Composition bar|1|21259|hex=#993366}}<!--Parish and town councillors do not count to this total, this is for principal authority seats-->\n}}\n\nThe '''Women's Equality Party''' is a [[List of feminist parties|feminist political party]] set up in the United Kingdom in 2015. The idea was conceived by [[Catherine Mayer]] and [[Sandi Toksvig]] at the [[Women of the World Festival]], when they concluded that there was a need for a party to campaign for [[gender equality]] to the benefit of all. The launch meeting was on 28 March 2015 under the title \"The Women's Equality Party needs you. But probably not as much as you need the Women's Equality Party\". The party's full policy was launched by its then leader, [[Sophie Walker]], at [[Conway Hall Ethical Society#Conway Hall|Conway Hall]], on 20 October 2015. In January 2020, [[Mandu Reid]] took over as party leader.\n\n== History ==\n{{multiple image| direction = vertical | width = 100 | footer = Co-founders of the Women's Equality Party | image1 = CatherineMayerPortrait.jpg | alt1 = | caption1 = [[Catherine Mayer]] | image2 = Sandi Toksvig in 2009.jpg | alt2 = | caption2 = [[Sandi Toksvig]] | align = left}}\nOn 2 March 2015, author and journalist [[Catherine Mayer]] attended a \"Women in Politics\" event at the [[Women of the World Festival]] (at the [[Southbank Centre]] in central London). The panel was chaired by [[Jude Kelly]] (Artistic Director, Southbank Centre), and the panel consisted of [[Katie Ghose]] (CEO, [[Electoral Reform Society]]), [[Margot James]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]), [[Stella Creasy]] ([[Labour Co-operative|Labour]]) and [[Jo Swinson]] ([[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Lib Dem]]).<ref name=Artefact>{{cite news |last1=Madberg |first1=Astrid |last2=Turnley |first2=Molly |title=Highlights from WOW 2015: Women in Politics, 2 March 2015 |url=https://www.artefactmagazine.com/2015/03/19/highlights-from-wow-2015/ |work=Artefact Magazine |date=19 March 2015 |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref> Having watched the panelists agreeing collegially with each other on almost every point, Mayer stood up and said, \"What about if I found a Women's Equality Party, tell you what, I'm going to go to the bar afterwards, anyone interested in discussing this come and see me.\"<ref name=Milligan>{{cite episode |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02pty5g |title=The brand new Women's Equality Party: 'not standing in this election' |series=[[PM (BBC Radio 4)|PM]] |last1=Milligan |first1=Becky |date=23 April 2015 |station=BBC Radio 4 |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2015 ([[International Women's Day]]), at the same festival, comedian [[Sandi Toksvig]] presented an event entitled \"Sandi Toksvig's Mirth Control: Stand Up and Be Counted\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Sandi Toksvig's mirth control: stand up and be counted, Royal Festival Hall, Southbank Centre, 8 March 2015 |url=http://www.southbankcentre.co.uk/whatson/mirth-control-89533 |publisher=[[Southbank Centre]] |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref> Interviewed by [[Jenni Murray]] on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Woman's Hour]]'', Toksvig said: \"I had a fantasy cabinet of women, and I didn't care which party they came from, we had [[Doreen Lawrence]] as our [[Home Secretary]]. Can you imagine anything more wonderful? We had [[Paralympics|paralympian]] [[Tanni Grey-Thompson]] as our [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport|Sports Minister]], and I asked them to put forward practical suggestions. The world is in a parlous state, 9.1 million women failed to vote in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|last election]], we need to attract them, we also need to attract the more than 7 million men who didn't vote. Why are people not engaged in politics, because I don't think that the people standing represent the diversity of this country.\"<ref name=W_Hour>{{cite episode |last1=Murray |first1=Jenni (host) |author-link1=Jenni Murray |last2=Toksvig |first2=Sandi (guest) |author-link2=Sandi Toksvig |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b05s3gyy |title=Sandi Toksvig interview |series=[[Woman's Hour]] |minutes=00:30 |date=30 April 2015 |station=BBC Radio 4 |accessdate=25 September 2015}}</ref> Mayer phoned Toksvig, and the two agreed to become co-founders of the party.<ref name=Cocozza>{{cite news |last=Cocozza |first=Paula |title=Women's Equality party founders: 'It needed doing. So we said, \"Let's do it\"' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/28/womens-equality-party-founders-it-needed-doing-so-we-said-lets-do-it-sandi-toksvig |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=28 August 2015 |accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first meeting of the as yet unnamed party was on 28 March 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/events/362216697294937/ |title=The Women's Equality Party needs you |last1= |first1= |website=Facebook |date= |accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=Artefact /><ref>{{cite web |title=First #WE meeting |url=https://womensequality.org.uk/news/2015/03/02/first-we-meeting/ |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=2 March 2015 |accessdate=25 September 2015}}</ref> Speakers included: [[Suzanne Moore]], who had previously stood for parliament as an independent candidate; [[Sophie Walker]], who spoke on careers, parenting and ensuring that both parents have opportunities in both; [[Halla Gunnarsd\u00f3ttir]], who described a [[Women's List|women's equality party in Iceland]]; and [[Hannah McGrath]], who discussed the practicalities of starting a party. The meeting was covered on ''Woman's Hour''<ref name=W_Hour /> and by the press, including ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' magazine<ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Ella |title=Will you support the Women's Equality Party? |url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/news/features/2015/04/02/womens-equality-party-formed-by-catherine-mayer-policies-and-background |work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |location=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast|Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications]] |date=2 April 2015 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> and the ''[[London Evening Standard]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Staff writer |title=Londoner's Diary: Women's party is ready to be a player |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/londoners-diary-womens-party-is-ready-to-be-a-player-10189809.html |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |location=London |date=20 April 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{external media |topic=TEDx talk by Sandi Toksvig |video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r92jUj7gNRw ''A political party for women's equality''] via [[TEDx|TEDx Talks]] on [[YouTube]]<ref name=\"C-SPAN\">{{cite AV media |people=[[Sandi Toksvig]] |date=October 2016 |accessdate=22 March 2017 |title=A political party for women's equality |medium=Video |publisher=[[TEDx|TEDx Talks]] via [[YouTube]] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r92jUj7gNRw}}\n:Toksvig tells the story of how she helped start a new political party in Britain, the Women's Equality Party, with the express purpose of putting equality on the ballot.</ref>}}\nA second meeting took place at [[Conway Hall]] on 18 April, and included Sandi Toksvig, [[Mandy Colleran]], [[Nimko Ali]], [[Shabnam Shabazi]] and [[Stella Duffy]] as speakers.<ref name=Milligan />\n\nOn 30 April, Toksvig announced that she was leaving her position as comp\u00e8re of Radio 4's ''[[The News Quiz]]'' in order to help set up the new [[political party]], which was now named the Women's Equality Party.<ref name=Topping>{{cite news |last=Topping |first=Alexandra |title=Sandi Toksvig reveals she quit Radio 4 to set up women's rights political party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/30/sandi-toksvig-quit-radio-4-news-quiz-set-up-womens-rights-political-party |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=30 April 2015 |access-date=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Furness>{{cite news |last=Furness |first=Hannah |title=Sandi Toksvig quit The News Quiz for Women's Equality Party |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/bbc/11574333/Sandi-Toksvig-quit-The-News-Quiz-for-Womens-Equality-Party.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Guest |first=Katy |title=Sandi Toksvig's Women's Equality Party is a movement for which time has come |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/sandi-toksvigs-womens-equality-party-is-a-movement-for-which-time-has-come-10221200.html |work=[[The Independent]] |publisher=Independent Print Ltd |date=2 May 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> Speaking at the [[Hay Festival]] in May, Toksvig reported that since she had announced the move on BBC One's ''[[The One Show]]'', she had been subjected to a significant level of [[cyberbullying|abuse online]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Elgot |first=Jessica |title=Sandi Toksvig: trolls are already out over plans to form Women's Equality party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/25/sandi-toksvig-trolls-womens-equality-party-bbc-abuse |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=25 May 2015 |accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Women's Equality Party was registered with the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] on 20 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/English/Registrations/PP2755 |title=Women's Equality Party |publisher=Electoral Commission |accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> On 22 July, [[Reuters]] journalist Sophie Walker was announced as the party's first leader.<ref name=Cocozza /><ref name=Cohen>{{cite news |last=Cohen |first=Claire |title=Watch out Cameron: Meet the leader of Britain's first feminist political party |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-politics/11753983/Womens-Equality-Party-Meet-politics-new-chief-feminist-leading-it.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=22 July 2015 |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Leadership contest 2018 ===\nThe party announced its first leadership contest in December 2017. Nominations opened on 5 January 2018, and closed on 24 January.<ref name=\"UKevote_Timetable\">{{cite web |title=Timetable |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204184709/https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/timetable |archive-date=4 February 2018 |url=https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/timetable |website=pre.ukevote.uk/we |publisher=Election portal for the Women\u2019s Equality Party Leadership Election |access-date=4 February 2018}}</ref> Two candidates were nominated: interim leader Sophie Walker<ref name=\"UKevote_Profiles1\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Sophie Walker |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204185634/https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/profiles/nzmcvdnn-sophie-walker |archive-date=4 February 2018 |url=https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/profiles/nzmcvdnn-sophie-walker |website=pre.ukevote.uk/we |publisher=Election portal for the Women's Equality Party Leadership Election |access-date=4 February 2018}}</ref> and Magda Devas, who had previously run for the [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] in the Streatham Wells ward in the [[2010 Lambeth London Borough Council election#Streatham Wells|Lambeth London Borough Council election of 2010]] and [[2014 Lambeth London Borough Council election#Streatham Wells|that of 2014]].<ref name=\"UKevote_Profiles2\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Magda Devas |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204185914/https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/profiles/jf2crfgh-magda-devas |archive-date=4 February 2018 |url=https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/profiles/jf2crfgh-magda-devas |website=pre.ukevote.uk/we |publisher=Election portal for the Women's Equality Party Leadership Election |access-date=4 February 2018}}</ref> The ballot opened on 14 February 2018, and closed on 6 March; Walker was declared the winner on 8 March.<ref name=\"UKevote_Timetable\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! %\n! Sources\n|-\n| Magda Devas\n| 550\n| 9.90\n|<ref name=\"UKevote_Results\">{{cite web |title=Declaration of result: Women's Equality Party Leadership Election |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308141643/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/4959/attachments/original/1520460695/results.pdf?1520460695 |archive-date=8 March 2018 |url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/4959/attachments/original/1520460695/results.pdf?1520460695 |website=uk-engage.org |publisher=UK Engage |access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sophie Walker]]\n| 5,002\n| 90.10\n|<ref name=\"UKevote_Results\" />\n|}\n\nWalker was due to serve a five-year term until 2023,<ref name=\"UKevote_Role\">{{cite web |title=Role description: Leader of the Women's Equality Party |url=https://files.ukevote.uk/wep/role_description__we_party_leader_18_12_17.pdf |website=pre.ukevote.uk/we |publisher=Election portal for the Women's Equality Party Leadership Election |access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> but stepped down from her role as leader in January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Syal |first=Rajeev |title=Women's Equality party leader Sophie Walker steps down |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/22/womens-equality-party-leader-sophie-walker-steps-down |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=22 January 2019 |accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> She was replaced by interim leader Mandu Reid, the party's national spokesperson on equal parenting and caregiving, its candidate in the [[2018 Lewisham East by-election]], and the CEO of period poverty charity The Cup Effect.<ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Equality Party announces Interim Leader and London Mayoral Candidate |url=https://www.womensequality.org.uk/new_interim_leader_mayoral_candidate |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=8 March 2019 |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political aims ==\nThe party's mission statement opens with: \"Equality for women isn't a women's issue. When women fulfil their potential, everyone benefits. Equality means better politics, a more vibrant economy, a workforce that draws on the talents of the whole population and a society at ease with itself\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Carrie |last=Lyell |title=Sandi Toksvig launches new political party |url=http://www.divamag.co.uk/category/news/sandi-toksvig-launches-new-political-party.aspx |work=[[Diva (magazine)|Diva]] |publisher=Millivres Prowler Group Ltd. |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote frame|\n* Equal representation in politics and business;\n* Equal representation in education;\n* Equal pay;\n* Equal treatment of women by and in the media;\n* Equal parenting rights;\n* An end to violence against women.\n|Women's Equality Party|six stated goals of the party<ref name=Cohen/>}}\n\nDescribing the six aims Mayer said, \"It's a very narrow palette, we're not looking to be a party that can answer questions about what should be done in the Ukraine, or trying to have a platform on the environment or anything else, we are focusing absolutely narrowly on that equality agenda.\"<ref name=Milligan /> Party leader Walker agreed: \"We won't have policies on other issues. We are going to concentrate, laser-like, on all of the above, to make them happen. And we will welcome people from any other political party that agrees with our values of diversity and inclusivity to work with us.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Sophie |author-link=Sophie Walker |title=Our party's going to reclaim women's equality: help us make it happen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jul/24/womens-equality-party-make-it-happen |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=24 July 2015 |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref> However, Walker promised that the party's working definition of the word \"woman\", as well as more detail of the party's policies, would be covered in its policy launch, following consultation with party members.<ref name=Statesman_220915>{{cite news |last=Speed |first=Barbara |title=Women's Equality Party leader: \"We aim to push ourselves out of business\" |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2015/09/sophie-walker-leader-womens-equality-party-were-only-party-whose-aim-push-ourselves-out-business |work=[[New Statesman]] |publisher=Progressive Media International |date=22 September 2015 |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nEarly indications of what to expect included Walker's call for a gender quota system to select [[Member of parliament#United Kingdom|MP]]s at the following two elections so that equal representation could be achieved in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] by 2025.<ref name=Guardian_131015>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Rowena |last2=Watt |first2=Nicholas |title=Women's Equality party says quotas could achieve balanced Commons in 10 years |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/13/womens-equality-party-says-quotas-could-achieve-balanced-commons-in-10-years |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=13 October 2015 |accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref> Walker also called for six weeks' paid leave, at 90% pay, for both parents after having a baby, as well as an extra 10 months of shared leave at statutory pay.<ref name=Buzz_151015>{{cite news |last=Ashton |first=Emily |title=This new political party wants to give both parents six weeks of paid leave |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/emilyashton/this-new-political-party-wants-to-give-both-parents-six-week#.ve56eBkln |work=[[BuzzFeed]] |publisher=BuzzFeed Inc. |date=15 October 2015 |access-date=16 October 2015}}</ref> Writing in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', Toksvig stated that the party further proposed that [[Employment Tribunal|industrial tribunal]] costs be reduced from over \u00a31,000 to \"\u00a350 for those who can afford it\" in order to \"empower all women to speak out about sexism at work.\"<ref name=Mirror_151015>{{cite news |last=Toksvig |first=Sandi |author-link=Sandi Toksvig |title=Sandi Toksvig: Bosses can turn a blind eye to sexism thanks to new rules |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/sandi-toksvig-bosses-can-turn-6638611 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=15 October 2015 |access-date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe party launched its full set of policies on 20 October 2015 at Conway Hall.<ref name=Policy_launch>{{cite web |title=Women's Equality Party announces first policies and campaigns |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/policy_launch_announcement |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=20 October 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=Guardian_211015a>{{cite news |last=Minter |first=Harriet |title=The Women's Equality Party launch is not a moment too soon |url=https://www.theguardian.com/women-in-leadership/2015/oct/21/the-womens-equality-party-launch-is-not-a-moment-too-soon |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=21 October 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== First party conference ===\nThe inaugural Women's Equality Party conference took place in Manchester on 25\u201327 November 2016,<ref>{{cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |title=Sophie Walker: 'Put a woman in a political race and she is always the outsider' |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/sophie-walker-put-a-woman-in-a-political-race-and-she-is-always-the-outsider-a3403576.html |work=London Evening Standard |location=London |date=24 November 2016 |accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/conference_2016 |title=Conference 2016 |publisher=Women's Equality Party |accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref> with opening speeches by founders Catherine Mayer and Sandi Toksvig on the first day,<ref>{{cite book |last=Women's Equality Party |title=Let's Make History Together: Conference Programme |issue=1 |page=22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329145618/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/1334/attachments/original/1479470574/WE_Party_Conference_Programme_2016.pdf?1479470574 |archive-date=29 March 2017 |url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/1334/attachments/original/1479470574/WE_Party_Conference_Programme_2016.pdf?1479470574 |publisher=Women's Equality Party |location=Manchester |year=2016}}</ref> and Sophie Walker's leader's speech on the second day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sophie Walker's leadership speech |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/sophie_walker_s_leadership_speech |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=27 November 2016 |accessdate=28 November 2016}} [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2j6uMTUKANc Video.]</ref>\n\nMotions carried at the conference include: a motion to expand the UK's definition of [[Hate crime#United Kingdom|hate crime]] to include [[misogyny]]; a motion to strengthen the legislation for carers who need flexible working arrangements; and a motion to fully decriminalise abortion across the UK (the current [[Abortion Act 1967|Abortion Act]] excludes Northern Ireland).<ref>{{cite news |last=Grant |first=Katie |title=Make misogyny a hate crime and decriminalise abortion, Women's Equality Party demands |url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/news/politics/make-misogyny-hate-crime-decriminalise-abortion-womens-equality-party-demands/ |work=[[i (newspaper)|i News]] |location=London |date=27 November 2016 |accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Additional party goal ====\nA seventh goal of the party was added to the existing six at the party's first conference.\n{{Quote frame|\n* Equality in healthcare and medical research.|Women's Equality Party|additional goal of the party.<ref name=Peaker_291116>{{cite news |last=Peaker |first=Hannah ''(chief of staff for WE)'' |title=Why health equality is the next goal for the Women's Equality party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/nov/29/health-equality-goal-womens-equality-party |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=29 November 2016 |accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Second party conference ===\nThe second party conference took place in [[Kettering]] in September 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hinsliff |first=Gaby |author-link=Gaby Hinsliff |title=Is the Women's Equality party too sensible for these extreme times? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/sep/07/womens-equality-party-politics-sophie-walker |work=The Guardian |nopp=yes |page=Opinion |date=7 September 2018 |access-date=25 January 2019}}</ref> Among the motions passed was one supporting the [[People's Vote]] campaign calling for a public vote on the final [[Brexit]] deal between the United Kingdom and the European Union.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conference 2018 Motion Outcomes |url=https://www.womensequality.org.uk/conf_18_motions_results |website=womensequality.org.uk |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=9 September 2018 |access-date=25 January 2019}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20190125170205/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/5824/attachments/original/1535466047/Brexit_amended_motion_2018_(1).pdf Text.]</ref>\n\n== The party's name ==\nThe party's name was \"debated and discussed at two public meetings\".<ref name=Duffy_310515>{{cite web |last=Duffy |first=Stella |author-link=Stella Duffy |title=The Women's Equality Party question I keep getting asked... (blog) |url=https://stelladuffy.wordpress.com/2015/05/31/the-womens-equality-party-question-i-keep-getting-asked/ |website=stelladuffy.wordpress.com |publisher=Stella Duffy via WordPress |date=31 May 2015 |accessdate=11 April 2016 }}</ref> When Toksvig was asked why the party was named the Women's Equality Party, rather than just the Equality Party, she answered: \"Because there is a huge issue, women are certainly not equal.... It's time that women, finally, after all these years, what is it, almost a hundred years since we finally got the vote, it's time we stepped up and took our equal place in society.\" She also stated the party's motto, \"Equality is better for everybody\".<ref name=W_Hour /> Mayer has also stated, \"I\u2019m very happy with the name: all genders are joining us and I hope they continue to. More than half the population is living in inequality and that is genuinely not good for everyone, economically or culturally.\"<ref name=Guardian_181015>{{cite news |last=McVeigh |first=Tracy |title=After a whirlwind start, the Women's Equality Party faces its first test \u2013 a call for quotas |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/18/women-equality-party-politics-first-test-quotas |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=18 October 2015 |accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Elections ==\n[[File:Pride in London 2016 - Enthusiastic members of the Women's Equality Party in Trafalgar Square.png|alt=Members of the Women's Equality Party at Trafalgar Square during the Pride in London 2016 parade.|thumb|Members of the Women's Equality Party at [[Trafalgar Square]] during the Pride in London 2016 parade]]\n\n=== 2015 ===\nThe party did not field any candidates in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], but planned to do so when the next election was assumed to be in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=ENG |first=Cafebabel |title=The new UK political party fighting for women's equality |work=[[caf\u00e9babel]] |publisher=[[Erasmus Programme]] |url=http://www.cafebabel.co.uk/politics/article/the-new-uk-political-party-fighting-for-womens-equality.html |date=2 June 2015 |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Staff writer |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-32531750 |title=Sandi Toksvig campaigns for equality with new political party |work=[[BBC News]] |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> Walker told [[BBC Radio Wales]]' ''Sunday Supplement'' programme that the party would be taking a [[Nonpartisanism|non-partisan]] approach to elections, stating that \"We will be undertaking consultations with our members and deciding which seats to target\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Staff writer |title=Women's Equality Party to field candidates in assembly elections |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-33664219 |work=BBC News: Wales politics |publisher=BBC |date=25 July 2015 |access-date=22 September 2015}}</ref> Figures from the party suggested that there was a possibility that an existing [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) might defect to the party before the party contested an election, citing the example of how the [[UK Independence Party]] got its first MPs.<ref name=Milligan/> although this did not happen. Initially Walker neither ruled in or out the possibility of a WEP candidate in the [[2016 London mayoral election]]: \"We'd like to. It's a \u00a320,000 losable deposit, though. If you're [[Zac Goldsmith]] that's not such a big deal but if a woman from a normal background wants to speak out for women and do it with the mayorship, automatically she's almost excluded\". However, in October 2015, the party announced its intention to field candidates in the [[2016 London Assembly election]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Urwin |first=Rosamund |title=Sophie Walker: 'We could have an equal parliament in a decade' |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/sophie-walker-we-could-have-an-equal-parliament-in-a-decade-a3093711.html |work=London Evening Standard |location=London |date=19 October 2015 |accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 ===\nFollowing various fundraisers, the party was able to field candidates in the 2016 London elections<ref name=Stewart_060416>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Heather |title=London mayoral race is transformed as Sophie Walker raises profile of women |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2016/apr/06/london-mayor-race-transformed-sophie-walker-women |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=6 April 2016 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> (Walker in the [[2016 London mayoral election|Mayoral election]], plus candidates for the [[2016 London Assembly election#List candidates|London Assembly]]);<ref name=\"Diversity\">{{cite web |last=Diversity UK Editor |title=Sophie Walker is WE candidate for London Mayor |url=http://diversityuk.org/sophie-walker-is-we-candidate-for-london-mayor/ |website=diversityuk.org |publisher=Diversity UK |date=3 February 2016 |accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> [[2016 Scottish Parliament election|Scottish Parliament election]], [[Glasgow (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Glasgow region]] (Anne Beetham, Susan Mackay, Ruth Wilkinson, Calum Shepherd, Penelope Haddrill, Carol Young)<ref>{{cite web |last=Campaigns |title=Women's Equality Party's Scottish manifesto out |url=http://www.womensviewsonnews.org/2016/04/womens-equality-partys-scottish-manifesto-out/ |website=womensviewsonnews.org |publisher=Women's Views on News |date=6 April 2016 |access-date=23 April 2016}}</ref> and [[Lothian (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Lothian region]] (Lee Chalmers, Jennifer Royston, Catriona MacDonald and Abigail Herrmann);<ref name=\"EEN_010416\">{{cite news |last=Staff writer |title=Edinburgh's parliament election candidates named |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/politics/edinburgh-s-parliament-election-candidates-named-1-4088458 |work=[[Edinburgh Evening News]] |publisher=[[Johnston Press]] |date=1 April 2016 |access-date=23 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Staff writer |title=Women's Equality Party adds two Scottish Parliament candidates to May election lineup |url=http://www.wearethecity.com/news-womens-equality-party-adds-two-scottish-parliament-candidates-to-may-election-lineup/ |website=wearethecity.com |publisher= WeAreTheCity |date=2 February 2016 |accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> and the [[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|Welsh Assembly election]] in [[South Wales Central (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|South Wales Central]] (Sharon Lovell, Emma Rose, Sarah Rees and Ruth Williams).<ref name=\"Diversity\" /><ref name=\"Walesonline_110416\">{{cite news |last=Mosalski |first=Ruth |title=The four women standing for the Women's Equality Party in the National Assembly election |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/four-women-standing-womens-equality-11169873 |work=[[Media Wales#WalesOnline|WalesOnline]] |publisher=[[Media Wales]] |date=11 April 2016 |access-date=23 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nSupporters of the WEP's election bid included: [[Emma Thompson]],<ref name=\"G_Letters\">{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Emma |author-link=Emma Thompson |title=Letters: Emma Thompson 'I do not want to die before closing the pay gap' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/02/emma-thompson-i-do-not-want-to-die-before-closing-the-pay-gap |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=2 May 2016 |accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_020516\">{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Heather |title=Emma Thompson backs Women's Equality party for mayoral election |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/may/02/emma-thompson-womens-equality-party-mayoral-election |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=2 May 2016 |accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref> [[Lily Allen]], [[Hugh Quarshie]], [[Tanya Moodie]], [[Philippa Perry]], [[Jack Monroe]],<ref name=Half>{{cite AV media |people=Catherine Mayer, Lily Allen, Ninotchka, Hugh Quarshie, Stella Duffy, Tanya Moodie, Philippa Perry, Jack Monroe and Leila Bertrand |date=27 April 2016 |accessdate=28 April 2016 |title=Give half your votes to equality on 5 May \u2013 WE think that's fair #VoteWE |medium=Video |publisher=Women's Equality Channel via YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0n-6pT0_uso}}</ref> [[Jo Brand]], [[Rosie Boycott]]<ref name=5x15_JBRB>{{cite AV media |people=Catherine Mayer (host), [[Jo Brand]] (guest) and [[Rosie Boycott]] (guest) |date=3 April 2016 |accessdate=28 April 2016 |title=Jo Brand & Rosie Boycott @ 5x15 \u2013 Women's Equality Party |medium=Video |publisher=5x15 Stories via YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G7nFW9YmW_M}}</ref> and [[Caitlin Moran]].<ref name=5x15_CM>{{cite AV media |people=[[Caitlin Moran]] |date=3 April 2016 |accessdate=28 April 2016 |title=Caitlin Moran @ 5x15 \u2013 Women's Equality Party |medium=Video |publisher=5x15 Stories via YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v2VDrDQLbxA}}</ref>\n\nThe WEP did not win any seats in the elections: Walker gained 53,055 votes (2.04%) in the first round of voting for [[2016 London mayoral election#Results|London mayor]].<ref name=Telegraph_070516>{{cite news |last1=Akkoc |first1=Raziye |last2=Riley-Smith |first2=Ben |last3=Wilkinson |first3=Michael |title=London mayor election results: Sadiq Khan 'proud London has chosen hope over fear' as he wins landslide (12.50am Full results and figures) |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/06/london-mayoral-election-results-what-time-will-the-votes-be-coun/ |work=The Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=7 May 2016 |accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> The party's best result was on the [[2016 London Assembly election#List candidates|London-wide list]] where it finished sixth with 91,772 votes (3.5%).<ref name=GLA_060516>{{cite book |last=London Elects |author-link=London Elects |title=2016 GLA elections: election of the London Assembly members |url=https://www.londonelects.org.uk/sites/default/files/London-wide%20Assembly%20Member%20results%202016.pdf |publisher=[[London Elects]] |date=7 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAnne Beetham gained 2,091 votes (0.8%) in [[Glasgow (Scottish Parliament electoral region)#Additional member results|Glasgow]]<ref name=BBCGlasgowElect_2016>{{cite news |title=Scotland election 2016: Glasgow results |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/scotland-regions/S17000010 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> and Lee Chalmers gained 3,877 votes (1.2%) in [[Lothian (Scottish Parliament electoral region)#Additional member results|Lothian]].<ref name=BBCLothianElect_2016>{{cite news |title=Scotland election 2016: Lothian results |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/scotland-regions/S17000012 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=Scotland_2016>{{cite web |title=Our results from Scotland |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/our_results_from_scotland |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> Overall the WEP obtained 5,968 votes, 0.3% of the Scottish vote.<ref name=BBCScotElect_2016>{{cite news |title=Scotland election 2016: results |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2016/scotland/results |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nSharon Lovell, Emma Rose, Sarah Rees and Ruth Williams gained 2,807 votes, 1.2% of the total vote in [[South Wales Central (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|South Wales Central]].<ref name=Wales_2016>{{cite web |title=Our results from Wales |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/our_results_from_wales |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=BBCWalesElect_2016>{{cite news |title=Wales election 2016: South Wales Central |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/wales-regions/W10000007 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe overall total number of votes cast for the party in Scotland, Wales and London was 350,000.<ref name=Independent_070516>{{cite news |last1=Cooper |first1=Charlie |last2=Forster |first2=Katie |title=Women's Equality Party gets more than 350,000 votes and beats George Galloway in London |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/womens-equality-party-350000-votes-george-galloway-london-council-elections-a7018451.html |work=The Independent |date=7 May 2016 |accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 ===\nTabitha Morton from [[Netherton, Merseyside|Netherton]] stood in the [[2017 Liverpool City Region mayoral election|Liverpool City Region mayoral election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet your candidate: Tabitha Morton |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/tabitha_morton |website=womensequality.org.uk |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=20 February 2017 |accessdate=20 March 2017}}<br />- {{cite news |last=Perraudin |first=Frances |title=The mayoral candidate fighting for women in the northern powerhouse: 'We need a better deal' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/shortcuts/2017/mar/13/mayor-northern-powerhouse-womens-equality-party-tabitha-morton-liverpool |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=13 March 2017 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> She came seventh, receiving 4,287 first round votes (1.5%).<ref>Liverpool City Region Combined Authority: [http://liverpoolcityregionelects.org/results/ Results]. Retrieved 29 May 2017.</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] the party stood seven candidates. None were elected, and all lost their deposits. The best result among them was by Sophie Walker coming fourth in [[Shipley (UK Parliament constituency)|Shipley]] against the sitting [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP [[Philip Davies]], a men's rights and anti-political correctness campaigner.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39683982 |title=General election 2017: Women's Equality Party leader to challenge MP Philip Davies |publisher=BBC News |date=23 April 2017 |accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> The party targeted Davies's seat because of his role in blocking legislation that would have implemented better support for domestic violence victims, and because of his public comments about women, people with disabilities and LGBT people. Academics Emily Harmer and Rosalynd Southern write that: \"Targeting Davies was controversial due to fears over potential vote-splitting and the fact that the WEP failed to engage with local feminist groups\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=More Stable than Strong: Women's Representation, Voters and Issues|first1=Emily|last1=Harmer|first2=Rosalynd|last2=Southern|journal=Parliamentary Affairs|year=2018|volume=71|issue=s1|pages=237\u2013254|doi=10.1093/pa/gsx072}}</ref> The full list of WEP candidates in the 2017 general election is below:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Constituency\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! %\n! Source(s)\n|-\n| [[Hornsey and Wood Green (UK Parliament constituency)|Hornsey and Wood Green]]\n| [[Nimco Ali]]\n| 551\n| 0.9\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000752 |title=Hornsey & Wood Green |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Manchester Withington (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Withington]]\n| Sally Carr\n| 234\n| 0.4\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000809 |title=Manchester Withington |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Shipley (UK Parliament constituency)|Shipley]]\n| [[Sophie Walker]]\n| 1,040\n| 1.9\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000925|title=Shipley |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Stirling (UK Parliament constituency)|Stirling]]\n| Kirstein Rummery\n| 337\n| 0.7\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/S14000057 |title=Stirling |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tunbridge Wells (UK Parliament constituency)|Tunbridge Wells]]\n| Celine Thomas\n| 702\n| 1.3\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001004 |title=Tunbridge Wells |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Vale of Glamorgan (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of Glamorgan]]\n| Sharon Lovell\n| 177\n| 0.3\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/W07000078 |title=Vale of Glamorgan |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Vauxhall (UK Parliament constituency)|Vauxhall]]\n| Harini Iyengar\n| 539\n| 1.0\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001008 |title=Vauxhall |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== 2018 ===\nThe party put up candidates in more than 30 elections in the [[2018 United Kingdom local elections|local elections of 2018]].{{ref|Timeline1|Note 1}}<ref name=\"Local_2018\">{{cite web |title=Local election results: WE candidates on the march |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/local_election_18 |website=womensequality.org.uk |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=4 May 2018 |access-date=17 May 2018}}</ref> None were elected.\n\nMandu Reid stood as a candidate for the WEP in the [[2018 Lewisham East by-election]]; she came fifth out of the 14 candidates, receiving 506 votes (2.3%).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lewisham East constituency by-election on 14 June 2018 |url=https://www.lewisham.gov.uk/mayorandcouncil/elections/results/Pages/Lewisham-East-by-election-results-2018.aspx |publisher=[[Lewisham London Borough Council]] |date=14 June 2018 |access-date=25 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 ===\nThe party put up candidates in more than 20 elections in the [[2019 United Kingdom local elections|local elections of 2019]].{{ref|Timeline2|Note 2}} The party saw its first Councillor, Kay Wesley, elected to [[Congleton Town Council]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Equality Party elects its first Councillor|url=https://www.womensequality.org.uk/local_election_19 |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=2 May 2019 |access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref> 33% of Congleton East voters gave one of their votes to the sole Women's Equality Party candidate, which got 1250 votes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Congleton Town Council East Ward Results 2019|url=https://www.cheshireeast.gov.uk/council_and_democracy/voting_and_elections/elections/parish-council-election-2019/calveley-to-faddiley/congleton-east.aspx |publisher=[[Cheshire East Council]] |date=2 May 2019 |access-date=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Constituency\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! %\n! Source(s)\n|-\n| [[Bury South (UK Parliament constituency)|Bury South]]\n| Gemma Evans\n| 130\n| 0.3\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000612|title=Bury South parliamentary election|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Luton North (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton North]]\n| Serena Laidley\n| 149\n| 0.3\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000800|title=Luton North parliamentary election|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Dover (UK Parliament constituency)|Dover]]\n| Eljai Morais\n| 137\n| 0.3\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000670|title=Dover parliamentary election|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\nThese constituencies have previously had an [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] suspended from his respective party because of allegations of sexual assault or harassment, although all three MPs that had been accused will not be seeking re-election. Two prospective candidates in [[Sheffield Hallam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Hallam]] and the [[Cities of London and Westminster (UK Parliament constituency)|Cities of London and Westminster]] stood aside to support the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] after they agreed to implement a WEP Policy to eject MPs guilty of harassment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/12/womens-equality-party-stands-aside-for-lib-dems-in-two-seats|title=Women's Equality party stands aside for Lib Dems in two seats|last=Quinn|first=Ben|date=12 November 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=30 November 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 ===\nIn January 2020, Mandu Reid was announced as the party leader following her role as interim leader since early 2019. The party are currently standing 26 candidates in the [[2020 London Assembly election]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womensequality.org.uk/gla_2020_candidates|title=GLA 2020 Candidates - Women's Equality Party|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> elections which is set to take place on 7 May 2020. Reid is the party's candidate for the [[2020 London mayoral election]], having replaced Sue Black, who had to withdraw for health reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/16/womens-equality-party-candidate-pulls-out-of-london-mayoral-race|title=Women's Equality party candidate pulls out of London mayoral race|first=Kate|last=Proctor|work=The Guardian|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Membership and local organisations==\nReportedly, 1,300 people joined the party on the day that it opened up membership, which costs \u00a34 per month.<ref name=Cohen/> In the first financial year, the party raised \u00a3512,219 in membership fees.<ref name=Accounts_2015>{{cite book |last=Da Soller |first=Samantha |title=Women's Equality Party Limited Annual Report and Financial Statements for the period ended 31 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404133854/http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/Api/Accounts/Documents/18498 |archive-date=4 April 2017 |url=http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/Api/Accounts/Documents/18498 |publisher=[[Electoral Commission]] |date=7 June 2016}}</ref> {{As of|2015|10|13}}, 65 local and regional Women's Equality Party groups had been founded,<ref name=Guardian_131015 /> and {{as of|2016|07|lc=y}} the party reported that it had 65,000 members.<ref name=Newsweek_290716>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Sophie |author-link= |title=How to solve the Labour Party's women problem |url=http://europe.newsweek.com/when-misogyny-becomes-mass-ogyny-485295 |work=[[Newsweek|Newsweek Europe]] |publisher=[[IBT Media]] |date=29 July 2016 |accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_130317\">{{cite news |last=Perraudin |first=Frances |title=The mayoral candidate fighting for women in the northern powerhouse: 'We need a better deal' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/shortcuts/2017/mar/13/mayor-northern-powerhouse-womens-equality-party-tabitha-morton-liverpool |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=13 March 2017 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> The WEP was described as \"the fastest growing political force in the UK\" in a ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]'' article on the party's campaigning for the [[2016 London mayoral election|May 2016 London mayoral election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/nudity-cats-and-doorstep-politics-welcome-to-election-canvassing/ |title=Nudity, cats and doorstep politics: Welcome to election canvassing \u2013 Women's Equality Party style |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Claire |last=Cohen |date=5 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> The party's membership reportedly grew from 25,000 to 55,000 in the month following the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|European Union membership referendum]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Brexit as a scandal: gender and global trumpism |first1=Aida A. |last1=Hozi\u0107 |first2=Jacqui |last2=True |author-link2=Jacqui True |journal=Review of International Political Economy |volume=24 |issue=2 |pages=270\u2013287 |year=2017 |doi=10.1080/09692290.2017.1302491}}</ref>\n\n== Fundraising and donations ==\nThe party's first [[fundraiser]], held in front of 400 people, including businesswoman [[Martha Lane Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho|Martha Lane Fox]], took place at Conway Hall on 9 June 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Staff writer |title=Londoner's Diary: Women are on the march with Sandi Toksvig |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/londoners-diary-women-are-on-the-march-with-sandi-toksvig-10310538.html |work=London Evening Standard |location=London |date=10 June 2015 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McLaren |first=Leah |author-link=Leah McLaren |title=Can a party for women, and by women, make it in Britain? |url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/worldpolitics/can-a-party-for-women-and-by-women-make-it-in-britain/ |work=[[Maclean's]] |publisher=[[Rogers Media|Rogers Media, Inc.]] |location=Canada |date=18 June 2015 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> In September that year Toksvig announced the dates for a comedy tour to raise funds for the party.<ref>{{cite news |last=Duffy |first=Nick |title=Sandi Toksvig launches comedy tour to raise funds for new political party |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/09/29/sandi-toksvig-launches-comedy-tour-to-raise-funds-for-new-political-party/ |work=[[PinkNews]] |publisher= |date=29 September 2015 |access-date=29 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=Times_290915>{{cite news |last=Nixey |first=Catherine |title=Sandi Toksvig on swapping The News Quiz for the Women's Equality Party |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/article4570067.ece |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=[[News UK]] |url-access=subscription |date=29 September 2015 |access-date=29 September 2015}}</ref> In the party's first year (ending 31 December 2015) \u00a3512,219 was raised through membership fees, \u00a338,528 through fundraising activities and \u00a379,212 was raised through donations.<ref name=Accounts_2015 />\n\nThe artist [[Damien Hirst]] created a piece of work for auction entitled \"Spin Drawing for Women's Equality\" (2015).<ref name=Art_160316>{{cite news |last=Gerlis |first=Melanie |title=Damien Hirst, suffragette, spins with a twist |url=http://theartnewspaper.com/news/damien-hirst-suffragette-spins-with-a-twist/ |work=[[The Art Newspaper]] |publisher=Umberto Allemandi |date=16 March 2016}}</ref> The piece, which contained the party's colours, raised \u00a320,000 when it was auctioned in April 2016. The artists [[Jake and Dinos Chapman]] also began a campaign, stamping the words \"Womens Equality Party\" onto [[Two pence (British decimal coin)|2p coins]] and then returning them into circulation.<ref name=SunTelegraph_240416>{{cite news |last=Furness |first=Hannah |title=The male artists risking jail to revive Suffragettes' spirit |url=http://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-sunday-telegraph/20160424/281771333374824 |work=[[The Sunday Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=24 April 2016 |access-date=27 April 2016}}</ref> ([[Suffragette]]s had also defaced pennies.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC - A History of the World - Object: Suffragette-defaced penny |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/iVUVhaKVREWjsHrr9IoOOA |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>)\n\nIn the party's second year (ending 31 December 2016) \u00a3447,946 was raised through membership fees, \u00a335,918 through fundraising activities and \u00a3261,394 was raised through donations.<ref name=Accounts_2016>{{cite book |last=Keshet |first=Shendi |title=Women's Equality Party Limited Annual Report and Financial Statements for the period ended 31 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914100704/http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/Api/Accounts/Documents/19410 |archive-date=14 September 2017 |url=http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/Api/Accounts/Documents/19410 |publisher=[[Electoral Commission]] |date=1 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nA year prior to the creation of the WEP, Suzanne Moore suggested in ''[[The Guardian]]'' that a feminist party should be formed, saying: \"the false doctrine of austerity has meant that women, single mothers in particular, and public sector workers in general, have been at the frontline of this war. They have been demonised and subject to punitive cuts.\"<ref name=Moore_090714>{{cite news |last=Moore |first=Suzanne |author-link=Suzanne Moore |title=Harriet Harman is right about sexism in politics \u2013 let's start a feminist party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jul/09/harriet-harman-sexism-politics-feminist-party |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=9 July 2014 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> Writing in ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', Kate Maltby responded by saying, \"My feminism is directly tied to a commitment to meritocracy and individual flourishing...if her [Moore's] grand new feminist party kicks off by nationalising private property, I'm hardly going to be able to sign up\".<ref name=Maltby_110714>{{cite news |last=Maltby |first=Kate |title=Suzanne Moore, please don't ruin feminism by starting a feminist party |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/katemaltby/100279483/suzanne-moore-please-dont-ruin-feminism-by-starting-a-feminist-party/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716061143/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/katemaltby/100279483/suzanne-moore-please-dont-ruin-feminism-by-starting-a-feminist-party/ |archivedate=16 July 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=11 July 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe British edition of ''[[GQ]]'' has also accused the party of \"alienating 50 per cent of the electorate\", adding that, \"while the WEP may aim to appeal to both female Tory voters and female Labour voters, it doesn't take away from the implicit suggestion that the party \u2013 which aims for 'diverse' membership \u2013 is still aimed almost solely at women\".<ref name=Carr_190815>{{cite news |last=Carr |first=Flora |title=The Women's Equality Party is alienating men |url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/comment/articles/2015-08/19/womens-equality-party-alienating-men-sandy-toksvig |work=[[GQ]] (UK edition) |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |date=19 August 2015 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> The party has also been criticised \"for being {{sic|comprised |hide=y|mainly of}} white, middle-class affluent women\".<ref>{{cite journal |first=Elizabeth |last=Evans |title=Intersectionality as feminist praxis in the UK |journal=[[Women's Studies International Forum]] |year=2016 |volume=59 |pages=67\u201375 |doi=10.1016/j.wsif.2016.10.004|url=http://research.gold.ac.uk/19038/1/October%20revised%20-%20Intersectionality%20as%20feminist%20praxis.doc }}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Union of Sex Workers]] have criticised the party stance on the criminalisation of commercial sex.<ref>https://www.iusw.org/2015/10/iusw-condemns-womens-equality-partys-harmful-choice-to-seek-criminalisation-of-commercial-sex/</ref>\n\nThe party has also been accused of being \"both too ambitious and not ambitious enough\", that, in order to maintain traction, it ought to concentrate on just one issue, e.g., quotas in the boardroom.<ref name=Guardian_211015b>{{cite news |last=Perkins |first=Anne |title=Two cheers for the Women's Equality party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/oct/21/womens-equality-party-politics |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=21 October 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral performance==\n\n===Westminster elections===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Year !! Candidates !! Total votes !! % of total vote !! Change !! Average vote<ref>Average vote per candidate.</ref> !! Average % vote !! Saved Deposits !! Number of MPs !! Change\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Women's Equality Party/meta/color}}\" |\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]\n|| 7 || 3,580 || 0.0% || ''n/a'' || 511 || 0.9% || 0 || 0 || {{nochange}} \n|}\n\n===London Mayoral elections===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Date\n!| Popular Vote\n!| % of Vote\n!| Change\n!| Place\n!| Notes\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Women's Equality Party/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[2016 London mayoral election|2016]] || 53,055 || 2.0% || ''n/a'' || 6th || \n|}\n\n===London Assembly elections===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Date\n!| Regional Vote\n!| % of Vote\n!| Change\n!| AMs\n!| Change\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Women's Equality Party/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[2016 London Assembly election|'''2016''']] || 91,772 || 3.5% || ''n/a'' || 0 || {{nochange}} \n|}\n\n===National Assembly for Wales elections===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Date\n!| Regional Vote\n!| % of Vote\n!| Change\n!| AMs\n!| Change\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Women's Equality Party/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|'''2016''']] || 2,807 || 0.3% || ''n/a'' || 0 || {{nochange}} \n|}\n\n===Scottish Parliament elections===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Date\n!| Regional Vote\n!| % of Vote\n!| Change\n!| MSPs\n!| Change\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Women's Equality Party/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[2016 Scottish Parliament election|'''2016''']] || 5,968 || 0.3% || ''n/a'' || 0 || {{nochange}} \n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Feminism in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Notes ==\n:{{note label|Timeline1|Note 1}}\n:* <small>Janet Baker, [[2018 Lambeth London Borough Council election#Brixton Hill|Brixton Hill ward]], Lambeth \u00b7 Ann Butler, [[2018 Sheffield City Council election#Walkley|Walkley ward]], Sheffield \u00b7 Diane Coffey, [[2018 Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council election#Heatons North|Heatons North ward]], Stockport \u00b7 Cat Crossley, [[2018 City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council election#Baildon ward|Baildon ward]], Bradford \u00b7 Claire Empson, [[2018 Southwark London Borough Council election#Goose Green|Goose Green ward]], Southwark \u00b7 Leila Fazal, [[2018 Lambeth London Borough Council election#Ferndale|Ferndale ward]], Lambeth \u00b7 Bea Gare, [[2018 Exeter City Council election#Duryard & St.James|Duryard & St James ward]], Exeter \u00b7 Tulip Hambleton, [[2018 Enfield London Borough Council election#Town|Town ward]], Enfield \u00b7 Jo Heathcote, [[2018 Manchester City Council election#Chorlton|Chorlton ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Eleanor Hemmens, [[2018 Lambeth London Borough Council election#Prince's|Prince's ward]], Lambeth \u00b7 Harini Iyengar, [[Mayor of Hackney#2018|Mayor of Hackney]] (and also [[2018 Hackney London Borough Council election#Dalston|Dalston ward]], Hackney) \u00b7 Louise Jennings, [[2018 Leeds City Council election#Headingley & Hyde Park|Headingley and Hyde Park ward]], Leeds \u00b7 Sam Johnson, [[2018 Manchester City Council election#Deansgate|Deansgate ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Emma Ko, [[2018 Brent London Borough Council election#Queens Park|Queens Park ward]], Brent \u00b7 Jean Laight, [[2018 Harrogate Borough Council election#Harrogate St Georges|St. Georges ward]], Harrogate \u00b7 Jessie Macneil-Brown, [[2018 Tower Hamlets London Borough Council election#Bethnal Green|Bethnal Green ward]], Tower Hamlets \u00b7 Alison Marshall, [[2018 Islington London Borough Council election#Highbury West|Highbury West ward]], Islington \u00b7 Caroline MacVay, [[2018 Bromley London Borough Council election#Plaistow and Sundridge|Plaistow and Sundridge ward]], Bromley \u00b7 Rebecca Manson Jones, [[2018 Lewisham London Borough Council election#Ladywell|Ladywell ward]], Lewisham \u00b7 Liz Orr, [[2018 Tunbridge Wells Borough Council election#Culverden|Culverden ward]], Tunbridge Wells \u00b7 Caroline Rayfield, [[2018 Richmond upon Thames London Borough Council election#Twickenham Riverside|Twickenham Riverside ward]], Richmond \u00b7 Mandu Reid, [[2018 Lewisham London Borough Council election#Lewisham Central|Lewisham Central ward]], Lewisham \u00b7 Pamela Richie, [[2018 Greenwich London Borough Council election#Charlton|Charlton ward]], Greenwich \u00b7 Eileen Scholes, [[2018 Southwark London Borough Council election#Borough & Bankside|Borough & Bankside ward]], Southwark \u00b7 Helen Shay, [[2018 Harrogate Borough Council election#Harrogate Stray|Stray ward]], Harrogate \u00b7 Amanda Shribman, [[2018 Barnet London Borough Council election#West Finchley|West Finchley ward]], Barnet \u00b7 Leisa Taylor, [[2018 Worcester City Council election#Bedwardine|Bedwardine ward]], Worcester \u00b7 Wendy Thomson, [[2018 Reading Borough Council election#Peppard|Peppard ward]], Reading \u00b7 Nikki Uppal, [[2018 Islington London Borough Council election#Hillrise|Hillrise ward]], Islington \u00b7 Kate Vang, [[2018 Lewisham London Borough Council election#Brockley|Brockley ward]], Lewisham</small>\n\n:{{note label|Timeline2|Note 2}}\n:* <small>Nicke Adebowale, [[Lewisham London Borough Council elections#2018-2022|Evelyn ward (by-election)]], Lewisham \u00b7 Hannah Barham-Brown, [[2019 Leeds City Council election#Roundhay|Roundhay ward]], Leeds \u00b7 Beverly Barstow, [[2019 Brighton and Hove City Council election#Hanover and Elm Grove|Hanover and Elm Grove ward]], Brighton and Hove \u00b7 Vinice Bridget Cowell, [[2019 Southend-on-Sea Borough Council election#Chalkwell|Chalkwell ward]], Southend-on-Sea \u00b7 Priya Brown, [[2019 Basingstoke and Deane Borough Council election#Eastrop|Eastrop ward]], Basingstoke and Deane \u00b7 Jen Bryan, [[Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council election, 2019#Heatons North|Heatons North ward]], Stockport \u00b7 Samantha Days, [[Manchester City Council election, 2019#Crumpsall|Crumpsall ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Sally Duffin, [[2019 City of York Council election#Heworth Ward|Heworth ward]], York \u00b7 Bea Gare, [[2019 Exeter City Council election#Duryard & St. James|Duryard & St. James ward]], Exeter \u00b7 Amy Gooding, [[Sheffield City Council election, 2019#Walkley|Walkley ward]], Sheffield \u00b7 Cairis Grant-Hickey, [[Lewisham London Borough Council elections#2018-2022|Whitefoot ward (by-election)]], Lewisham \u00b7 Jo Heathcote, [[Manchester City Council election, 2019#Chorlton|Chorlton ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Caroline Hunt, [[2019 Leeds City Council election#Headingley & Hyde Park|Headingley & Hyde Park ward]], Leeds \u00b7 Louise Jennings, [[Leeds City Council election, 2019#Alwoodley|Alwoodley ward]], Leeds \u00b7 Sam Johnson, [[Manchester City Council election, 2019#Deansgate|Deansgate ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Jessie MacNeil-Brown, [[2019 Brighton and Hove City Council election#Central Hove|Central Hove ward]], Brighton and Hove \u00b7 Liz Orr, [[Tunbridge Wells Borough Council election, 2019#Culverden|Culverden ward]], Tunbridge Wells \u00b7 Sarika Paul, [[Manchester City Council election, 2019#Didsbury West|Didsbury West ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Erika Raffle-Currie, [[2019 Liverpool City Council election#Childwall|Childwall ward]], Liverpool \u00b7 Kanndiss Riley, [[2019 Thanet District Council election#Cliftonville East|Cliftonville East ward]], Thanet \u00b7 Megan Senior, [[Sheffield City Council election, 2019#Ecclesall|Ecclesall ward]], Sheffield \u00b7 Leisa Taylor, [[Worcester City Council election, 2019#Bedwardine|Bedwardine ward]], Worcester \u00b7 Celine Thomas, [[Tunbridge Wells Borough Council election, 2019#Pantiles & St Mark's|Pantiles & St Mark's ward]], Tunbridge Wells \u00b7 Louise Timlin, [[2019 Wokingham Borough Council election#Ward results|Evendons ward]], Wokingham \u00b7 Kay Wesley, [[2019 Cheshire East Council election#Congleton East|Congleton East ward]], Cheshire East (and Kay Wesley, [[Congleton Town Council]]) \u00b7 Jane Whild, [[2019 Milton Keynes Council election#Ward Results|Campbell Park & Old Woughton ward]], Milton Keynes \u00b7 Annie Wood, [[2019 Salford City Council election#Eccles|Eccles ward]], Salford</small>\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite news |last=Beaty |first=Zoe |title=Hope: How to build a feminist political party |trans-title=''Online title'': Just who are the Women's Equality Party and what do they stand for? |url=http://www.stylist.co.uk/life/who-are-the-womens-equality-party-and-what-do-they-stand-for-policies-pay-parenting-education |work=[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]] |issue=310 |pages=26\u201327, 29\u201330 |publisher=Shortlist Media |date=23 March 2016}}\n*{{cite news |last=Cohen |first=Nick |author-link=Nick Cohen |title=Why the Women's Equality party is long overdue |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/sep/27/womens-equality-party-long-overdue |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=27 September 2015}}\n*{{cite journal|first1=Elizabeth|last1=Evans|first2=Meryl|last2=Kenny|title=The Women's Equality Party: Emergence, Organisation and Challenges|journal=Political Studies|year=2019|volume=67|issue=4|pages=855\u2013871|doi=10.1177/0032321718812885|url=https://research.gold.ac.uk/24750/1/Final%20Manuscript%20.doc}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n*{{Official website|http://www.womensequality.org.uk/}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/pages/The-Womens-Equality-Party/1567955710156124 Party-wide Facebook page]\n\n{{British political parties}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Women's Equality Party}}\n[[Category:2015 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Feminist parties in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Pro-European political parties in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the UK political party|the New York based political party|Women's Equality Party (New York)}}\n{{short description|UK political party}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| country = United Kingdom\n| name = Women's Equality Party\n| logo = WEP logo.JPG\n| abbreviation = WE (or WEP)\n| founders = [[Sandi Toksvig]]<br />[[Catherine Mayer]]\n| leader1_title = Leader\n| leader1_name = [[Mandu Reid]]\n| foundation = {{start date|df=yes|2015|03|02}}\n| headquarters = 2 Tunstall Road<br>London<br>SW9 8BN\n| membership_year = September 2018\n| membership = 45,000<ref>{{cite news |last=Agerholm |first=Harriet |title=Final Say: Leader of Women's Equality Party backs the Independent's campaign |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/final-say-womens-equality-party-sophie-walker-peoples-vote-second-referendum-a8528296.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=8 September 2018 |access-date=8 September 2018}}</ref>\n| ideology = {{Nowrap|[[Feminism]]<br />[[Egalitarianism]]<br />[[Pro-Europeanism]]<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1194163519769522177|user=WEP_UK|date=12 December 2019|title=BREAKING: WE are thrilled to announce that the @LibDems have adopted our key policies on ending #abuse in their manifesto. Following this, WE will be standing down in Cities of London & Westminster and Sheffield Hallam to help them campaign against #Brexit}}</ref>}}\n| euopean = \n| europarl = \n| affiliation1_title = \n| affiliation1 = [[Progressive Alliance]]\n| colours = {{Color box|{{Women's Equality Party (UK)/meta/color2}}|border=darkgray}} Purple<br/>{{Color box|{{Women's Equality Party (UK)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} Green\n''[[Women's Social and Political Union|WSPU]] colours''\n| website = http://womensequality.org.uk/\n| colorcode = {{Women's Equality Party (UK)/meta/color}}\n| seats1_title = [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|0|650|hex=#993366}}\n| seats2_title = [[House of Lords]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|724|hex=#993366}}\n| seats3_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|0|73|hex=#993366}}\n| seats8_title = [[Local government in the United Kingdom|Local government]]\n| seats8 = {{Composition bar|1|21259|hex=#993366}}<!--Parish and town councillors do not count to this total, this is for principal authority seats-->\n}}\n\nThe '''Women's Equality Party''' is a [[List of feminist parties|feminist political party]] set up in the United Kingdom in 2015. The idea was conceived by [[Catherine Mayer]] and [[Sandi Toksvig]] at the [[Women of the World Festival]], when they concluded that there was a need for a party to campaign for [[gender equality]] to the benefit of all. The launch meeting was on 28 March 2015 under the title \"The Women's Equality Party needs you. But probably not as much as you need the Women's Equality Party\". The party's full policy was launched by its then leader, [[Sophie Walker]], at [[Conway Hall Ethical Society#Conway Hall|Conway Hall]], on 20 October 2015. In January 2020, [[Mandu Reid]] took over as party leader.\n\n== History ==\n{{multiple image| direction = vertical | width = 100 | footer = Co-founders of the Women's Equality Party | image1 = CatherineMayerPortrait.jpg | alt1 = | caption1 = [[Catherine Mayer]] | image2 = Sandi Toksvig in 2009.jpg | alt2 = | caption2 = [[Sandi Toksvig]] | align = left}}\nOn 2 March 2015, author and journalist [[Catherine Mayer]] attended a \"Women in Politics\" event at the [[Women of the World Festival]] (at the [[Southbank Centre]] in central London). The panel was chaired by [[Jude Kelly]] (Artistic Director, Southbank Centre), and the panel consisted of [[Katie Ghose]] (CEO, [[Electoral Reform Society]]), [[Margot James]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]), [[Stella Creasy]] ([[Labour Co-operative|Labour]]) and [[Jo Swinson]] ([[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Lib Dem]]).<ref name=Artefact>{{cite news |last1=Madberg |first1=Astrid |last2=Turnley |first2=Molly |title=Highlights from WOW 2015: Women in Politics, 2 March 2015 |url=https://www.artefactmagazine.com/2015/03/19/highlights-from-wow-2015/ |work=Artefact Magazine |date=19 March 2015 |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref> Having watched the panelists agreeing collegially with each other on almost every point, Mayer stood up and said, \"What about if I found a Women's Equality Party, tell you what, I'm going to go to the bar afterwards, anyone interested in discussing this come and see me.\"<ref name=Milligan>{{cite episode |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02pty5g |title=The brand new Women's Equality Party: 'not standing in this election' |series=[[PM (BBC Radio 4)|PM]] |last1=Milligan |first1=Becky |date=23 April 2015 |station=BBC Radio 4 |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2015 ([[International Women's Day]]), at the same festival, comedian [[Sandi Toksvig]] presented an event entitled \"Sandi Toksvig's Mirth Control: Stand Up and Be Counted\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Sandi Toksvig's mirth control: stand up and be counted, Royal Festival Hall, Southbank Centre, 8 March 2015 |url=http://www.southbankcentre.co.uk/whatson/mirth-control-89533 |publisher=[[Southbank Centre]] |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref> Interviewed by [[Jenni Murray]] on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Woman's Hour]]'', Toksvig said: \"I had a fantasy cabinet of women, and I didn't care which party they came from, we had [[Doreen Lawrence]] as our [[Home Secretary]]. Can you imagine anything more wonderful? We had [[Paralympics|paralympian]] [[Tanni Grey-Thompson]] as our [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport|Sports Minister]], and I asked them to put forward practical suggestions. The world is in a parlous state, 9.1 million women failed to vote in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|last election]], we need to attract them, we also need to attract the more than 7 million men who didn't vote. Why are people not engaged in politics, because I don't think that the people standing represent the diversity of this country.\"<ref name=W_Hour>{{cite episode |last1=Murray |first1=Jenni (host) |author-link1=Jenni Murray |last2=Toksvig |first2=Sandi (guest) |author-link2=Sandi Toksvig |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b05s3gyy |title=Sandi Toksvig interview |series=[[Woman's Hour]] |minutes=00:30 |date=30 April 2015 |station=BBC Radio 4 |accessdate=25 September 2015}}</ref> Mayer phoned Toksvig, and the two agreed to become co-founders of the party.<ref name=Cocozza>{{cite news |last=Cocozza |first=Paula |title=Women's Equality party founders: 'It needed doing. So we said, \"Let's do it\"' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/28/womens-equality-party-founders-it-needed-doing-so-we-said-lets-do-it-sandi-toksvig |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=28 August 2015 |accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first meeting of the as yet unnamed party was on 28 March 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/events/362216697294937/ |title=The Women's Equality Party needs you |last1= |first1= |website=Facebook |date= |accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=Artefact /><ref>{{cite web |title=First #WE meeting |url=https://womensequality.org.uk/news/2015/03/02/first-we-meeting/ |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=2 March 2015 |accessdate=25 September 2015}}</ref> Speakers included: [[Suzanne Moore]], who had previously stood for parliament as an independent candidate; [[Sophie Walker]], who spoke on careers, parenting and ensuring that both parents have opportunities in both; [[Halla Gunnarsd\u00f3ttir]], who described a [[Women's List|women's equality party in Iceland]]; and [[Hannah McGrath]], who discussed the practicalities of starting a party. The meeting was covered on ''Woman's Hour''<ref name=W_Hour /> and by the press, including ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' magazine<ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Ella |title=Will you support the Women's Equality Party? |url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/news/features/2015/04/02/womens-equality-party-formed-by-catherine-mayer-policies-and-background |work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |location=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast|Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications]] |date=2 April 2015 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> and the ''[[London Evening Standard]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Staff writer |title=Londoner's Diary: Women's party is ready to be a player |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/londoners-diary-womens-party-is-ready-to-be-a-player-10189809.html |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |location=London |date=20 April 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{external media |topic=TEDx talk by Sandi Toksvig |video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r92jUj7gNRw ''A political party for women's equality''] via [[TEDx|TEDx Talks]] on [[YouTube]]<ref name=\"C-SPAN\">{{cite AV media |people=[[Sandi Toksvig]] |date=October 2016 |accessdate=22 March 2017 |title=A political party for women's equality |medium=Video |publisher=[[TEDx|TEDx Talks]] via [[YouTube]] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r92jUj7gNRw}}\n:Toksvig tells the story of how she helped start a new political party in Britain, the Women's Equality Party, with the express purpose of putting equality on the ballot.</ref>}}\nA second meeting took place at [[Conway Hall]] on 18 April, and included Sandi Toksvig, [[Mandy Colleran]], [[Nimko Ali]], [[Shabnam Shabazi]] and [[Stella Duffy]] as speakers.<ref name=Milligan />\n\nOn 30 April, Toksvig announced that she was leaving her position as comp\u00e8re of Radio 4's ''[[The News Quiz]]'' in order to help set up the new [[political party]], which was now named the Women's Equality Party.<ref name=Topping>{{cite news |last=Topping |first=Alexandra |title=Sandi Toksvig reveals she quit Radio 4 to set up women's rights political party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/30/sandi-toksvig-quit-radio-4-news-quiz-set-up-womens-rights-political-party |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=30 April 2015 |access-date=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Furness>{{cite news |last=Furness |first=Hannah |title=Sandi Toksvig quit The News Quiz for Women's Equality Party |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/bbc/11574333/Sandi-Toksvig-quit-The-News-Quiz-for-Womens-Equality-Party.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Guest |first=Katy |title=Sandi Toksvig's Women's Equality Party is a movement for which time has come |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/sandi-toksvigs-womens-equality-party-is-a-movement-for-which-time-has-come-10221200.html |work=[[The Independent]] |publisher=Independent Print Ltd |date=2 May 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> Speaking at the [[Hay Festival]] in May, Toksvig reported that since she had announced the move on BBC One's ''[[The One Show]]'', she had been subjected to a significant level of [[cyberbullying|abuse online]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Elgot |first=Jessica |title=Sandi Toksvig: trolls are already out over plans to form Women's Equality party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/25/sandi-toksvig-trolls-womens-equality-party-bbc-abuse |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=25 May 2015 |accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Women's Equality Party was registered with the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] on 20 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/English/Registrations/PP2755 |title=Women's Equality Party |publisher=Electoral Commission |accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> On 22 July, [[Reuters]] journalist Sophie Walker was announced as the party's first leader.<ref name=Cocozza /><ref name=Cohen>{{cite news |last=Cohen |first=Claire |title=Watch out Cameron: Meet the leader of Britain's first feminist political party |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-politics/11753983/Womens-Equality-Party-Meet-politics-new-chief-feminist-leading-it.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=22 July 2015 |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Leadership contest 2018 ===\nThe party announced its first leadership contest in December 2017. Nominations opened on 5 January 2018, and closed on 24 January.<ref name=\"UKevote_Timetable\">{{cite web |title=Timetable |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204184709/https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/timetable |archive-date=4 February 2018 |url=https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/timetable |website=pre.ukevote.uk/we |publisher=Election portal for the Women\u2019s Equality Party Leadership Election |access-date=4 February 2018}}</ref> Two candidates were nominated: interim leader Sophie Walker<ref name=\"UKevote_Profiles1\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Sophie Walker |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204185634/https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/profiles/nzmcvdnn-sophie-walker |archive-date=4 February 2018 |url=https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/profiles/nzmcvdnn-sophie-walker |website=pre.ukevote.uk/we |publisher=Election portal for the Women's Equality Party Leadership Election |access-date=4 February 2018}}</ref> and Magda Devas, who had previously run for the [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] in the Streatham Wells ward in the [[2010 Lambeth London Borough Council election#Streatham Wells|Lambeth London Borough Council election of 2010]] and [[2014 Lambeth London Borough Council election#Streatham Wells|that of 2014]].<ref name=\"UKevote_Profiles2\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Magda Devas |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204185914/https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/profiles/jf2crfgh-magda-devas |archive-date=4 February 2018 |url=https://pre.ukevote.uk/we/profiles/jf2crfgh-magda-devas |website=pre.ukevote.uk/we |publisher=Election portal for the Women's Equality Party Leadership Election |access-date=4 February 2018}}</ref> The ballot opened on 14 February 2018, and closed on 6 March; Walker was declared the winner on 8 March.<ref name=\"UKevote_Timetable\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! %\n! Sources\n|-\n| Magda Devas\n| 550\n| 9.90\n|<ref name=\"UKevote_Results\">{{cite web |title=Declaration of result: Women's Equality Party Leadership Election |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308141643/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/4959/attachments/original/1520460695/results.pdf?1520460695 |archive-date=8 March 2018 |url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/4959/attachments/original/1520460695/results.pdf?1520460695 |website=uk-engage.org |publisher=UK Engage |access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sophie Walker]]\n| 5,002\n| 90.10\n|<ref name=\"UKevote_Results\" />\n|}\n\nWalker was due to serve a five-year term until 2023,<ref name=\"UKevote_Role\">{{cite web |title=Role description: Leader of the Women's Equality Party |url=https://files.ukevote.uk/wep/role_description__we_party_leader_18_12_17.pdf |website=pre.ukevote.uk/we |publisher=Election portal for the Women's Equality Party Leadership Election |access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> but stepped down from her role as leader in January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Syal |first=Rajeev |title=Women's Equality party leader Sophie Walker steps down |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/22/womens-equality-party-leader-sophie-walker-steps-down |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=22 January 2019 |accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> She was replaced by interim leader Mandu Reid, the party's national spokesperson on equal parenting and caregiving, its candidate in the [[2018 Lewisham East by-election]], and the CEO of period poverty charity The Cup Effect.<ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Equality Party announces Interim Leader and London Mayoral Candidate |url=https://www.womensequality.org.uk/new_interim_leader_mayoral_candidate |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=8 March 2019 |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political aims ==\nThe party's mission statement opens with: \"Equality for women isn't a women's issue. When women fulfil their potential, everyone benefits. Equality means better politics, a more vibrant economy, a workforce that draws on the talents of the whole population and a society at ease with itself\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Carrie |last=Lyell |title=Sandi Toksvig launches new political party |url=http://www.divamag.co.uk/category/news/sandi-toksvig-launches-new-political-party.aspx |work=[[Diva (magazine)|Diva]] |publisher=Millivres Prowler Group Ltd. |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote frame|\n* Equal representation in politics and business;\n* Equal representation in education;\n* Equal pay;\n* Equal treatment of women by and in the media;\n* Equal parenting rights;\n* An end to violence against women.\n|Women's Equality Party|six stated goals of the party<ref name=Cohen/>}}\n\nDescribing the six aims Mayer said, \"It's a very narrow palette, we're not looking to be a party that can answer questions about what should be done in the Ukraine, or trying to have a platform on the environment or anything else, we are focusing absolutely narrowly on that equality agenda.\"<ref name=Milligan /> Party leader Walker agreed: \"We won't have policies on other issues. We are going to concentrate, laser-like, on all of the above, to make them happen. And we will welcome people from any other political party that agrees with our values of diversity and inclusivity to work with us.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Sophie |author-link=Sophie Walker |title=Our party's going to reclaim women's equality: help us make it happen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jul/24/womens-equality-party-make-it-happen |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=24 July 2015 |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref> However, Walker promised that the party's working definition of the word \"woman\", as well as more detail of the party's policies, would be covered in its policy launch, following consultation with party members.<ref name=Statesman_220915>{{cite news |last=Speed |first=Barbara |title=Women's Equality Party leader: \"We aim to push ourselves out of business\" |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2015/09/sophie-walker-leader-womens-equality-party-were-only-party-whose-aim-push-ourselves-out-business |work=[[New Statesman]] |publisher=Progressive Media International |date=22 September 2015 |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nEarly indications of what to expect included Walker's call for a gender quota system to select [[Member of parliament#United Kingdom|MP]]s at the following two elections so that equal representation could be achieved in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] by 2025.<ref name=Guardian_131015>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Rowena |last2=Watt |first2=Nicholas |title=Women's Equality party says quotas could achieve balanced Commons in 10 years |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/13/womens-equality-party-says-quotas-could-achieve-balanced-commons-in-10-years |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=13 October 2015 |accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref> Walker also called for six weeks' paid leave, at 90% pay, for both parents after having a baby, as well as an extra 10 months of shared leave at statutory pay.<ref name=Buzz_151015>{{cite news |last=Ashton |first=Emily |title=This new political party wants to give both parents six weeks of paid leave |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/emilyashton/this-new-political-party-wants-to-give-both-parents-six-week#.ve56eBkln |work=[[BuzzFeed]] |publisher=BuzzFeed Inc. |date=15 October 2015 |access-date=16 October 2015}}</ref> Writing in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', Toksvig stated that the party further proposed that [[Employment Tribunal|industrial tribunal]] costs be reduced from over \u00a31,000 to \"\u00a350 for those who can afford it\" in order to \"empower all women to speak out about sexism at work.\"<ref name=Mirror_151015>{{cite news |last=Toksvig |first=Sandi |author-link=Sandi Toksvig |title=Sandi Toksvig: Bosses can turn a blind eye to sexism thanks to new rules |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/sandi-toksvig-bosses-can-turn-6638611 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=15 October 2015 |access-date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe party launched its full set of policies on 20 October 2015 at Conway Hall.<ref name=Policy_launch>{{cite web |title=Women's Equality Party announces first policies and campaigns |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/policy_launch_announcement |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=20 October 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=Guardian_211015a>{{cite news |last=Minter |first=Harriet |title=The Women's Equality Party launch is not a moment too soon |url=https://www.theguardian.com/women-in-leadership/2015/oct/21/the-womens-equality-party-launch-is-not-a-moment-too-soon |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=21 October 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== First party conference ===\nThe inaugural Women's Equality Party conference took place in Manchester on 25\u201327 November 2016,<ref>{{cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |title=Sophie Walker: 'Put a woman in a political race and she is always the outsider' |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/sophie-walker-put-a-woman-in-a-political-race-and-she-is-always-the-outsider-a3403576.html |work=London Evening Standard |location=London |date=24 November 2016 |accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/conference_2016 |title=Conference 2016 |publisher=Women's Equality Party |accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref> with opening speeches by founders Catherine Mayer and Sandi Toksvig on the first day,<ref>{{cite book |last=Women's Equality Party |title=Let's Make History Together: Conference Programme |issue=1 |page=22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329145618/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/1334/attachments/original/1479470574/WE_Party_Conference_Programme_2016.pdf?1479470574 |archive-date=29 March 2017 |url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/1334/attachments/original/1479470574/WE_Party_Conference_Programme_2016.pdf?1479470574 |publisher=Women's Equality Party |location=Manchester |year=2016}}</ref> and Sophie Walker's leader's speech on the second day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sophie Walker's leadership speech |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/sophie_walker_s_leadership_speech |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=27 November 2016 |accessdate=28 November 2016}} [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2j6uMTUKANc Video.]</ref>\n\nMotions carried at the conference include: a motion to expand the UK's definition of [[Hate crime#United Kingdom|hate crime]] to include [[misogyny]]; a motion to strengthen the legislation for carers who need flexible working arrangements; and a motion to fully decriminalise abortion across the UK (the current [[Abortion Act 1967|Abortion Act]] excludes Northern Ireland).<ref>{{cite news |last=Grant |first=Katie |title=Make misogyny a hate crime and decriminalise abortion, Women's Equality Party demands |url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/news/politics/make-misogyny-hate-crime-decriminalise-abortion-womens-equality-party-demands/ |work=[[i (newspaper)|i News]] |location=London |date=27 November 2016 |accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Additional party goal ====\nA seventh goal of the party was added to the existing six at the party's first conference.\n{{Quote frame|\n* Equality in healthcare and medical research.|Women's Equality Party|additional goal of the party.<ref name=Peaker_291116>{{cite news |last=Peaker |first=Hannah ''(chief of staff for WE)'' |title=Why health equality is the next goal for the Women's Equality party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/nov/29/health-equality-goal-womens-equality-party |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=29 November 2016 |accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Second party conference ===\nThe second party conference took place in [[Kettering]] in September 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hinsliff |first=Gaby |author-link=Gaby Hinsliff |title=Is the Women's Equality party too sensible for these extreme times? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/sep/07/womens-equality-party-politics-sophie-walker |work=The Guardian |nopp=yes |page=Opinion |date=7 September 2018 |access-date=25 January 2019}}</ref> Among the motions passed was one supporting the [[People's Vote]] campaign calling for a public vote on the final [[Brexit]] deal between the United Kingdom and the European Union.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conference 2018 Motion Outcomes |url=https://www.womensequality.org.uk/conf_18_motions_results |website=womensequality.org.uk |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=9 September 2018 |access-date=25 January 2019}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20190125170205/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/womensequality/pages/5824/attachments/original/1535466047/Brexit_amended_motion_2018_(1).pdf Text.]</ref>\n\n== The party's name ==\nThe party's name was \"debated and discussed at two public meetings\".<ref name=Duffy_310515>{{cite web |last=Duffy |first=Stella |author-link=Stella Duffy |title=The Women's Equality Party question I keep getting asked... (blog) |url=https://stelladuffy.wordpress.com/2015/05/31/the-womens-equality-party-question-i-keep-getting-asked/ |website=stelladuffy.wordpress.com |publisher=Stella Duffy via WordPress |date=31 May 2015 |accessdate=11 April 2016 }}</ref> When Toksvig was asked why the party was named the Women's Equality Party, rather than just the Equality Party, she answered: \"Because there is a huge issue, women are certainly not equal.... It's time that women, finally, after all these years, what is it, almost a hundred years since we finally got the vote, it's time we stepped up and took our equal place in society.\" She also stated the party's motto, \"Equality is better for everybody\".<ref name=W_Hour /> Mayer has also stated, \"I\u2019m very happy with the name: all genders are joining us and I hope they continue to. More than half the population is living in inequality and that is genuinely not good for everyone, economically or culturally.\"<ref name=Guardian_181015>{{cite news |last=McVeigh |first=Tracy |title=After a whirlwind start, the Women's Equality Party faces its first test \u2013 a call for quotas |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/18/women-equality-party-politics-first-test-quotas |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=18 October 2015 |accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Elections ==\n[[File:Pride in London 2016 - Enthusiastic members of the Women's Equality Party in Trafalgar Square.png|alt=Members of the Women's Equality Party at Trafalgar Square during the Pride in London 2016 parade.|thumb|Members of the Women's Equality Party at [[Trafalgar Square]] during the Pride in London 2016 parade]]\n\n=== 2015 ===\nThe party did not field any candidates in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], but planned to do so when the next election was assumed to be in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=ENG |first=Cafebabel |title=The new UK political party fighting for women's equality |work=[[caf\u00e9babel]] |publisher=[[Erasmus Programme]] |url=http://www.cafebabel.co.uk/politics/article/the-new-uk-political-party-fighting-for-womens-equality.html |date=2 June 2015 |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Staff writer |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-32531750 |title=Sandi Toksvig campaigns for equality with new political party |work=[[BBC News]] |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> Walker told [[BBC Radio Wales]]' ''Sunday Supplement'' programme that the party would be taking a [[Nonpartisanism|non-partisan]] approach to elections, stating that \"We will be undertaking consultations with our members and deciding which seats to target\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Staff writer |title=Women's Equality Party to field candidates in assembly elections |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-33664219 |work=BBC News: Wales politics |publisher=BBC |date=25 July 2015 |access-date=22 September 2015}}</ref> Figures from the party suggested that there was a possibility that an existing [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) might defect to the party before the party contested an election, citing the example of how the [[UK Independence Party]] got its first MPs.<ref name=Milligan/> although this did not happen. Initially Walker neither ruled in or out the possibility of a WEP candidate in the [[2016 London mayoral election]]: \"We'd like to. It's a \u00a320,000 losable deposit, though. If you're [[Zac Goldsmith]] that's not such a big deal but if a woman from a normal background wants to speak out for women and do it with the mayorship, automatically she's almost excluded\". However, in October 2015, the party announced its intention to field candidates in the [[2016 London Assembly election]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Urwin |first=Rosamund |title=Sophie Walker: 'We could have an equal parliament in a decade' |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/sophie-walker-we-could-have-an-equal-parliament-in-a-decade-a3093711.html |work=London Evening Standard |location=London |date=19 October 2015 |accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 ===\nFollowing various fundraisers, the party was able to field candidates in the 2016 London elections<ref name=Stewart_060416>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Heather |title=London mayoral race is transformed as Sophie Walker raises profile of women |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2016/apr/06/london-mayor-race-transformed-sophie-walker-women |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=6 April 2016 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> (Walker in the [[2016 London mayoral election|Mayoral election]], plus candidates for the [[2016 London Assembly election#List candidates|London Assembly]]);<ref name=\"Diversity\">{{cite web |last=Diversity UK Editor |title=Sophie Walker is WE candidate for London Mayor |url=http://diversityuk.org/sophie-walker-is-we-candidate-for-london-mayor/ |website=diversityuk.org |publisher=Diversity UK |date=3 February 2016 |accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> [[2016 Scottish Parliament election|Scottish Parliament election]], [[Glasgow (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Glasgow region]] (Anne Beetham, Susan Mackay, Ruth Wilkinson, Calum Shepherd, Penelope Haddrill, Carol Young)<ref>{{cite web |last=Campaigns |title=Women's Equality Party's Scottish manifesto out |url=http://www.womensviewsonnews.org/2016/04/womens-equality-partys-scottish-manifesto-out/ |website=womensviewsonnews.org |publisher=Women's Views on News |date=6 April 2016 |access-date=23 April 2016}}</ref> and [[Lothian (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Lothian region]] (Lee Chalmers, Jennifer Royston, Catriona MacDonald and Abigail Herrmann);<ref name=\"EEN_010416\">{{cite news |last=Staff writer |title=Edinburgh's parliament election candidates named |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/politics/edinburgh-s-parliament-election-candidates-named-1-4088458 |work=[[Edinburgh Evening News]] |publisher=[[Johnston Press]] |date=1 April 2016 |access-date=23 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Staff writer |title=Women's Equality Party adds two Scottish Parliament candidates to May election lineup |url=http://www.wearethecity.com/news-womens-equality-party-adds-two-scottish-parliament-candidates-to-may-election-lineup/ |website=wearethecity.com |publisher= WeAreTheCity |date=2 February 2016 |accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> and the [[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|Welsh Assembly election]] in [[South Wales Central (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|South Wales Central]] (Sharon Lovell, Emma Rose, Sarah Rees and Ruth Williams).<ref name=\"Diversity\" /><ref name=\"Walesonline_110416\">{{cite news |last=Mosalski |first=Ruth |title=The four women standing for the Women's Equality Party in the National Assembly election |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/four-women-standing-womens-equality-11169873 |work=[[Media Wales#WalesOnline|WalesOnline]] |publisher=[[Media Wales]] |date=11 April 2016 |access-date=23 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nSupporters of the WEP's election bid included: [[Emma Thompson]],<ref name=\"G_Letters\">{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Emma |author-link=Emma Thompson |title=Letters: Emma Thompson 'I do not want to die before closing the pay gap' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/02/emma-thompson-i-do-not-want-to-die-before-closing-the-pay-gap |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=2 May 2016 |accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_020516\">{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Heather |title=Emma Thompson backs Women's Equality party for mayoral election |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/may/02/emma-thompson-womens-equality-party-mayoral-election |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=2 May 2016 |accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref> [[Lily Allen]], [[Hugh Quarshie]], [[Tanya Moodie]], [[Philippa Perry]], [[Jack Monroe]],<ref name=Half>{{cite AV media |people=Catherine Mayer, Lily Allen, Ninotchka, Hugh Quarshie, Stella Duffy, Tanya Moodie, Philippa Perry, Jack Monroe and Leila Bertrand |date=27 April 2016 |accessdate=28 April 2016 |title=Give half your votes to equality on 5 May \u2013 WE think that's fair #VoteWE |medium=Video |publisher=Women's Equality Channel via YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0n-6pT0_uso}}</ref> [[Jo Brand]], [[Rosie Boycott]]<ref name=5x15_JBRB>{{cite AV media |people=Catherine Mayer (host), [[Jo Brand]] (guest) and [[Rosie Boycott]] (guest) |date=3 April 2016 |accessdate=28 April 2016 |title=Jo Brand & Rosie Boycott @ 5x15 \u2013 Women's Equality Party |medium=Video |publisher=5x15 Stories via YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G7nFW9YmW_M}}</ref> and [[Caitlin Moran]].<ref name=5x15_CM>{{cite AV media |people=[[Caitlin Moran]] |date=3 April 2016 |accessdate=28 April 2016 |title=Caitlin Moran @ 5x15 \u2013 Women's Equality Party |medium=Video |publisher=5x15 Stories via YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v2VDrDQLbxA}}</ref>\n\nThe WEP did not win any seats in the elections: Walker gained 53,055 votes (2.04%) in the first round of voting for [[2016 London mayoral election#Results|London mayor]].<ref name=Telegraph_070516>{{cite news |last1=Akkoc |first1=Raziye |last2=Riley-Smith |first2=Ben |last3=Wilkinson |first3=Michael |title=London mayor election results: Sadiq Khan 'proud London has chosen hope over fear' as he wins landslide (12.50am Full results and figures) |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/06/london-mayoral-election-results-what-time-will-the-votes-be-coun/ |work=The Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=7 May 2016 |accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> The party's best result was on the [[2016 London Assembly election#List candidates|London-wide list]] where it finished sixth with 91,772 votes (3.5%).<ref name=GLA_060516>{{cite book |last=London Elects |author-link=London Elects |title=2016 GLA elections: election of the London Assembly members |url=https://www.londonelects.org.uk/sites/default/files/London-wide%20Assembly%20Member%20results%202016.pdf |publisher=[[London Elects]] |date=7 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAnne Beetham gained 2,091 votes (0.8%) in [[Glasgow (Scottish Parliament electoral region)#Additional member results|Glasgow]]<ref name=BBCGlasgowElect_2016>{{cite news |title=Scotland election 2016: Glasgow results |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/scotland-regions/S17000010 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> and Lee Chalmers gained 3,877 votes (1.2%) in [[Lothian (Scottish Parliament electoral region)#Additional member results|Lothian]].<ref name=BBCLothianElect_2016>{{cite news |title=Scotland election 2016: Lothian results |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/scotland-regions/S17000012 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=Scotland_2016>{{cite web |title=Our results from Scotland |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/our_results_from_scotland |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> Overall the WEP obtained 5,968 votes, 0.3% of the Scottish vote.<ref name=BBCScotElect_2016>{{cite news |title=Scotland election 2016: results |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2016/scotland/results |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nSharon Lovell, Emma Rose, Sarah Rees and Ruth Williams gained 2,807 votes, 1.2% of the total vote in [[South Wales Central (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|South Wales Central]].<ref name=Wales_2016>{{cite web |title=Our results from Wales |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/our_results_from_wales |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=BBCWalesElect_2016>{{cite news |title=Wales election 2016: South Wales Central |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/wales-regions/W10000007 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe overall total number of votes cast for the party in Scotland, Wales and London was 350,000.<ref name=Independent_070516>{{cite news |last1=Cooper |first1=Charlie |last2=Forster |first2=Katie |title=Women's Equality Party gets more than 350,000 votes and beats George Galloway in London |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/womens-equality-party-350000-votes-george-galloway-london-council-elections-a7018451.html |work=The Independent |date=7 May 2016 |accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 ===\nTabitha Morton from [[Netherton, Merseyside|Netherton]] stood in the [[2017 Liverpool City Region mayoral election|Liverpool City Region mayoral election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet your candidate: Tabitha Morton |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/tabitha_morton |website=womensequality.org.uk |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=20 February 2017 |accessdate=20 March 2017}}<br />- {{cite news |last=Perraudin |first=Frances |title=The mayoral candidate fighting for women in the northern powerhouse: 'We need a better deal' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/shortcuts/2017/mar/13/mayor-northern-powerhouse-womens-equality-party-tabitha-morton-liverpool |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=13 March 2017 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> She came seventh, receiving 4,287 first round votes (1.5%).<ref>Liverpool City Region Combined Authority: [http://liverpoolcityregionelects.org/results/ Results]. Retrieved 29 May 2017.</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] the party stood seven candidates. None were elected, and all lost their deposits. The best result among them was by Sophie Walker coming fourth in [[Shipley (UK Parliament constituency)|Shipley]] against the sitting [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP [[Philip Davies]], a men's rights and anti-political correctness campaigner.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39683982 |title=General election 2017: Women's Equality Party leader to challenge MP Philip Davies |publisher=BBC News |date=23 April 2017 |accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> The party targeted Davies's seat because of his role in blocking legislation that would have implemented better support for domestic violence victims, and because of his public comments about women, people with disabilities and LGBT people. Academics Emily Harmer and Rosalynd Southern write that: \"Targeting Davies was controversial due to fears over potential vote-splitting and the fact that the WEP failed to engage with local feminist groups\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=More Stable than Strong: Women's Representation, Voters and Issues|first1=Emily|last1=Harmer|first2=Rosalynd|last2=Southern|journal=Parliamentary Affairs|year=2018|volume=71|issue=s1|pages=237\u2013254|doi=10.1093/pa/gsx072}}</ref> The full list of WEP candidates in the 2017 general election is below:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Constituency\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! %\n! Source(s)\n|-\n| [[Hornsey and Wood Green (UK Parliament constituency)|Hornsey and Wood Green]]\n| [[Nimco Ali]]\n| 551\n| 0.9\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000752 |title=Hornsey & Wood Green |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Manchester Withington (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Withington]]\n| Sally Carr\n| 234\n| 0.4\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000809 |title=Manchester Withington |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Shipley (UK Parliament constituency)|Shipley]]\n| [[Sophie Walker]]\n| 1,040\n| 1.9\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000925|title=Shipley |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Stirling (UK Parliament constituency)|Stirling]]\n| Kirstein Rummery\n| 337\n| 0.7\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/S14000057 |title=Stirling |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tunbridge Wells (UK Parliament constituency)|Tunbridge Wells]]\n| Celine Thomas\n| 702\n| 1.3\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001004 |title=Tunbridge Wells |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Vale of Glamorgan (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of Glamorgan]]\n| Sharon Lovell\n| 177\n| 0.3\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/W07000078 |title=Vale of Glamorgan |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Vauxhall (UK Parliament constituency)|Vauxhall]]\n| Harini Iyengar\n| 539\n| 1.0\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001008 |title=Vauxhall |work=Election 2017 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== 2018 ===\nThe party put up candidates in more than 30 elections in the [[2018 United Kingdom local elections|local elections of 2018]].{{ref|Timeline1|Note 1}}<ref name=\"Local_2018\">{{cite web |title=Local election results: WE candidates on the march |url=http://www.womensequality.org.uk/local_election_18 |website=womensequality.org.uk |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=4 May 2018 |access-date=17 May 2018}}</ref> None were elected.\n\nMandu Reid stood as a candidate for the WEP in the [[2018 Lewisham East by-election]]; she came fifth out of the 14 candidates, receiving 506 votes (2.3%).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lewisham East constituency by-election on 14 June 2018 |url=https://www.lewisham.gov.uk/mayorandcouncil/elections/results/Pages/Lewisham-East-by-election-results-2018.aspx |publisher=[[Lewisham London Borough Council]] |date=14 June 2018 |access-date=25 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 ===\nThe party put up candidates in more than 20 elections in the [[2019 United Kingdom local elections|local elections of 2019]].{{ref|Timeline2|Note 2}} The party saw its first Councillor, Kay Wesley, elected to [[Congleton Town Council]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Equality Party elects its first Councillor|url=https://www.womensequality.org.uk/local_election_19 |publisher=Women's Equality Party |date=2 May 2019 |access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref> 33% of Congleton East voters gave one of their votes to the sole Women's Equality Party candidate, which got 1250 votes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Congleton Town Council East Ward Results 2019|url=https://www.cheshireeast.gov.uk/council_and_democracy/voting_and_elections/elections/parish-council-election-2019/calveley-to-faddiley/congleton-east.aspx |publisher=[[Cheshire East Council]] |date=2 May 2019 |access-date=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Constituency\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! %\n! Source(s)\n|-\n| [[Bury South (UK Parliament constituency)|Bury South]]\n| Gemma Evans\n| 130\n| 0.3\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000612|title=Bury South parliamentary election|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Luton North (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton North]]\n| Serena Laidley\n| 149\n| 0.3\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000800|title=Luton North parliamentary election|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Dover (UK Parliament constituency)|Dover]]\n| Eljai Morais\n| 137\n| 0.3\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000670|title=Dover parliamentary election|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\nThese constituencies have previously had an [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] suspended from his respective party because of allegations of sexual assault or harassment, although all three MPs that had been accused will not be seeking re-election. Two prospective candidates in [[Sheffield Hallam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Hallam]] and the [[Cities of London and Westminster (UK Parliament constituency)|Cities of London and Westminster]] stood aside to support the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] after they agreed to implement a WEP Policy to eject MPs guilty of harassment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/12/womens-equality-party-stands-aside-for-lib-dems-in-two-seats|title=Women's Equality party stands aside for Lib Dems in two seats|last=Quinn|first=Ben|date=12 November 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=30 November 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 ===\nIn January 2020, Mandu Reid was announced as the party leader following her role as interim leader since early 2019. The party are currently standing 26 candidates in the [[2020 London Assembly election]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womensequality.org.uk/gla_2020_candidates|title=GLA 2020 Candidates - Women's Equality Party|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> elections which is set to take place on 7 May 2020. Reid is the party's candidate for the [[2020 London mayoral election]], having replaced Sue Black, who had to withdraw for health reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/16/womens-equality-party-candidate-pulls-out-of-london-mayoral-race|title=Women's Equality party candidate pulls out of London mayoral race|first=Kate|last=Proctor|work=The Guardian|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Membership and local organisations==\nReportedly, 1,300 people joined the party on the day that it opened up membership, which costs \u00a34 per month.<ref name=Cohen/> In the first financial year, the party raised \u00a3512,219 in membership fees.<ref name=Accounts_2015>{{cite book |last=Da Soller |first=Samantha |title=Women's Equality Party Limited Annual Report and Financial Statements for the period ended 31 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404133854/http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/Api/Accounts/Documents/18498 |archive-date=4 April 2017 |url=http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/Api/Accounts/Documents/18498 |publisher=[[Electoral Commission]] |date=7 June 2016}}</ref> {{As of|2015|10|13}}, 65 local and regional Women's Equality Party groups had been founded,<ref name=Guardian_131015 /> and {{as of|2016|07|lc=y}} the party reported that it had 65,000 members.<ref name=Newsweek_290716>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Sophie |author-link= |title=How to solve the Labour Party's women problem |url=http://europe.newsweek.com/when-misogyny-becomes-mass-ogyny-485295 |work=[[Newsweek|Newsweek Europe]] |publisher=[[IBT Media]] |date=29 July 2016 |accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_130317\">{{cite news |last=Perraudin |first=Frances |title=The mayoral candidate fighting for women in the northern powerhouse: 'We need a better deal' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/shortcuts/2017/mar/13/mayor-northern-powerhouse-womens-equality-party-tabitha-morton-liverpool |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=13 March 2017 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> The WEP was described as \"the fastest growing political force in the UK\" in a ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]'' article on the party's campaigning for the [[2016 London mayoral election|May 2016 London mayoral election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/nudity-cats-and-doorstep-politics-welcome-to-election-canvassing/ |title=Nudity, cats and doorstep politics: Welcome to election canvassing \u2013 Women's Equality Party style |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Claire |last=Cohen |date=5 May 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> The party's membership reportedly grew from 25,000 to 55,000 in the month following the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|European Union membership referendum]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Brexit as a scandal: gender and global trumpism |first1=Aida A. |last1=Hozi\u0107 |first2=Jacqui |last2=True |journal=Review of International Political Economy |volume=24 |issue=2 |pages=270\u2013287 |year=2017 |doi=10.1080/09692290.2017.1302491}}</ref>\n\n== Fundraising and donations ==\nThe party's first [[fundraiser]], held in front of 400 people, including businesswoman [[Martha Lane Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho|Martha Lane Fox]], took place at Conway Hall on 9 June 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Staff writer |title=Londoner's Diary: Women are on the march with Sandi Toksvig |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/londoners-diary-women-are-on-the-march-with-sandi-toksvig-10310538.html |work=London Evening Standard |location=London |date=10 June 2015 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McLaren |first=Leah |author-link=Leah McLaren |title=Can a party for women, and by women, make it in Britain? |url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/worldpolitics/can-a-party-for-women-and-by-women-make-it-in-britain/ |work=[[Maclean's]] |publisher=[[Rogers Media|Rogers Media, Inc.]] |location=Canada |date=18 June 2015 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> In September that year Toksvig announced the dates for a comedy tour to raise funds for the party.<ref>{{cite news |last=Duffy |first=Nick |title=Sandi Toksvig launches comedy tour to raise funds for new political party |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/09/29/sandi-toksvig-launches-comedy-tour-to-raise-funds-for-new-political-party/ |work=[[PinkNews]] |publisher= |date=29 September 2015 |access-date=29 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=Times_290915>{{cite news |last=Nixey |first=Catherine |title=Sandi Toksvig on swapping The News Quiz for the Women's Equality Party |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/article4570067.ece |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=[[News UK]] |url-access=subscription |date=29 September 2015 |access-date=29 September 2015}}</ref> In the party's first year (ending 31 December 2015) \u00a3512,219 was raised through membership fees, \u00a338,528 through fundraising activities and \u00a379,212 was raised through donations.<ref name=Accounts_2015 />\n\nThe artist [[Damien Hirst]] created a piece of work for auction entitled \"Spin Drawing for Women's Equality\" (2015).<ref name=Art_160316>{{cite news |last=Gerlis |first=Melanie |title=Damien Hirst, suffragette, spins with a twist |url=http://theartnewspaper.com/news/damien-hirst-suffragette-spins-with-a-twist/ |work=[[The Art Newspaper]] |publisher=Umberto Allemandi |date=16 March 2016}}</ref> The piece, which contained the party's colours, raised \u00a320,000 when it was auctioned in April 2016. The artists [[Jake and Dinos Chapman]] also began a campaign, stamping the words \"Womens Equality Party\" onto [[Two pence (British decimal coin)|2p coins]] and then returning them into circulation.<ref name=SunTelegraph_240416>{{cite news |last=Furness |first=Hannah |title=The male artists risking jail to revive Suffragettes' spirit |url=http://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-sunday-telegraph/20160424/281771333374824 |work=[[The Sunday Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=24 April 2016 |access-date=27 April 2016}}</ref> ([[Suffragette]]s had also defaced pennies.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC - A History of the World - Object: Suffragette-defaced penny |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/iVUVhaKVREWjsHrr9IoOOA |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>)\n\nIn the party's second year (ending 31 December 2016) \u00a3447,946 was raised through membership fees, \u00a335,918 through fundraising activities and \u00a3261,394 was raised through donations.<ref name=Accounts_2016>{{cite book |last=Keshet |first=Shendi |title=Women's Equality Party Limited Annual Report and Financial Statements for the period ended 31 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914100704/http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/Api/Accounts/Documents/19410 |archive-date=14 September 2017 |url=http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/Api/Accounts/Documents/19410 |publisher=[[Electoral Commission]] |date=1 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nA year prior to the creation of the WEP, Suzanne Moore suggested in ''[[The Guardian]]'' that a feminist party should be formed, saying: \"the false doctrine of austerity has meant that women, single mothers in particular, and public sector workers in general, have been at the frontline of this war. They have been demonised and subject to punitive cuts.\"<ref name=Moore_090714>{{cite news |last=Moore |first=Suzanne |author-link=Suzanne Moore |title=Harriet Harman is right about sexism in politics \u2013 let's start a feminist party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jul/09/harriet-harman-sexism-politics-feminist-party |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=9 July 2014 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> Writing in ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', Kate Maltby responded by saying, \"My feminism is directly tied to a commitment to meritocracy and individual flourishing...if her [Moore's] grand new feminist party kicks off by nationalising private property, I'm hardly going to be able to sign up\".<ref name=Maltby_110714>{{cite news |last=Maltby |first=Kate |title=Suzanne Moore, please don't ruin feminism by starting a feminist party |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/katemaltby/100279483/suzanne-moore-please-dont-ruin-feminism-by-starting-a-feminist-party/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716061143/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/katemaltby/100279483/suzanne-moore-please-dont-ruin-feminism-by-starting-a-feminist-party/ |archivedate=16 July 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=11 July 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe British edition of ''[[GQ]]'' has also accused the party of \"alienating 50 per cent of the electorate\", adding that, \"while the WEP may aim to appeal to both female Tory voters and female Labour voters, it doesn't take away from the implicit suggestion that the party \u2013 which aims for 'diverse' membership \u2013 is still aimed almost solely at women\".<ref name=Carr_190815>{{cite news |last=Carr |first=Flora |title=The Women's Equality Party is alienating men |url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/comment/articles/2015-08/19/womens-equality-party-alienating-men-sandy-toksvig |work=[[GQ]] (UK edition) |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |date=19 August 2015 |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> The party has also been criticised \"for being {{sic|comprised |hide=y|mainly of}} white, middle-class affluent women\".<ref>{{cite journal |first=Elizabeth |last=Evans |title=Intersectionality as feminist praxis in the UK |journal=[[Women's Studies International Forum]] |year=2016 |volume=59 |pages=67\u201375 |doi=10.1016/j.wsif.2016.10.004|url=http://research.gold.ac.uk/19038/1/October%20revised%20-%20Intersectionality%20as%20feminist%20praxis.doc }}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Union of Sex Workers]] have criticised the party stance on the criminalisation of commercial sex.<ref>https://www.iusw.org/2015/10/iusw-condemns-womens-equality-partys-harmful-choice-to-seek-criminalisation-of-commercial-sex/</ref>\n\nThe party has also been accused of being \"both too ambitious and not ambitious enough\", that, in order to maintain traction, it ought to concentrate on just one issue, e.g., quotas in the boardroom.<ref name=Guardian_211015b>{{cite news |last=Perkins |first=Anne |title=Two cheers for the Women's Equality party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/oct/21/womens-equality-party-politics |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=21 October 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral performance==\n\n===Westminster elections===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Year !! Candidates !! Total votes !! % of total vote !! Change !! Average vote<ref>Average vote per candidate.</ref> !! Average % vote !! Saved Deposits !! Number of MPs !! Change\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Women's Equality Party/meta/color}}\" |\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]\n|| 7 || 3,580 || 0.0% || ''n/a'' || 511 || 0.9% || 0 || 0 || {{nochange}} \n|}\n\n===London Mayoral elections===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Date\n!| Popular Vote\n!| % of Vote\n!| Change\n!| Place\n!| Notes\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Women's Equality Party/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[2016 London mayoral election|2016]] || 53,055 || 2.0% || 