n Shay, [[2018 Harrogate Borough Council election#Harrogate Stray|Stray ward]], Harrogate \u00b7 Amanda Shribman, [[2018 Barnet London Borough Council election#West Finchley|West Finchley ward]], Barnet \u00b7 Leisa Taylor, [[2018 Worcester City Council election#Bedwardine|Bedwardine ward]], Worcester \u00b7 Wendy Thomson, [[2018 Reading Borough Council election#Peppard|Peppard ward]], Reading \u00b7 Nikki Uppal, [[2018 Islington London Borough Council election#Hillrise|Hillrise ward]], Islington \u00b7 Kate Vang, [[2018 Lewisham London Borough Council election#Brockley|Brockley ward]], Lewisham</small>\n\n:{{note label|Timeline2|Note 2}}\n:* <small>Nicke Adebowale, [[Lewisham London Borough Council elections#2018-2022|Evelyn ward (by-election)]], Lewisham \u00b7 Hannah Barham-Brown, [[2019 Leeds City Council election#Roundhay|Roundhay ward]], Leeds \u00b7 Beverly Barstow, [[2019 Brighton and Hove City Council election#Hanover and Elm Grove|Hanover and Elm Grove ward]], Brighton and Hove \u00b7 Vinice Bridget Cowell, [[2019 Southend-on-Sea Borough Council election#Chalkwell|Chalkwell ward]], Southend-on-Sea \u00b7 Priya Brown, [[2019 Basingstoke and Deane Borough Council election#Eastrop|Eastrop ward]], Basingstoke and Deane \u00b7 Jen Bryan, [[Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council election, 2019#Heatons North|Heatons North ward]], Stockport \u00b7 Samantha Days, [[Manchester City Council election, 2019#Crumpsall|Crumpsall ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Sally Duffin, [[2019 City of York Council election#Heworth Ward|Heworth ward]], York \u00b7 Bea Gare, [[2019 Exeter City Council election#Duryard & St. James|Duryard & St. James ward]], Exeter \u00b7 Amy Gooding, [[Sheffield City Council election, 2019#Walkley|Walkley ward]], Sheffield \u00b7 Cairis Grant-Hickey, [[Lewisham London Borough Council elections#2018-2022|Whitefoot ward (by-election)]], Lewisham \u00b7 Jo Heathcote, [[Manchester City Council election, 2019#Chorlton|Chorlton ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Caroline Hunt, [[2019 Leeds City Council election#Headingley & Hyde Park|Headingley & Hyde Park ward]], Leeds \u00b7 Louise Jennings, [[Leeds City Council election, 2019#Alwoodley|Alwoodley ward]], Leeds \u00b7 Sam Johnson, [[Manchester City Council election, 2019#Deansgate|Deansgate ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Jessie MacNeil-Brown, [[2019 Brighton and Hove City Council election#Central Hove|Central Hove ward]], Brighton and Hove \u00b7 Liz Orr, [[Tunbridge Wells Borough Council election, 2019#Culverden|Culverden ward]], Tunbridge Wells \u00b7 Sarika Paul, [[Manchester City Council election, 2019#Didsbury West|Didsbury West ward]], Manchester \u00b7 Erika Raffle-Currie, [[2019 Liverpool City Council election#Childwall|Childwall ward]], Liverpool \u00b7 Kanndiss Riley, [[2019 Thanet District Council election#Cliftonville East|Cliftonville East ward]], Thanet \u00b7 Megan Senior, [[Sheffield City Council election, 2019#Ecclesall|Ecclesall ward]], Sheffield \u00b7 Leisa Taylor, [[Worcester City Council election, 2019#Bedwardine|Bedwardine ward]], Worcester \u00b7 Celine Thomas, [[Tunbridge Wells Borough Council election, 2019#Pantiles & St Mark's|Pantiles & St Mark's ward]], Tunbridge Wells \u00b7 Louise Timlin, [[2019 Wokingham Borough Council election#Ward results|Evendons ward]], Wokingham \u00b7 Kay Wesley, [[2019 Cheshire East Council election#Congleton East|Congleton East ward]], Cheshire East (and Kay Wesley, [[Congleton Town Council]]) \u00b7 Jane Whild, [[2019 Milton Keynes Council election#Ward Results|Campbell Park & Old Woughton ward]], Milton Keynes \u00b7 Annie Wood, [[2019 Salford City Council election#Eccles|Eccles ward]], Salford</small>\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite news |last=Beaty |first=Zoe |title=Hope: How to build a feminist political party |trans-title=''Online title'': Just who are the Women's Equality Party and what do they stand for? |url=http://www.stylist.co.uk/life/who-are-the-womens-equality-party-and-what-do-they-stand-for-policies-pay-parenting-education |work=[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]] |issue=310 |pages=26\u201327, 29\u201330 |publisher=Shortlist Media |date=23 March 2016}}\n*{{cite news |last=Cohen |first=Nick |author-link=Nick Cohen |title=Why the Women's Equality party is long overdue |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/sep/27/womens-equality-party-long-overdue |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=27 September 2015}}\n*{{cite journal|first1=Elizabeth|last1=Evans|first2=Meryl|last2=Kenny|title=The Women's Equality Party: Emergence, Organisation and Challenges|journal=Political Studies|year=2019|volume=67|issue=4|pages=855\u2013871|doi=10.1177/0032321718812885|url=https://research.gold.ac.uk/24750/1/Final%20Manuscript%20.doc}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n*{{Official website|http://www.womensequality.org.uk/}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/pages/The-Womens-Equality-Party/1567955710156124 Party-wide Facebook page]\n\n{{British political parties}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Women's Equality Party}}\n[[Category:2015 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Feminist parties in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Pro-European political parties in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "+link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_Equality_Party"}
{"title_page": "Lake Hule", "text_new": "{{short description|Lake in Costa Rica}}\n{{Infobox lake\n| name = Lake Hule\n| type = [[Volcanic crater lake|crater lake]]\n| image = Laguna de Hule.jpg\n| caption = \n| pushpin_map = Costa Rica\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Costa Rica\n| coordinates = {{coord|10.295278|N|84.208889|W|region:CR_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| area = {{convert|0.547|km2|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|1|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = {{convert|19.8|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|740|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}\n\n'''Lake Hule''' ({{lang-es|Laguna de Hule}}), which translates to ''Lake of Rubber'', due to the abundance of [[Castilla elastica|rubber trees]] nearby, it is a [[Fresh water|fresh water]] [[Volcanic crater lake|crater lake]] located in the northern highlands of [[Costa Rica]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Haberyan |first1=Kurt A. |title=Basic limnology of fifty-one lakes in Costa Rica |journal=SciELO |date=March 2003 |volume=51 |issue=1 |url=https://www.scielo.sa.cr/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0034-77442003000100009 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is part of a complex of lakes made of by Lake Hule, [[Lake Congo]] and [[Lake Bosque Alegre]]. \n\n== Location ==\n\nIt is located in Los \u00c1ngeles Sur, of [[R\u00edo Cuarto (canton)|R\u00edo Cuarto]] canton, of [[Alajuela Province|Alajuela]] province. \n\n== Physical aspects ==\n\nLake Hule is a [[maar]] lake located within a crater, it has an almost circular outline. There is no secondary volcanic activity present. <ref>{{cite web |title=Laguna R\u00edo Cuarto |url=https://rsn.ucr.ac.cr/rsn/doi/109-vulcanologia/volcanes-de-costa-rica-ii/19-laguna-rio-cuarto |website=RSN |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Social and economic uses ==\n\nIt is part of the Bosque Alegre Wildlife Refuge. \n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of lakes in Costa Rica]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Alajuela Province]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Alajuela Province]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Costa Rica|Hule]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox lake\n| name = Lake Hule\n| type = [[Volcanic crater lake|crater lake]]\n| image = Laguna de Hule.jpg\n| caption = \n| pushpin_map = Costa Rica\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Costa Rica\n| coordinates = {{coord|10.295278|N|84.208889|W|region:CR_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| area = {{convert|0.547|km2|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|1|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = {{convert|19.8|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|740|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}\n\n'''Lake Hule''' ({{lang-es|Laguna de Hule}}), which translates to ''Lake of Rubber'', due to the abundance of [[Castilla elastica|rubber trees]] nearby, it is a [[Fresh water|fresh water]] [[Volcanic crater lake|crater lake]] located in the northern highlands of [[Costa Rica]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Haberyan |first1=Kurt A. |title=Basic limnology of fifty-one lakes in Costa Rica |journal=SciELO |date=March 2003 |volume=51 |issue=1 |url=https://www.scielo.sa.cr/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0034-77442003000100009 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is part of a complex of lakes made of by Lake Hule, [[Lake Congo]] and [[Lake Bosque Alegre]]. \n\n== Location ==\n\nIt is located in Los \u00c1ngeles Sur, of [[R\u00edo Cuarto (canton)|R\u00edo Cuarto]] canton, of [[Alajuela Province|Alajuela]] province. \n\n== Physical aspects ==\n\nLake Hule is a [[maar]] lake located within a crater, it has an almost circular outline. There is no secondary volcanic activity present. <ref>{{cite web |title=Laguna R\u00edo Cuarto |url=https://rsn.ucr.ac.cr/rsn/doi/109-vulcanologia/volcanes-de-costa-rica-ii/19-laguna-rio-cuarto |website=RSN |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Social and economic uses ==\n\nIt is part of the Bosque Alegre Wildlife Refuge. \n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of lakes in Costa Rica]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Alajuela Province]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Alajuela Province]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Costa Rica|Hule]]\n", "name_user": "Roqz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Hule"}
{"title_page": "Sir Samuel Lennard, 3rd Baronet", "text_new": "'''Sir Samuel Lennard, 3rd Baronet''' (2 October 1672 \u2013 8 October 1727) of [[Wickham Court]], Bromley, Kent was a British army officer and politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1715 to 1727.\n\nLennard was the only son of [[Sir Stephen Lennard, 2nd Baronet]] of [[West Wickham]] and his wife  Elizabeth Hussey, daughter of Delalynd Hussey of Shapwick, Dorset. He was admitted at [[Middle Temple]] in 1689 and matriculated at [[Trinity College, Oxford]] on 4 April 1690.<ref name=ALUM>{{cite web |url = https://www.british-history.ac.uk/alumni-oxon/1500-1714/pp892-921 |title='Lee-Llewellin', in Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714, ed. Joseph Foster (Oxford, 1891), pp. 892-921   | author= Foster, Joseph |publisher= British History Online | accessdate = 8 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nLennard joined the army and was a Captain in the Earl of Denbigh's Dragoons from 1696 to 1697. He went onto  half-pay in 1698 and became a captain in Viscount Shannon's Regiment of Marines  in 1702 and a captain in the Life Guards in 1704. In 1709 he became aide-de-camp  to Prince George of Denmark and was guidon and major and then cornet and major.  He succeeded his father in the [[Lennard baronets|baronetcy]] on 15 December 1709. In 1713 he was lieutenant and lieutenant-colonel and in 1714 appointed groom of the bedchamber to the Prince of Wales, a post he held until 1717.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/lennard-sir-samuel-1672-1727| title=LENNARD, Sir Samuel, 3rd Bt. (1672-1727), of West Wickham, Kent. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 8 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1715 British general election|1715 general election]] Lennard was returned as Whig  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hythe (UK Parliament constituency)|Hythe]] on the interest of the Lord Warden. He was knighted for [[standing proxy]] for Prince Frederick at his installation as Knight of the Garter in April 1718. Also in 1718, he was made Captain of [[Sandgate Castle]], a position he held until death. He was elected again as MP for Hythe at the  [[1722 British general election|1722 general election]] and at the [[1727 British general election|1727 general election]].<ref name=HOP/>\n\nLennard died shortly after the last election on 8 October 1727. He was unmarried, but had two illegitimate daughters. The baronetcy became extinct on his death.<ref name=HOP/> His alleged illegitimate son Samuel was born by Mary Johnson at Maskell's house in Great Ormond Street, London on 10 September 1720.<ref name=CoE>[https://www.ancestry.com/interactive/1624/31281_a100931-00061/155057106? London, England, Church of England Baptisms, Marriages and Burials, 1538-1812: Camden \u2013 St Andrew, Holborn]; accessed via Ancestry.com paid subscription site, February 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Jacob des Bouverie]]\n | before2 = [[John Boteler (died 1746)|John Boteler]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n| title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hythe (UK Parliament constituency)|Hythe]]\n| years = [[1715 British general election|1715]] \u2013 1727  \n | with  =  [[Jacob des Bouverie]]\n   | with2  =  [[Hercules Baker|Captain Hercules Baker]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Hercules Baker|Captain Hercules Baker]]\n | after2 = [[William Glanville (Hythe MP)|William Glanville]]\n}}\n{{S-reg|en-bt}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[Sir Stephen Lennard, 2nd Baronet]]}}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Lennard baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of  West Wickham) | years=1709-1727''' }}\n{{s-aft | after = Extinct}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lennard, Sir Samuel, 3rd Baronet}}\n[[Category:1672 births]]\n[[Category:1727 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Members of the Middle Temple]]\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1715\u20131722]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1722\u20131727]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir Samuel Lennard, 3rd Baronet''' (2 October 1672 \u2013 8 October 1727) of [[Wickham Court]], Bromley, Kent was a British army officer and politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1715 to 1727.\n\nLennard was the only son of [[Sir Stephen Lennard, 2nd Baronet]] of [[West Wickham]] and his wife  Elizabeth Hussey, daughter of Delalynd Hussey of Shapwick, Dorset. He was admitted at [[Middle Temple]] in 1689 and matriculated at [[Trinity College, Oxford]] on 4 April 1690.<ref name=ALUM>{{cite web |url = https://www.british-history.ac.uk/alumni-oxon/1500-1714/pp892-921 |title='Lee-Llewellin', in Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714, ed. Joseph Foster (Oxford, 1891), pp. 892-921   | author= Foster, Joseph |publisher= British History Online | accessdate = 8 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nLennard joined the army and was a Captain in the Earl of Denbigh\u2019s Dragoons from 1696 to 1697. He went onto  half-pay in 1698 and became a captain in Viscount Shannon\u2019s Regiment of Marines  in 1702 and a captain in the Life Guards in 1704. In 1709 he became aide-de-camp  to Prince George of Denmark and was guidon and major and then cornet and major.  He succeeded his father in the [[Lennard baronets|baronetcy]] on 15 December 1709. In 1713 he was lieutenant and lieutenant-colonel and in 1714 appointed groom of the bedchamber to the Prince of Wales, a post he held until 1717.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/lennard-sir-samuel-1672-1727| title=LENNARD, Sir Samuel, 3rd Bt. (1672-1727), of West Wickham, Kent. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 8 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1715 British general election|1715 general election]] Lennard was returned as Whig  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hythe (UK Parliament constituency)|Hythe]] on the interest of the Lord Warden. He was knighted for [[standing proxy]] for Prince Frederick at his installation as Knight of the Garter in April 1718. Also in 1718, he was made Captain of [[Sandgate Castle]], a position he held until death. He was elected again as MP for Hythe at the  [[1722 British general election|1722 general election]] and at the [[1727 British general election|1727 general election]].<ref name=HOP/>\n\nLennard died shortly after the last election on 8 October 1727. He was unmarried, but had two illegitimate daughters. The baronetcy became extinct on his death.<ref name=HOP/> His alleged illegitimate son Samuel was born by Mary Johnson at Maskell's house in Great Ormond Street, London on 10 September 1720.<ref name=CoE>[https://www.ancestry.com/interactive/1624/31281_a100931-00061/155057106? London, England, Church of England Baptisms, Marriages and Burials, 1538-1812: Camden \u2013 St Andrew, Holborn]; accessed via Ancestry.com paid subscription site, February 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Jacob des Bouverie]]\n | before2 = [[John Boteler (died 1746)|John Boteler]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n| title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hythe (UK Parliament constituency)|Hythe]]\n| years = [[1715 British general election|1715]] \u2013 1727  \n | with  =  [[Jacob des Bouverie]]\n   | with2  =  [[Hercules Baker|Captain Hercules Baker]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Hercules Baker|Captain Hercules Baker]]\n | after2 = [[William Glanville (Hythe MP)|William Glanville]]\n}}\n{{S-reg|en-bt}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[Sir Stephen Lennard, 2nd Baronet]]}}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Lennard baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of  West Wickham) | years=1709-1727''' }}\n{{s-aft | after = Extinct}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lennard, Sir Samuel, 3rd Baronet}}\n[[Category:1672 births]]\n[[Category:1727 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of T